(1, 1, 'Hypertension', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Hypertension (High Blood Pressure): </h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Signs and More Many times, high blood pressure has little or no symptoms. Unaware of it, many individuals have it for years. Study more.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Examples of Primary, Secondary, and Other Types of Hypertension</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Other kinds of hypertension entail controlling the causes and symptoms of high blood pressure in addition to primary and secondary hypertension. Here, we discuss the many forms and phases of hypertension.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Thoracic hypertension Life expectancy, prospects, and therapies</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">A condition that advances swiftly is pulmonary hypertension. Learn more about the effects of this type of high blood pressure on life expectancy, therapies, and other topics.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The heart and lungs are both affected by the uncommon, progressive condition known as pulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH). Study up on PAH here.</p>', 'Hypertension.png'),
(2, 1, 'Heart failure', '<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Angina, Treatment Options, and Other Coronary Artery Disease Symptoms</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Your heart receives less blood when you have coronary artery disease. Discover the signs of coronary artery disease, how to treat them, and other information.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Risks for coronary artery disease</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">For both men and women, heart disease is the leading cause of mortality. Find out more about the several variables that might make you more likely to develop CAD.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Epicardial Adipose Tissue:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">A Coronary Artery Disease Predictor Fat called epicardial adipose tissue (EAT) lies between your heart&#39;s muscle and outer layers. Overeating might be a sign of heart disease.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Doctors may refer to your condition as if there is significant plaque accumulation in your coronary arteries</p>', 'Heart failure.png '),
(3, 1, 'Arrhythmia', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Ventricular Arrhythmia:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">A ventricular arrhythmia is an irregular heartbeat that originates in the lower chambers of the heart. It may result in symptoms including dizziness, racing heart, and weakness.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms of an Arrhythmia:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abnormal or irregular heartbeats are known as arrhythmias. They happen when your heart\'s electrical impulses misalign with the regular beat.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Reperfusion Arrhythmia:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">An irregular heartbeat known as reperfusion arrhythmia (RA) can develop after a blocked artery has its blood flow restored. If you have RA, be prepared for the following.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Detecting and Preventing Arrhythmia:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Find out the signs and symptoms of arrhythmias as well as potential treatments and prevention measures.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Magnesium and Ventricular Arrhythmias:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">A Connection You may be wondering if magnesium is effective in maintaining healthy heart rhythms because it</p>', 'Arrhythmia.png'),
(4, 1, 'Atherosclerosis', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Atherosclerosis:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Regular Sleeping Patterns May Increase Risk of Atherosclerosis<br /> According to research, adults over 45 who have irregular sleeping habits may be more susceptible to atherosclerosis.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Is it possible to reverse atherosclerosis?:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Although atherosclerosis cannot be reversed, it can be slowed down by lifestyle modifications. At What Age Does Atherosclerosis Start  The life-threatening side effects of atherosclerosis (hardening of the arteries) typically don&#39;t manifest until middle age. Others may experience the onset of atherosclerosis in their 20s or 30s, or even as early as 10 years old. Continue reading to discover more about the signs and signs of atherosclerosis. 15 Foods That May Aid in Preventing Arterial Blockages Atherosclerosis is sometimes referred to as artery hardening or artery blockage. In this article, 15</p>', 'Atherosclerosis.png'),
(5, 1, 'Myocardial infarction', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Myocardial infarction:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Myocardial infarction, commonly known as a heart attack, is a serious medical condition that occurs when the blood flow to the heart muscle is significantly reduced or completely blocked. This reduction or blockage of blood flow prevents the heart muscle from receiving adequate oxygen and nutrients, leading to damage or death of the heart tissue.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Here is a comprehensive description of myocardial infarction:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Causes and Risk Factors: Myocardial infarction is primarily caused by the formation of a blood clot (thrombus) that blocks one or more coronary arteries, which supply blood to the heart muscle. The formation of a blood clot is often a result of the buildup of fatty deposits (plaques) in the arteries, a condition known as atherosclerosis. Several risk factors contribute to the development of atherosclerosis and the risk of experiencing a heart attack. These includ</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Age:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The risk of myocardial infarction increases with age, particularly after the age of 45 for men and 55 for women.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">High blood pressure</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Uncontrolled high blood pressure puts added strain on the arteries and increases the risk of heart disease.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">High cholesterol:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Elevated levels of LDL (low-density lipoprotein) cholesterol, often referred to as &quot;bad&quot; cholesterol, can contribute to the development of plaque buildup.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The symptoms of a heart attack can vary from person to person, and some individuals may experience no symptoms at all, which is known as a silent heart attack. However, common symptoms of myocardial infarction include:</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Chest pain or discomfort:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">his is often described as a feeling of pressure, tightness, heaviness, or squeezing in the chest that may radiate to the arms, shoulders, jaw, or back.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Electrocardiogram (ECG):</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">This test measures the electrical activity of the heart and can detect abnormal rhythms or changes associated with a heart attack.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Blood tests:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blood samples can be analyzed to measure cardiac enzymes and proteins released into the blood following heart muscle damage.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Imaging tests:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Tests such as echocardiography, cardiac MRI, or coronary angiography may be performed to assess the extent of heart damage, identify blockages, or evaluate heart function.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Prompt treatment is crucial during a heart attack to minimize damage to the</p>', 'Myocardial infarction.png'),
(6, 1, 'Coronary artery disease', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Coronary artery disease</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Heart disease refers to a range of conditions that affect the heart&#39;s ability to function properly. Some common types of heart disease include coronary artery disease, heart attack, heart failure, and arrhythmias.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Symptoms of heart disease can vary depending on the specific type and severity of the condition. Some common symptoms include:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chest pain or discomfort, which may feel like a pressure or squeezing sensation</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Shortness of breath, especially during physical activity or when lying down</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Swelling in the feet, ankles, or legs</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Light headedness or fainting</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">There are several types of heart disease, each with its own set of symptoms. Here is a brief overview of some common types of heart disease:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Atrial fibrillation - This is a type of arrhythmia (irregular heartbeat) that can lead to blood clots and stroke. Symptoms may include palpitations (a feeling of rapid or irregular heartbeats), shortness of breath, and dizziness.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Aortic aneurysms are typically diagnosed through various imaging techniques, including:</p>', 'Coronary artery disease.png'),
(7, 1, 'Aortic aneurysm', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Aortic aneurysm</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">An aortic aneurysm refers to a condition characterized by a weakened and bulging section in the wall of the aorta, which is the largest artery in the body responsible for carrying oxygen-rich blood from the heart to the rest of the body. The aorta runs through the chest (thoracic aorta) and abdomen (abdominal aorta). An aneurysm can occur in either location and is typically classified based on its location and size.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Types of Aortic Aneurysms:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Thoracic Aortic Aneurysm (TAA): This type of aneurysm occurs in the thoracic portion of the aorta, which is located in the chest cavity. TAAs are further classified into two types: a. Ascending Aortic Aneurysm: Located in the section of the aorta that is closest to the heart. b. Descending Aortic Aneurysm: Located in the section of the aorta that extends through the chest and towards the abdomen</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Abdominal Aortic Aneurysm (AAA):</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">This type of aneurysm occurs in the abdominal portion of the aorta, which extends from the chest down to the abdomen.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Aortic aneurysms can be caused by various factors, including:</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Atherosclerosis:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The buildup of fatty deposits and plaque in the arteries, which weakens the arterial walls.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Genetic factors:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Certain genetic conditions can predispose individuals to develop aortic aneurysms.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Connective tissue disorders:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Conditions such as Marfan syndrome and Ehlers-Danlos syndrome, which affect the strength and integrity of connective tissues.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Infections:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">In rare cases, infections such as syphilis or mycotic infections can weaken the aortic wall and lead to an aneurysm.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Aortic aneurysms often do not cause symptoms until they reach a large size or rupture. When symptoms do occur, they may include:</p>\n<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Other signs:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Shortness of breath, hoarseness, coughing, difficulty swallowing, or symptoms of shock in case of rupture.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Ultrasound:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">A non-invasive test that uses sound waves to create images of the aorta.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The treatment of aortic aneurysms depends on several factors, including the size, location, and overall health of the individual. Options include:</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Medications:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Certain medications may be prescribed to manage risk factors such as high blood pressure and cholesterol.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Surgery:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Depending on the size and location of the aneurysm, surgical repair may be necessary to prevent rupture. Procedures may include open surgical repair or endovascular repair using stent grafts.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It&#39;s important to note that aortic aneurysms can be life-threatening if they rupture. If you suspect you have an aortic aneurysm or are experiencing severe symptoms, it is crucial to seek immediate medical attention.</p>', 'Aortic aneurysm.png'),
(8, 1, 'Angina', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Angina</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Angina, also known as angina pectoris, is a common symptom of coronary artery disease (CAD). It is characterized by recurring chest pain or discomfort that occurs when the heart muscle does not receive enough blood and oxygen. Angina is typically caused by the narrowing or blockage of the coronary arteries, which supply blood to the heart muscle.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Types of Angina:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Stable Angina: This is the most common type of angina. It occurs predictably and is triggered by physical exertion, emotional stress, or other activities that increase the heart&#39;s demand for oxygen. The pain or discomfort is usually relieved by rest or nitroglycerin medication.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Unstable Angina:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Unstable angina is more serious and occurs at rest or with minimal exertion. It may be an early sign of a heart attack and requires immediate medical attention. The pain or discomfort may be more severe and prolonged compared to stable angina, and it is not easily relieved by rest or nitroglycerin.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Variant Angina (Prinzmetal&#39;s Angina): This type of angina is caused by a spasm in the coronary arteries, leading to a temporary narrowing of the blood vessels. It can occur at rest and may be unrelated to physical exertion or emotional stress. Variant angina is usually relieved by medications that relax and widen the coronary arteries.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Angina typically presents as chest pain or discomfort, which can be described as:</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Fatigue or weakness:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It&#39;s important to note that symptoms of angina can vary between individuals, and some people may experience atypical symptoms such as shortness of breath without chest pain.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">To diagnose angina, a healthcare professional will perform a thorough evaluation, including:</p>\n<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Electrocardiogram (ECG):</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Records the electrical activity of the heart and can detect abnormal heart rhythms and signs of decreased blood flow to the heart.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Exercise stress test:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Monitoring the heart&#39;s activity during physical exercise to evaluate how it responds to stress.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Coronary angiography:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Injecting a contrast dye into the coronary arteries and taking X-ray images to assess the presence and severity of blockages.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Coronary Artery Bypass Grafting (CABG):</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">A surgical procedure that reroutes blood flow around blocked or narrowed coronary arteries using blood vessels from other parts of the body.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It&#39;s essential for individuals with angina to work closely with their healthcare providers to manage their condition effectively, reduce symptoms, and lower the risk of complications such as heart attack or heart failure.</p>', 'Angina.png'),
(9, 1, 'Peripheral arterial disease', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Peripheral arterial disease:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Peripheral arterial disease (PAD), also known as peripheral vascular disease, is a condition characterized by the narrowing or blockage of the arteries that supply blood to the extremities, most commonly the legs. It is caused by atherosclerosis, a condition in which fatty deposits called plaque build up in the artery walls, leading to reduced blood flow.</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes and Risk Factors:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The primary cause of peripheral arterial disease is atherosclerosis, which occurs when plaque accumulates in the arteries. Several factors can contribute to the development of PAD, including:</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Smoking:</h3><0 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Cigarette smoking significantly increases the risk of PAD.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diabetes:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> People with diabetes have a higher likelihood of developing PAD due to associated damage to blood vessels.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">High blood pressure:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Hypertension can contribute to the development and progression of PAD.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">High cholesterol:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Elevated levels of LDL (bad) cholesterol and reduced levels of HDL (good) cholesterol can contribute to plaque formation.</p> 	<ul><li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Age and gender: PAD is more common in individuals over 50, and men tend to have a higher risk compared to women.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Obesity: Excess body weight puts additional strain on the circulatory system.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Family history: Having a close relative with PAD increases the risk.</li> </ul><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The symptoms of peripheral arterial disease may vary depending on the severity and location of the blockage. Common symptoms include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Leg pain: Cramping, aching, or fatigue in the legs, particularly during physical activity (intermittent claudication).</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Numbness or weakness: Reduced sensation or muscle strength in the legs.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cold feet: Decreased temperature in the lower extremities.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Non-healing sores or wounds: Difficulty in healing wounds or ulcers on the feet or legs.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Changes in skin color: Pale or bluish skin discoloration.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Poor nail and hair growth on the affected limb.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Erectile dysfunction: Men with PAD may experience difficulties with erectile function.</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Diagnosis: To diagnose peripheral arterial disease, healthcare providers may perform the following tests:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Ankle-brachial index (ABI): Measures blood pressure at the ankle and compares it to the pressure in the arm to assess blood flow.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Doppler ultrasound: Uses sound waves to evaluate blood flow in the arteries and detect blockages.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Angiography: Invasive imaging technique that uses contrast dye and X-rays to visualize blood flow and identify narrowed or blocked arteries.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Magnetic resonance angiography (MRA) or computed tomography angiography (CTA): Non-invasive imaging techniques that provide detailed images of blood vessels.</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Treatment: The treatment of peripheral arterial disease aims to relieve symptoms, slow disease progression, and reduce the risk of complications. Treatment options may include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lifestyle modifications: Quitting smoking, adopting a healthy diet low in saturated fats and high in fruits and vegetables, regular exercise, and managing other risk factors such as diabetes, high blood pressure, and high cholesterol.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Prescribed medications may include antiplatelet agents (such as aspirin or clopidogrel) to reduce the risk of blood clots, cholesterol-lowering drugs (statins), and medications to manage blood pressure or improve blood flow.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Angioplasty and stenting: A minimally invasive procedure to open blocked or narrowed arteries using a balloon-like device to widen the artery and a stent to help keep it open.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bypass surgery: In cases of severe blockages, a surgical procedure may be performed to create a bypass around the blocked artery, allowing blood to flow through a different route.</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Early diagnosis and management of peripheral arterial disease are crucial to prevent complications such as non-healing wounds, infections, and in severe cases, limb amputation. Regular follow-up with a healthcare provider is essential to</p>  <p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Peripheral arterial disease.png'),
(10, 1, 'Stroke', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Stroke:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Stroke, also known as cerebrovascular accident (CVA), is a medical condition that occurs when the blood supply to a part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, leading to the rapid loss of brain function. It is a medical emergency and requires immediate medical attention to minimize brain damage and prevent potential complications.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Here is a comprehensive description of stroke:</p>  <p>Types of Stroke:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Ischemic Stroke: This is the most common type of stroke, accounting for approximately 85% of cases. It occurs when a blood clot (thrombus) forms in an artery supplying blood to the brain or when a clot from another part of the body travels to the brain (embolism), blocking the blood flow.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hemorrhagic Stroke: This type of stroke occurs when a weakened blood vessel in the brain ruptures and causes bleeding. The two main types of hemorrhagic stroke are: a. Intracerebral Hemorrhage: Bleeding occurs within the brain tissue, often due to high blood pressure or a ruptured aneurysm. b. Subarachnoid Hemorrhage: Bleeding occurs in the space between the brain and the surrounding membranes (subarachnoid space), typically caused by a ruptured aneurysm.</p> 	</li> </ol> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes and Risk Factors:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The causes and risk factors for stroke can vary depending on the type. Common risk factors include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">High blood pressure (hypertension)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Smoking</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Diabetes</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">High cholesterol</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Obesity</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Physical inactivity</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Atrial fibrillation (an irregular heartbeat)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Family history of stroke</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Age (risk increases with age)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Previous history of stroke or transient ischemic attack (TIA)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Certain medical conditions, such as carotid artery disease or certain blood disorders</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">: Stroke symptoms often occur suddenly and may include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Weakness or numbness of the face, arm, or leg (usually on one side of the body)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Confusion or trouble understanding speech</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Difficulty speaking or slurred speech</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Trouble walking, dizziness, or loss of balance and coordination</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Severe headache without a known cause</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blurred or double vision</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It&#39;s important to remember the acronym &quot;FAST&quot; to recognize and respond to stroke symptoms:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Face drooping: One side of the face droops or feels numb.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Arm weakness: One arm drifts downward when raised.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Speech difficulties: Slurred speech or difficulty speaking.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Time to call emergency services: Seek immediate medical attention if any of these symptoms are present.</li> </ul>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Diagnosing a stroke typically involves a combination of medical history assessment, physical examination, and diagnostic tests, including:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Neurological examination: Evaluating the person&#39;s physical and mental functions.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Imaging tests: Computed tomography (CT) scan or magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) to visualize the brain and identify the type and location of the stroke.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blood tests: Assessing blood clotting factors, cholesterol levels, and other markers to identify underlying risk factors and potential causes.</li> </ul><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment:</h3>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Treatment for stroke depends on the type and cause of the stroke, as well as the time of onset. The primary goals of stroke treatment are to restore blood flow to the brain, prevent further damage, and support recovery. Treatment options include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Ischemic stroke: 	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Intravenous thrombolytic therapy (tPA): A clot-dissolving medication administered within a specific time window.</li> <li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Endovascular procedures: Mechanical removal of the clot using devices such as a stent retriever or thrombectomy.</li><li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Antiplatelet or anticoagulant medications: Prescribed to prevent future blood clots.</li> </ul> </li> <li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hemorrhagic stroke: <ul> <li>Surgery: If necessary, surgical intervention may be</li> 	</ul> 	</li> </ul>  <p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Stroke.png'),
(11, 2, 'Asthma', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Asthma:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Asthma is a chronic respiratory disease that affects the airways in the lungs. It is characterized by inflammation and narrowing of the airways, which can lead to difficulty breathing, wheezing, coughing, and chest tightness. Asthma is a chronic condition, which means that it is a long-term illness that requires ongoing management.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Symptoms of asthma can vary from person to person, and they may also change over time. Common symptoms of asthma include:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Coughing, especially at night or early in the morning</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Chest tightness or pain :</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Difficulty speaking or performing normal activities due to shortness of breath</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Asthma symptoms can be triggered by a variety of factors, including allergens (such as pollen or mold), irritants (such as smoke or pollution), exercise, and respiratory infections. Some people with asthma may only experience symptoms occasionally, while others may experience them daily.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Asthma is diagnosed through a combination of medical history, physical examination, and test results. Your doctor may recommend one or more of the following tests to diagnose asthma:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lung function tests: These tests measure how well your lungs are functioning by measuring the amount of air you can exhale and how fast you can exhale.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Allergy tests: Allergies can trigger asthma symptoms, so your doctor may recommend an allergy test to determine if you have any allergies that may be contributing to your symptoms.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chest X-ray: This test can help your doctor rule out other conditions that may be causing your symptoms.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bronchoscopy: During this procedure, a thin, flexible tube with a light and camera on the end is inserted through your nose or mouth and into your airways. This allows your doctor to examine the inside of your airways and collect samples of mucus and cells for testing.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">If you are diagnosed with asthma, your doctor will work with you to develop a treatment plan that is right for you. This may include medications to control your symptoms, as well as lifestyle changes to help you manage your condition. It is important to follow your treatment plan as prescribed and to work with your doctor to adjust your treatment if your symptoms change.</p>', 'Asthma.png'),
(12, 2, 'Sleep apnea ', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Sleep apnea:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Sleep apnea is a sleep disorder characterized by interrupted breathing during sleep. It occurs when the muscles in the back of the throat fail to keep the airway open, leading to temporary pauses in breathing (apneas) or shallow breathing. These pauses can last for several seconds to minutes and can occur multiple times throughout the night. Sleep apnea can significantly disrupt sleep and lead to various health problems if left untreated.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Here is a comprehensive description of sleep apnea:</p>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: 600;\">Types of Sleep Apnea:</h3>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Obstructive Sleep Apnea (OSA): This is the most common type of sleep apnea. It occurs when the muscles in the throat relax and block the airway during sleep. When airflow is partially or completely obstructed, oxygen levels decrease, and the brain briefly wakes the person up to resume breathing.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Central Sleep Apnea (CSA): This type of sleep apnea is less common and occurs when the brain fails to send proper signals to the muscles that control breathing. Unlike OSA, there is no physical blockage in the airway. Instead, the pauses in breathing result from a lack of effort to breathe.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Complex Sleep Apnea Syndrome (also known as mixed sleep apnea): This is a combination of both obstructive and central sleep apnea, where a person initially has OSA but develops central sleep apnea during treatment with continuous positive airway pressure (CPAP).</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Causes and Risk Factors: Several factors can contribute to the development of sleep apnea, including:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Obesity: Excess weight can lead to fat deposits around the upper airway, contributing to airway obstruction.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Age: Sleep apnea becomes more common as people age, although it can occur at any age.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Gender: Men are more likely to develop sleep apnea compared to women, although the risk in women increases after menopause.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Family history: Having family members with sleep apnea increases the risk.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Smoking: Smoking can increase inflammation and fluid retention in the airway, contributing to airway narrowing.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Alcohol and sedative use: These substances can relax the muscles in the throat, making it more likely for the airway to collapse during sleep.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Nasal congestion: Chronic nasal congestion can obstruct airflow and contribute to sleep apnea.</li> </ul>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\"> Common signs and symptoms of sleep apnea include:</h3>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Loud, chronic snoring.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pauses in breathing during sleep, often witnessed by a bed partner.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Excessive daytime sleepiness or fatigue.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Morning headaches.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Waking up with a dry mouth or sore throat.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Difficulty concentrating and memory problems.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Irritability and mood changes.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Decreased libido or sexual dysfunction.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Nighttime sweating and restless sleep.</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Diagnosis: Diagnosing sleep apnea typically involves a combination of medical history assessment, physical examination, and sleep studies. Diagnostic methods include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Polysomnography (PSG): This is a comprehensive sleep study conducted in a sleep center, where various parameters are monitored, including brain activity, eye movements, muscle activity, heart rate, and breathing patterns.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Home sleep apnea testing: In certain cases, portable monitoring devices can be used at home to assess sleep apnea. These devices usually record breathing patterns, oxygen levels, and heart rate.</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Treatment: The treatment of sleep apnea aims to improve breathing during sleep, alleviate symptoms, and reduce associated health risks. Treatment options may include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Continuous Positive Airway Pressure (CPAP): This is the most common and effective treatment for sleep apnea. It involves wearing a mask that delivers a continuous flow of pressurized air, keeping the airway open during sleep.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Oral appliances: These devices are custom-made and can help keep the airway open by repositioning the jaw and tongue.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lifestyle modifications</li> </ul>  <p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Sleep apnea.png'),
(13, 2, 'Bronchitis', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Bronchitis:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bronchitis is a respiratory condition characterized by inflammation of the bronchial tubes, which are the airways that carry air to and from the lungs. It can be acute or chronic, depending on the duration and frequency of symptoms. Acute bronchitis is a common condition that typically develops as a result of viral or bacterial infections, while chronic bronchitis is a long-term condition often associated with smoking or prolonged exposure to lung irritants.</p>\n<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Here is a comprehensive description of bronchitis:</h3>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Acute bronchitis is usually caused by viral infections, such as the common cold or influenza viruses. It can also be caused by bacterial infections in some cases. The condition is characterized by inflammation of the bronchial tubes, which results in increased mucus production, coughing, and other respiratory symptoms. Acute bronchitis typically lasts for a few weeks and resolves on its own with symptomatic treatment.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Chronic Bronchitis:</h3>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Chronic bronchitis is a type of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). It is defined as a persistent cough that occurs on most days for at least three months in two consecutive years. Chronic bronchitis is primarily associated with long-term exposure to irritants, especially cigarette smoke. Other factors, such as air pollution, occupational exposure to lung irritants, and respiratory infections, can also contribute to its development. Chronic bronchitis is characterized by inflammation and narrowing of the bronchial tubes, excessive mucus production, and frequent coughing. It is a progressive condition that can cause significant impairment of lung function and quality of life.</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The symptoms of bronchitis may vary depending on whether it is acute or chronic. Common symptoms include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cough: This is the hallmark symptom of bronchitis. The cough may start dry and irritating and progress to produce mucus.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Phlegm production: Increased production of mucus, which may be clear, white, yellowish-green, or occasionally blood-tinged.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chest discomfort or tightness: Some individuals may experience chest pain or a feeling of pressure in the chest.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Shortness of breath: Breathing difficulties may occur, especially during physical exertion or as the condition worsens.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue and general malaise: Feeling tired and unwell.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Mild fever and body aches: These symptoms may occur in cases of viral or bacterial infection.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> To diagnose bronchitis, healthcare providers typically perform a physical examination and consider the patient&#39;s medical history and symptoms. Additional tests, such as a chest X-ray or pulmonary function tests, may be conducted to rule out other respiratory conditions and assess lung function if chronic bronchitis is suspected.</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The treatment of bronchitis focuses on relieving symptoms, managing complications, and preventing further lung damage. Treatment options may include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Symptomatic relief: Rest, hydration, and over-the-counter pain relievers (e.g., acetaminophen) can help alleviate symptoms.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cough suppressants: These medications may be used to control excessive coughing if it interferes with sleep or daily activities.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bronchodilators: These medications help relax the airway muscles and improve breathing.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Expectorants: Medications that thin and loosen mucus, making it easier to cough up.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Antibiotics: If a bacterial infection is present or suspected, antibiotics may be prescribed. However, they are not effective for viral bronchitis.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Smoking cessation: Quitting smoking is crucial for individuals with chronic bronchitis to slow the progression of the disease and reduce symptoms.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pulmonary rehabilitation: A program that combines exercise, breathing techniques, and education to improve lung function and quality of life for individuals with chronic bronchitis.</li> </ul>   <p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Bronchitis.png');
