(14, 2, 'Pneumonia', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Pneumonia:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pneumonia is an infection that causes inflammation in the air sacs (alveoli) of the lungs. It can be caused by various infectious agents, including bacteria, viruses, fungi, and parasites. Pneumonia can affect people of all ages, but it is most common in young children, older adults, and individuals with weakened immune systems.</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Here is a comprehensive description of pneumonia:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Causes: Pneumonia is primarily caused by the inhalation of infectious particles or the spread of an infection from another part of the body. The most common causes of pneumonia include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bacteria: Streptococcus pneumoniae is the most common bacterial cause, but other bacteria such as Haemophilus influenzae and Legionella pneumophila can also cause pneumonia.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Viruses: Influenza viruses, respiratory syncytial virus (RSV), and rhinoviruses are common viral causes of pneumonia.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fungi: Fungal pneumonia is more common in individuals with weakened immune systems, such as those with HIV/AIDS or who have undergone organ transplantation.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Parasites: Certain parasites, such as Pneumocystis jirovecii, can cause pneumonia, particularly in individuals with compromised immune systems.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The symptoms of pneumonia can vary depending on the cause, the individual&#39;s age, and overall health. Common signs and symptoms include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cough: Often accompanied by mucus production, which may be yellow, green, or bloody.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Shortness of breath: Rapid or shallow breathing and feeling breathless, especially during physical activity.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chest pain: Sharp or stabbing pain that worsens with deep breathing or coughing.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fever: High body temperature, often accompanied by chills.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue: Feeling unusually tired or weak.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Sweating and shaking chills.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Headache, muscle pain, and joint pain.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bluish tint to the lips or nail beds (in severe cases).</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> To diagnose pneumonia, healthcare providers may perform the following tests:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Physical examination: This includes listening to the lungs with a stethoscope to detect abnormal lung sounds, such as crackles or decreased breath sounds.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chest X-ray: This imaging test can help identify areas of inflammation or consolidation in the lungs.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blood tests: These tests may be done to check for infection and evaluate the overall health of the individual.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Sputum culture: A sample of mucus coughed up from the lungs may be collected and tested to identify the specific infectious agent causing pneumonia.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The treatment of pneumonia depends on the cause and severity of the infection. Common treatment options include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Antibiotics: Bacterial pneumonia is usually treated with antibiotics, while antiviral medications may be prescribed for viral pneumonia.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Antifungal medications: These are used to treat fungal pneumonia.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Supportive care: Rest, staying hydrated, and taking over-the-counter pain relievers to reduce fever and discomfort.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hospitalization: In severe cases, hospitalization may be necessary, especially for individuals with weakened immune systems or those experiencing complications such as respiratory failure.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Oxygen therapy: Supplemental oxygen may be provided if blood oxygen levels are low.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Prevention: Vaccinations, such as the pneumococcal vaccine and influenza vaccine, can help prevent certain types of pneumonia.</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It is important to seek medical attention if pneumonia is suspected, especially in individuals who are at higher risk or experiencing severe symptoms. Prompt diagnosis and appropriate treatment are essential for a successful recovery.</p>', 'Pneumonia.png'),
(15, 2, 'Emphysema', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Emphysema:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Emphysema is a chronic lung disease that is a type of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). It is characterized by the destruction and enlargement of the air sacs (alveoli) in the lungs, resulting in decreased lung function and difficulty breathing. Emphysema is primarily caused by long-term exposure to irritants, with cigarette smoke being the most common cause.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Here is a comprehensive description of emphysema:</p>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes and Risk Factors:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The primary cause of emphysema is cigarette smoking. Prolonged exposure to tobacco smoke irritates and inflames the airways, leading to damage and destruction of the alveoli. Other factors that can contribute to emphysema include long-term exposure to air pollution, occupational exposure to respiratory irritants (such as dust, chemicals, or fumes), and genetic factors (such as alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency).</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Emphysema symptoms develop slowly and progressively worsen over time. Common signs and symptoms include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Shortness of breath: Initially with physical exertion, but as the disease progresses, shortness of breath can occur even during rest.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chronic cough: Often accompanied by sputum production.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Wheezing: A whistling or high-pitched sound during breathing.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chest tightness: A feeling of constriction or pressure in the chest.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue and reduced exercise tolerance.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Unintended weight loss (in advanced stages).</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> To diagnose emphysema, healthcare providers may perform the following tests:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pulmonary function tests (PFTs): These tests measure lung function and include spirometry, which assesses the airflow limitation and lung capacity.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Imaging tests: Chest X-ray or computed tomography (CT) scan can help visualize the lungs and identify signs of emphysema.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Arterial blood gas analysis: This test measures oxygen and carbon dioxide levels in the blood to assess lung function and oxygenation.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Stages of Emphysema :</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Emphysema is often categorized into stages based on the severity of lung damage. The most commonly used staging system is the Global Initiative for Chronic Obstructive Lung Disease (GOLD) system, which classifies emphysema into four stages (from mild to very severe) based on lung function and symptoms.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Treatment: While emphysema cannot be cured, treatment focuses on managing symptoms, slowing disease progression, and improving quality of life. Treatment options may include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Smoking cessation: The most crucial step in managing emphysema is quitting smoking and avoiding exposure to secondhand smoke and other respiratory irritants.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Bronchodilators are commonly prescribed to help relax and open the airways, making breathing easier. Inhaled corticosteroids may be used to reduce inflammation.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Oxygen therapy: Supplemental oxygen may be prescribed if blood oxygen levels are low.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pulmonary rehabilitation: A comprehensive program that combines exercise, breathing techniques, education, and support to improve symptoms, physical endurance, and overall well-being.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Surgical interventions: In severe cases, surgical procedures like lung volume reduction surgery or lung transplantation may be considered to improve lung function and quality of life.</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It&#39;s important for individuals with emphysema to work closely with their healthcare provider to develop a personalized treatment plan, manage symptoms, and prevent exacerbations. Regular follow-up appointments and adherence to medication and lifestyle recommendations are crucial for optimal disease management.</p>  <p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Emphysema.png'),
(16, 2, 'Tuberculosis', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Tuberculosis (TB) :</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Tuberculosis (TB) is a contagious infectious disease caused by the bacterium Mycobacterium tuberculosis. It primarily affects the lungs but can also affect other parts of the body, such as the kidneys, spine, and brain. TB is a global health concern and one of the leading causes of death from infectious diseases worldwide.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Here is a comprehensive description of tuberculosis:</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> TB is caused by the bacterium Mycobacterium tuberculosis. It is primarily transmitted through the air when an infected person coughs, sneezes, or talks, releasing infectious droplets containing the bacteria. It is important to note that TB is not easily spread, and direct, prolonged contact with an infected individual is usually necessary for transmission to occur.</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Risk Factors:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Several factors can increase the risk of developing TB or progressing from latent infection to active disease, including:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Weakened immune system: Individuals with HIV/AIDS, malnutrition, or those taking immunosuppressive medications are at higher risk.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Close contact: Living or working in close quarters with someone with active TB increases the risk of exposure.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Age: Young children and older adults have a higher risk of developing active TB.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Health conditions: Certain medical conditions, such as diabetes, cancer, kidney disease, and lung disease, can increase the risk of developing TB.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Substance abuse: Excessive alcohol or drug use weakens the immune system and increases vulnerability to TB infection.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> TB can be either latent or active. Latent TB infection occurs when the bacteria are present in the body but are inactive and do not cause symptoms. Active TB disease occurs when the bacteria become active and cause symptoms. Common symptoms of active TB disease include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Persistent cough that lasts three weeks or longer.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Coughing up blood or bloody sputum.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chest pain and discomfort.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue and weakness.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Weight loss and loss of appetite.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fever, night sweats, and chills.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Shortness of breath.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Swollen lymph nodes.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Diagnosing TB involves several tests and evaluations, including:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Tuberculin skin test (TST): A small amount of TB protein is injected under the skin, and if a raised bump or induration occurs at the injection site, it indicates a possible TB infection.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Interferon-gamma release assays (IGRAs): Blood tests that detect immune response to TB infection.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chest X-ray: An X-ray of the chest can help identify abnormal areas in the lungs.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Sputum analysis: A sample of sputum is collected and examined for the presence of TB bacteria.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Molecular tests: These tests can detect the presence of TB DNA or RNA in sputum or other body fluids.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> TB is treatable and curable with appropriate treatment. Treatment typically involves a combination of several antibiotics taken for a prolonged period (usually six to nine months) to ensure complete eradication of the bacteria. Commonly used medications include isoniazid, rifampin, ethambutol, and pyrazinamide. It is crucial to complete the full course of treatment as prescribed to prevent the development of drug-resistant TB.</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Prevention:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Preventive measures play a vital role in controlling the spread of TB. These include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Vaccination: The Bacille Calmette-Gu&eacute;rin (BCG) vaccine provides partial protection against severe forms of TB, particularly in children.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Infection control: Ensuring proper ventilation and implementing infection control measures in healthcare settings and congregate settings can reduce the risk of TB transmission.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Early detection and treatment: Prompt diagnosis and treatment of TB cases help prevent the spread of the disease.</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weig', 'Tuberculosis.png'),
(17, 2, 'Lung cancer', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Lung cancer:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lung cancer is a malignant tumor that originates in the cells of the lungs. It is one of the most common types of cancer and a leading cause of cancer-related deaths worldwide. Lung cancer is primarily caused by long-term exposure to harmful substances, particularly tobacco smoke, although it can also occur in non-smokers.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Here is a comprehensive description of lung cancer:</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Types of Lung Cancer:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> There are two main types of lung cancer:</p>  <ol> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Non-small cell lung cancer (NSCLC): This is the most common type, accounting for about 80-85% of all lung cancer cases. NSCLC includes subtypes such as adenocarcinoma, squamous cell carcinoma, and large cell carcinoma.</li> <li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Small cell lung cancer (SCLC): This type is less common, accounting for about 10-15% of lung cancer cases. SCLC tends to grow and spread more quickly than NSCLC and is often associated with a history of heavy smoking.</li> </ol> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes and Risk Factors:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The primary cause of lung cancer is tobacco smoke, including cigarette, cigar, and pipe smoking. However, lung cancer can also occur in non-smokers due to other risk factors, such as:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Secondhand smoke exposure: Breathing in smoke from other people&#39;s tobacco products.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Occupational exposure: Prolonged exposure to asbestos, radon gas, certain chemicals (e.g., arsenic, chromium, nickel), and industrial substances.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Family history: A personal or family history of lung cancer can increase the risk.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Radon gas exposure: Radon, a naturally occurring radioactive gas that can be present in homes and buildings, is a significant risk factor for lung cancer.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Air pollution: Prolonged exposure to high levels of air pollution, including pollutants from vehicles, factories, and other sources.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Personal history of lung disease: Individuals with a history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), tuberculosis, or lung fibrosis are at higher risk.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The symptoms of lung cancer can vary depending on the type, stage, and location of the tumor. Common signs and symptoms include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Persistent cough that worsens over time.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Shortness of breath or wheezing.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chest pain or discomfort.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Coughing up blood or bloody mucus.</li> <li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hoarseness or voice changes.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Unexplained weight loss.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue and weakness.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Recurrent respiratory infections, such as bronchitis or pneumonia.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Diagnosing lung cancer involves several tests and procedures, including:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Imaging tests: Chest X-rays, computed tomography (CT) scans, and positron emission tomography (PET) scans help visualize the lungs and detect any abnormalities.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Biopsy: A tissue sample is taken from the lung or lymph nodes for microscopic examination to confirm the presence of cancer cells.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Molecular testing: Genetic testing of the cancer cells to identify specific gene mutations that can guide treatment decisions.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Staging: Determining the extent of cancer spread, which helps determine the appropriate treatment approach.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Treatment options for lung cancer depend on various factors, including the type, stage, and overall health of the individual. Common treatment modalities include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Surgery: Removing the tumor and nearby lymph nodes is often an option for early-stage lung cancer.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Radiation therapy: High-energy X-rays or other forms of radiation are used to destroy cancer cells.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chemotherapy: Powerful medications are used to kill cancer cells throughout the body.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Targeted therapy: Drugs that specifically target certain genetic mutations or proteins involved in cancer growth.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Immunotherapy: Medications that stimulate the immune system to recognize and attack cancer cells.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Palliative care: Focusing on symptom management and improving quality of life, particularly for advanced-stage or metastatic lung</li> </ul><li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It is important to seek medical attention if TB is suspected. Timely diagnosis, appropriate treatment, and adherence</p>', 'Lung cancer.png'),
(18, 2, 'Pulmonary embolism', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Pulmonary Embolism :</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pulmonary embolism (PE) is a potentially life-threatening condition that occurs when a blood clot forms in one of the pulmonary arteries, which are the blood vessels that carry blood from the heart to the lungs. The clot, known as an embolus, typically originates in the deep veins of the legs (deep vein thrombosis) and travels to the lungs, blocking blood flow and causing various symptoms.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Here is a comprehensive description of pulmonary embolism:</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes and Risk Factors:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The most common cause of pulmonary embolism is a blood clot that forms in the deep veins of the legs, known as a deep vein thrombosis (DVT). Several factors can increase the risk of developing a blood clot and subsequently developing a pulmonary embolism, including:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Prolonged immobility: Such as during long periods of travel, bed rest, or immobility due to surgery.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Surgery: Particularly orthopedic surgeries such as hip or knee replacements.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Trauma: Injuries, fractures, or severe muscle damage can increase the risk.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cancer: Some types of cancer and cancer treatments can make blood more prone to clotting.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pregnancy and childbirth: Hormonal changes and pressure on veins during pregnancy increase the risk.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hormonal therapy: Use of oral contraceptives or hormone replacement therapy.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Obesity: Being overweight or obese increases the risk of clot formation.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Smoking: Smoking damages blood vessels and increases the risk of clotting.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Inherited or acquired clotting disorders: Certain genetic or acquired conditions can predispose individuals to clot formation.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The symptoms of pulmonary embolism can vary depending on the size of the clot and the extent of the obstruction in the pulmonary arteries. Common signs and symptoms include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Sudden onset of shortness of breath, which may worsen with exertion.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chest pain: Sharp or stabbing pain that may worsen with deep breathing or coughing.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Rapid or irregular heartbeat (palpitations).</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cough: May be dry or accompanied by blood-tinged sputum.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Anxiety and a sense of impending doom.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Sweating and lightheadedness.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fainting or loss of consciousness (in severe cases). It is important to note that the severity of symptoms does not always correlate with the size of the clot, and some individuals may experience few or no symptoms.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Diagnosing pulmonary embolism can be challenging as the symptoms can mimic other conditions. Healthcare providers use several tests and evaluations to confirm the diagnosis, including:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Imaging tests: Computed tomography pulmonary angiography (CTPA) is the most commonly used imaging test to visualize blood flow and identify blockages in the pulmonary arteries.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Doppler ultrasound: Used to detect blood clots in the legs or pelvis (deep vein thrombosis).</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blood tests: Measuring D-dimer levels, a marker of blood clot breakdown, can help assess the likelihood of a clot.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Electrocardiogram (ECG): Used to evaluate heart function and detect any abnormalities.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Ventilation-perfusion (V/Q) scan: A nuclear medicine test that assesses lung ventilation and blood flow.</li> </ul>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Prompt treatment is crucial in managing pulmonary embolism and preventing complications. Treatment options include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Anticoagulant medications: Blood-thinning medications, such as heparin and warfarin, are typically prescribed to prevent further clot formation and facilitate the body&#39;s natural clot-dissolving processes.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Thrombolytic therapy: In severe cases, clot-dissolving medications may be administered to rapidly dissolve the clot.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Inferior vena cava (IVC) filter: A small device placed in the inferior vena cava to prevent clots fr</li> </ul>', 'Pulmonary embolism.png'),
(19, 2, 'Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD):</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) is a chronic respiratory condition that causes airflow limitation and difficulty breathing. It is a progressive disease that worsens over time and is primarily caused by long-term exposure to irritating substances, most commonly cigarette smoke. COPD encompasses several lung conditions, including chronic bronchitis and emphysema.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Here is a comprehensive description of COPD:</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes and Risk Factors:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The primary cause of COPD is long-term exposure to irritants that damage the lungs and airways. The most significant risk factor for developing COPD is smoking. However, exposure to other harmful substances can also contribute, such as occupational dust and chemicals, air pollution, and indoor cooking and heating fuels. Other risk factors include a family history of COPD, respiratory infections during childhood, and genetic factors like alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency.</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The symptoms of COPD may develop gradually and worsen over time. Common signs and symptoms include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Persistent cough: Often accompanied by mucus production (chronic bronchitis).</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Shortness of breath: Particularly during physical activity, and as the disease progresses, breathlessness may occur even during rest.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Wheezing: A whistling or squeaky sound when breathing.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chest tightness: A sensation of constriction or pressure in the chest.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Frequent respiratory infections.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue and reduced exercise tolerance.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Unintended weight loss (in advanced stages).</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> To diagnose COPD, healthcare providers may perform the following tests:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pulmonary function tests (PFTs): Measures lung function, including spirometry to assess airflow limitation and lung capacity.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chest X-ray or CT scan: Provides images of the lungs to evaluate for signs of COPD and rule out other lung conditions.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Arterial blood gas analysis: Measures oxygen and carbon dioxide levels in the blood to assess lung function and oxygenation.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Stages of COPD:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> COPD is typically categorized into four stages based on the severity of airflow limitation, as determined by spirometry:</p>  <ol> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Mild COPD: Mild airflow limitation with a minimal impact on daily life.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Moderate COPD: Increased airflow limitation, leading to symptoms that affect daily activities.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Severe COPD: Further worsening of airflow limitation, causing a significant impact on quality of life and increased risk of complications.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Very severe COPD: Severe airflow limitation with severe symptoms, frequent exacerbations, and significant limitations in physical activity.</li><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment:</h3>  </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Although COPD is a chronic condition with no cure, treatment aims to manage symptoms, slow disease progression, and improve overall quality of life. Treatment options may include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Smoking cessation: The most crucial step in managing COPD is quitting smoking and avoiding exposure to secondhand smoke and other respiratory irritants.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Bronchodilators to relax and open the airways, corticosteroids to reduce inflammation, and medications to thin mucus and improve coughing.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pulmonary rehabilitation: A comprehensive program that combines exercise, breathing techniques, education, and support to improve symptoms and physical endurance.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Oxygen therapy: Supplemental oxygen may be prescribed if blood oxygen levels are low.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Vaccinations: Annual influenza vaccine and pneumococcal vaccine to reduce the risk of respiratory infections.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Surgical interventions: In some cases, surgical procedures such as lung volume reduction surgery or lung transplantation may be considered for severe COPD.</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It&#39;s important for individuals with COPD to work closely with their healthcare provider to develop a personalized treatment plan, manage symptoms, and prevent exacerbations. Regular follow-up appointments and adherence to medication and lifestyle recommendations are crucial for optimal disease management.</p>  <p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.png'),
(20, 3, 'Gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD)', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD):</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) is a chronic digestive disorder characterized by the abnormal flow of stomach acid and other contents back into the esophagus. It occurs when the lower esophageal sphincter (LES), a muscular ring that normally keeps the stomach contents from flowing backward, becomes weakened or relaxes inappropriately. This can lead to a variety of uncomfortable symptoms and potential complications.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Here is a comprehensive description of GERD:</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes and Risk Factors:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The exact cause of GERD is not fully understood, but several factors can contribute to its development, including:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Weak lower esophageal sphincter (LES): A weakened LES allows stomach acid to flow back into the esophagus.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hiatal hernia: A condition in which a portion of the stomach pushes up through the diaphragm, impairing the function of the LES.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Obesity: Excess weight puts pressure on the abdomen, leading to increased risk of GERD.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pregnancy: Hormonal changes and increased pressure on the stomach during pregnancy can contribute to GERD.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Certain foods and beverages: Spicy, fatty, or acidic foods, as well as caffeine, alcohol, and carbonated drinks, can trigger symptoms.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Smoking: Tobacco use can weaken the LES and impair normal esophageal function.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Certain medications, such as nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs), calcium channel blockers, and some asthma medications, may contribute to GERD symptoms.</li> </ul>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> GERD can cause a range of symptoms, which may vary in frequency and severity among individuals. Common symptoms include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Heartburn: A burning sensation or discomfort in the chest, often occurring after meals or when lying down.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Acid regurgitation: The sensation of stomach acid or bitter-tasting fluid coming back into the throat or mouth.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Difficulty swallowing: A feeling of food getting stuck in the throat or chest.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chest pain: May mimic the symptoms of a heart attack, but it is typically less severe and does not radiate to the arm.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chronic cough: A persistent cough, often worse at night, that is unrelated to other respiratory conditions.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hoarseness or voice changes: Refluxed stomach acid can irritate the vocal cords.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Asthma symptoms: GERD can worsen asthma symptoms in some individuals.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Diagnosing GERD involves a combination of medical history, symptom assessment, and diagnostic tests. These may include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Symptom evaluation: Assessing the frequency, severity, and pattern of symptoms.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Upper endoscopy: A procedure in which a thin, flexible tube with a camera is inserted through the mouth to visualize the esophagus, stomach, and upper digestive tract.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Esophageal pH monitoring: Measures the amount of acid in the esophagus over a 24-hour period.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Esophageal manometry: Evaluates the function and movement of the esophagus and LES.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Barium swallow: X-ray imaging of the esophagus and stomach after drinking a contrast material (barium).</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Treatment for GERD aims to alleviate symptoms, heal any esophageal damage, and prevent complications. Common treatment options include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lifestyle modifications: This includes weight loss, avoiding trigger foods, eating smaller meals, avoiding lying down after meals, and elevating the head of the bed during sleep.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Over-the-counter antacids, such as Tums or Rolaids, can provide temporary relief. Proton pump inhibitors (PPIs), such as omeprazole or esomeprazole, reduce stomach acid production and promote healing of the esophagus.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Surgery: In severe cases or when medications and lifestyle changes do not provide adequate relief, surgical interventions such as fund</li> </ul>', 'Gastroesophageal reflux disease.png'),
(21, 3, 'Peptic ulcer disease', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Peptic ulcer disease:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Peptic ulcer disease refers to the formation of open sores or ulcers in the lining of the stomach, upper small intestine (duodenum), or esophagus. These ulcers occur when the protective lining of these organs is damaged and eroded, exposing the underlying tissues to digestive acids and enzymes. Peptic ulcers can cause various symptoms and, if left untreated, can lead to complications.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Here is a comprehensive description of peptic ulcer disease:</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes and Risk Factors:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Peptic ulcers are primarily caused by an imbalance between the factors that protect the lining of the digestive tract and those that can damage it. The most common causes and risk factors include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Helicobacter pylori (H. pylori) infection: This bacterium is a major cause of peptic ulcers. H. pylori can weaken the protective mucus layer in the stomach, allowing stomach acid to damage the underlying tissue.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs): Regular or prolonged use of NSAIDs, such as aspirin, ibuprofen, or naproxen, can irritate and erode the lining of the stomach and duodenum.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Smoking: Smoking increases the risk of developing peptic ulcers and delays the healing process.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Excessive alcohol consumption: Heavy alcohol use can irritate and erode the stomach lining.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Stress: Although stress does not directly cause peptic ulcers, it can worsen symptoms and delay healing.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Other factors: Certain medical conditions, such as Zollinger-Ellison syndrome (a rare tumor that causes excessive acid production), and genetic predisposition may also increase the risk of peptic ulcers.</li> </ul>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The symptoms of peptic ulcers can vary from person to person and depend on the location and severity of the ulcer. Some common signs and symptoms include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abdominal pain: A burning or gnawing pain in the middle or upper abdomen, which can occur between meals or during the night.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Nausea and vomiting: Some individuals may experience these symptoms, especially after eating.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Loss of appetite and unintended weight loss.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bloating and feeling full quickly.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Indigestion or heartburn.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bloody or dark stool (indicating bleeding from the ulcer).</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Vomiting blood or material that resembles coffee grounds (indicating bleeding from the ulcer).</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Diagnosing peptic ulcer disease involves a combination of medical history, symptom evaluation, and diagnostic tests. These may include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Physical examination: The healthcare provider will evaluate your symptoms and perform a physical examination.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Endoscopy: This procedure involves inserting a thin, flexible tube with a camera (endoscope) through the mouth to visualize the lining of the esophagus, stomach, and duodenum.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Upper gastrointestinal series: X-ray imaging of the upper digestive tract after drinking a contrast material (barium).</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">H. pylori testing: This can include blood tests, breath tests, stool tests, or tissue biopsy during endoscopy to detect the presence of H. pylori bacteria.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Treatment for peptic ulcer disease aims to relieve symptoms, promote ulcer healing, and prevent complications. The specific treatment plan may vary depending on the underlying cause and severity of the ulcer. Common treatment options include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Antibiotics are prescribed to eradicate H. pylori infection if present. Acid-suppressing medications, such as proton pump inhibitors (PPIs) or H2 blockers, are used to reduce stomach acid production and promote healing.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Antacids: Over-the-counter antacids can provide temporary relief from symptoms by neutralizing stomach acid.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Avoidance of irritants: This includes avoiding NSAIDs, alcohol, smoking, and spicy or acidic foods that can worsen symptoms</li> </ul>', 'Peptic ulcer disease.png');
