(22, 3, 'Irritable bowel syndrome (IBS)', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Irritable bowel syndrome (IBS):</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Irritable bowel syndrome (IBS) is a common chronic disorder that affects the functioning of the large intestine (colon). It is characterized by a group of symptoms, including abdominal pain or discomfort, changes in bowel habits, and bloating. While IBS does not cause permanent damage to the intestines or increase the risk of serious diseases, it can significantly impact a person&#39;s quality of life.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Here is a comprehensive description of irritable bowel syndrome (IBS):</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes and Risk Factors:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The exact cause of IBS is not fully understood, but several factors may contribute to its development. These include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abnormal gastrointestinal motility: People with IBS may experience either stronger or weaker contractions of the colon, leading to changes in bowel habits.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Increased sensitivity to pain: Individuals with IBS may have a more sensitive colon, making them more susceptible to discomfort or pain.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Intestinal inflammation: Low-grade inflammation in the intestines may contribute to the development of IBS symptoms in some individuals.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Changes in gut microbiota: An imbalance in the normal bacteria that reside in the intestines (gut microbiota) may play a role in IBS development.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Food intolerances: Certain foods or substances, such as lactose or gluten, may trigger symptoms in some individuals.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Mental health conditions: Psychological factors, including stress, anxiety, and depression, can influence the onset and severity of IBS symptoms.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The symptoms of IBS can vary from person to person and may range from mild to severe. The most common symptoms include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abdominal pain or cramping: Typically located in the lower abdomen and often relieved by bowel movements.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Changes in bowel habits: This can include diarrhea, constipation, or alternating episodes of both.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bloating and excess gas: Many individuals with IBS experience bloating, which can cause the abdomen to feel distended.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Changes in stool consistency: Stools may appear loose, watery, hard, or pellet-like.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Urgency to have a bowel movement: Some individuals may feel an intense urge to have a bowel movement, often accompanied by difficulty controlling it.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Mucus in the stool: Some people with IBS may notice the presence of mucus in their stools.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abnormal bowel movements: Some individuals may experience a feeling of incomplete bowel movement or the sensation of not being able to completely empty the bowels.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Diagnosing IBS involves a comprehensive evaluation of symptoms, medical history, and ruling out other possible conditions. There is no specific test to definitively diagnose IBS, but diagnostic approaches may include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medical history and symptom assessment: The healthcare provider will evaluate the frequency, duration, and nature of your symptoms.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Physical examination: This may include an abdominal examination to check for signs of tenderness or abnormality.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Rome criteria: A set of diagnostic criteria that help classify and identify IBS based on specific symptom patterns.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blood tests: These may be conducted to rule out other conditions that could cause similar symptoms.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Stool tests: These tests may be performed to check for signs of infection, inflammation, or other abnormalities.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Treatment for IBS focuses on managing symptoms and improving quality of life. It often involves a combination of lifestyle changes, dietary modifications, and medication. Treatment options may include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Dietary modifications: Identifying and avoiding trigger foods, such as certain types of carbohydrates (FODMAPs), caffeine, alcohol, and spicy foods.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fiber supplements: Adding fiber to the diet or taking fiber supplements can help regulate bowel movements and reduce constipation.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Depending on the predominant symptoms, various medications may be prescribed, such as antispasmodics to reduce abdominal pain and cramping, laxatives for constipation, or</li> </ul>', 'Irritable bowel syndrome.png'),
(23, 3, 'Crohn\'s disease', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Crohn&#39;s disease:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Crohn&#39;s disease is a chronic inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) that primarily affects the gastrointestinal tract. It causes inflammation and damage to various parts of the digestive system, leading to a range of symptoms and potential complications. Crohn&#39;s disease is characterized by periods of flare-ups and remission, with no known cure.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Here is a comprehensive description of Crohn&#39;s disease:</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes and Risk Factors:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The exact cause of Crohn&#39;s disease is unknown, but several factors may contribute to its development, including:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Genetic predisposition: People with a family history of Crohn&#39;s disease have a higher risk of developing the condition.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abnormal immune response: The immune system may mistakenly attack healthy cells in the gastrointestinal tract, leading to inflammation.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Environmental factors: Certain environmental factors, such as diet, smoking, and exposure to certain bacteria or viruses, may play a role in triggering or exacerbating Crohn&#39;s disease.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Gut microbiota: Alterations in the balance of bacteria in the gut may contribute to the development of Crohn&#39;s disease.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The symptoms of Crohn&#39;s disease can vary widely from person to person, and they depend on the location and severity of the inflammation. Common signs and symptoms include:</p>  <ul> <li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abdominal pain and cramping: Often occurs in the lower right abdomen, but can occur anywhere along the digestive tract.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Diarrhea: Often chronic and may be bloody or contain mucus.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Weight loss: Loss of appetite, malabsorption, and increased calorie expenditure due to inflammation can lead to unintentional weight loss.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue: Inflammation, nutritional deficiencies, and the body&#39;s response to the disease can cause fatigue and a lack of energy.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fever: Some individuals may experience recurrent low-grade fevers.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Rectal bleeding: Inflammation in the rectum can lead to bleeding, which may present as blood in the stool.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Mouth sores: Some people with Crohn&#39;s disease may develop ulcers in the mouth.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Reduced appetite and malnutrition: Ongoing inflammation can affect nutrient absorption, leading to malnutrition and nutrient deficiencies.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Diagnosing Crohn&#39;s disease involves a combination of medical history, physical examination, and various diagnostic tests. These may include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Endoscopy and colonoscopy: These procedures allow visualization of the gastrointestinal tract and collection of tissue samples (biopsy) for examination.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Imaging tests: X-rays, computed tomography (CT) scans, magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), or ultrasound may be used to assess the extent and location of inflammation.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blood tests: These can help evaluate inflammation levels, identify nutritional deficiencies, and rule out other conditions.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Stool tests: These tests may be conducted to rule out infections or other causes of gastrointestinal symptoms.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Treatment for Crohn&#39;s disease aims to control symptoms, reduce inflammation, promote healing, and prevent complications. Treatment plans are individualized based on the severity and location of the disease. Common treatment options include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Various medications may be prescribed, including anti-inflammatory drugs (such as corticosteroids and 5-aminosalicylates), immunomodulators, biologic therapies, and antibiotics.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Nutrition therapy: In some cases, a special liquid diet or nutritional supplements may be recommended to provide necessary nutrients and allow the intestines to heal.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lifestyle modifications: Managing stress, adopting a healthy diet, staying hydrated, and getting regular exercise can help manage symptoms and promote overall well-being.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Surgery: In severe cases or when medication and lifestyle changes do not provide adequate relief, surgery may be necessary to remove the affected portion of the digestive tract or address complications.</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It is important for individuals with Crohn&#39;s disease to work closely with healthcare providers to develop a comprehensive treatment plan and receive ongoing monitoring</p>', 'Crohn\'s disease.png'),
(24, 3, 'Ulcerative colitis', '<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Ulcerative colitis is a chronic inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) that primarily affects the colon (large intestine) and rectum. It is characterized by inflammation and ulcers in the inner lining of the colon, leading to a range of symptoms and potential complications. Ulcerative colitis is a lifelong condition with periods of flare-ups and remission.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Here is a comprehensive description of ulcerative colitis:</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Causes and Risk Factors: The exact cause of ulcerative colitis is unknown, but several factors may contribute to its development, including:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abnormal immune response: The immune system may mistakenly trigger inflammation in the colon and rectum, leading to chronic inflammation.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Genetic factors: People with a family history of ulcerative colitis have an increased risk of developing the condition.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Environmental factors: Certain environmental factors, such as diet, stress, and exposure to bacteria or viruses, may play a role in triggering or exacerbating ulcerative colitis.</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Symptoms: The symptoms of ulcerative colitis can vary in severity and depend on the extent and location of inflammation in the colon. Common signs and symptoms include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Diarrhea: Often with blood or pus, and may be accompanied by an urgent need to have a bowel movement.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abdominal pain and cramping: Typically located in the lower left side of the abdomen.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Rectal bleeding: Blood may be present in the stool or noticed on toilet paper.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Urgency to have a bowel movement: The feeling of needing to pass stool urgently.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Loss of appetite and weight loss: Inflammation and symptoms can lead to reduced appetite and unintentional weight loss.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue: Chronic inflammation and ongoing symptoms can cause fatigue and lack of energy.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fever: Some individuals may experience recurrent low-grade fevers.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Tenesmus: A constant feeling of needing to pass stool, even after a bowel movement.</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Diagnosis: Diagnosing ulcerative colitis involves a combination of medical history, physical examination, and various diagnostic tests. These may include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Colonoscopy: A procedure that allows visualization of the colon and rectum to assess the extent and severity of inflammation and obtain tissue samples (biopsy) for examination.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Flexible sigmoidoscopy: A similar procedure to colonoscopy, but it examines only the lower part of the colon and rectum.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Imaging tests: X-rays, computed tomography (CT) scans, magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), or ultrasound may be used to evaluate the extent and severity of inflammation.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blood tests: These can help evaluate inflammation levels, identify nutritional deficiencies, and rule out other conditions.</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Treatment: Treatment for ulcerative colitis aims to control symptoms, reduce inflammation, promote healing, and prevent complications. Treatment plans are individualized based on the severity and extent of the disease. Common treatment options include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Various medications may be prescribed, including anti-inflammatory drugs (such as corticosteroids and 5-aminosalicylates), immunomodulators, and biologic therapies.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Rectal medications: These may include suppositories or enemas containing medications to reduce inflammation in the rectum.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lifestyle modifications: Managing stress, adopting a healthy diet, staying hydrated, and getting regular exercise can help manage symptoms and promote overall well-being.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Surgery: In severe cases or when medication and lifestyle changes do not provide adequate relief, surgery may be necessary to remove the colon and rectum (proctocolectomy). Surgery may be done in stages or may involve creating an ostomy.</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It is important for individuals with ulcerative colitis to work closely with healthcare providers to develop a comprehensive treatment plan, receive ongoing monitoring, and manage the condition effectively.</p>', 'Ulcerative colitis.png'),
(25, 3, 'Gallstones', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Gallstones:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Gallstones are small, hardened deposits that form in the gallbladder, a small organ located beneath the liver. Gallstones can vary in size and composition, and they can cause a range of symptoms and complications. The condition is known as cholelithiasis.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Here is a comprehensive description of gallstones:</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes and Risk Factors:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Causes and Risk Factors: The exact cause of gallstones formation is not fully understood, but several factors may contribute to their development. These include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Excess cholesterol: High levels of cholesterol in the bile can lead to the formation of cholesterol gallstones, which are the most common type.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Excess bilirubin: An excessive breakdown of red blood cells or liver disease can lead to an increased production of bilirubin, contributing to the formation of pigment gallstones.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Gallbladder motility: A gallbladder that does not empty properly or empties infrequently may increase the risk of gallstone formation.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Obesity: Being overweight or obese is a risk factor for gallstones.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Gender and age: Women, especially those who have had multiple pregnancies, are at a higher risk of developing gallstones. Additionally, the risk increases with age.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Genetics: A family history of gallstones increases the likelihood of developing the condition.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Certain medical conditions: Certain medical conditions, such as diabetes, liver disease, and rapid weight loss, may increase the risk of gallstones.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Gallstones may not always cause symptoms and can be silent in some cases. However, when symptoms do occur, they can be quite uncomfortable. Common signs and symptoms of gallstones include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abdominal pain: Typically, pain occurs in the upper right part of the abdomen and may be severe and intermittent, lasting from minutes to hours.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Back pain: Pain may radiate to the back, between the shoulder blades.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Nausea and vomiting: Some individuals may experience nausea and vomiting, especially after a meal.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Indigestion: Digestive symptoms, such as bloating, gas, and heartburn, may be present.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Changes in bowel movements: Gallstones can cause changes in bowel habits, including diarrhea or pale-colored stools.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Jaundice: In rare cases, if a gallstone blocks the bile duct, it can lead to yellowing of the skin and eyes (jaundice).</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Diagnosing gallstones involves a combination of medical history, physical examination, and diagnostic tests. These may include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abdominal ultrasound: This non-invasive imaging test uses sound waves to create images of the gallbladder and detect the presence of gallstones.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blood tests: These can help evaluate liver function and detect signs of inflammation or infection.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Other imaging tests: In some cases, additional tests such as a computed tomography (CT) scan, magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), or a hepatobiliary iminodiacetic acid (HIDA) scan may be performed to evaluate the gallbladder and bile ducts.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Treatment for gallstones depends on the presence of symptoms and the risk of complications. Common treatment options include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Watchful waiting: If gallstones are not causing symptoms, treatment may not be necessary, but regular monitoring is recommended.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Medications may be prescribed to dissolve gallstones in certain cases, but they are typically not effective for all types of gallstones.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Surgery: The most common and effective treatment for symptomatic gallstones is surgery to remove the gallbladder (cholecystectomy). This can be done using minimally invasive laparoscopic techniques or open surgery.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Endoscopic procedures: In some cases, gallstones can be removed through endoscopic procedures, such as endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) or</li> </ul>', 'Gallstones.png'),
(26, 3, 'Pancreatitis', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Pancreatitis:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pancreatitis is a condition characterized by inflammation of the pancreas, an organ located behind the stomach. The pancreas plays a vital role in digestion and the regulation of blood sugar levels. Pancreatitis can be acute, occurring suddenly and lasting for a short period, or chronic, developing gradually and persisting over a long period of time.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Here is a comprehensive description of pancreatitis:</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes and Risk Factors:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The two main causes of pancreatitis are:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Gallstones: The most common cause of acute pancreatitis is the presence of gallstones, which can block the pancreatic duct and lead to inflammation. Gallstones are small, hardened deposits that form in the gallbladder.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Alcohol consumption: Chronic alcohol abuse is a leading cause of chronic pancreatitis. Prolonged alcohol use can lead to the development of pancreatic inflammation and scarring.</p> 	</li> </ol> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Other risk factors for pancreatitis include:</h3> <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Smoking: Cigarette smoking increases the risk of both acute and chronic pancreatitis.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Genetic factors: Certain genetic mutations and hereditary disorders, such as cystic fibrosis, can increase the risk of developing pancreatitis.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">High levels of blood triglycerides: Elevated triglyceride levels can contribute to the development of pancreatitis.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Certain medications: Some medications, such as certain antibiotics, diuretics, and immunosuppressants, have been associated with an increased risk of pancreatitis.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Trauma or injury to the pancreas: In some cases, trauma or injury to the abdomen can lead to pancreatitis.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The symptoms of pancreatitis can vary in severity and may include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abdominal pain: The most common symptom of pancreatitis is severe and persistent abdominal pain. The pain is usually located in the upper abdomen and can radiate to the back.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Nausea and vomiting: Individuals with pancreatitis often experience nausea, vomiting, and loss of appetite.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fever: Some cases of pancreatitis can be accompanied by a low-grade fever.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Rapid pulse: An increased heart rate may be observed in severe cases.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Jaundice: In cases where the bile duct is blocked, yellowing of the skin and eyes (jaundice) may occur.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Digestive problems: Pancreatitis can lead to problems with digestion, resulting in diarrhea and oily, foul-smelling stools (steatorrhea).</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Weight loss: Chronic pancreatitis can cause malabsorption of nutrients, leading to unintentional weight loss.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Diagnosing pancreatitis involves a combination of medical history, physical examination, and diagnostic tests. These may include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blood tests: Blood tests can help assess levels of pancreatic enzymes, such as amylase and lipase, which are elevated in pancreatitis.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Imaging tests: Tests such as ultrasound, CT scan, or MRI may be used to visualize the pancreas and detect inflammation, blockages, or structural abnormalities.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP): This procedure combines endoscopy and X-ray imaging to examine the pancreatic and bile ducts.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Treatment for pancreatitis aims to relieve symptoms, promote healing, prevent complications, and manage underlying causes. Treatment options may include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hospitalization: Severe cases of pancreatitis often require hospitalization for close monitoring and supportive care.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pain management: Medications can be prescribed to manage pain during acute episodes.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">IV fluids and nutrition: If the individual is unable to eat or drink, intravenous fluids and nutrition may be administered to maintain hydration and provide essential nutrients.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Removal of gallstones or blockages: In cases where gallstones or blockages are the cause of pancreatitis, procedures may be performed to remove them.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lifestyle changes: For chronic pancreatitis, lifestyle modifications such as avoiding alcohol</li> </ul>', 'Pancreatitis.png'),
(27, 3, 'Celiac disease', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Celiac disease:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Celiac disease, also known as celiac sprue or gluten-sensitive enteropathy, is an autoimmune disorder that affects the small intestine. It is triggered by the ingestion of gluten, a protein found in wheat, barley, and rye. When individuals with celiac disease consume gluten, their immune system responds by attacking the lining of the small intestine, causing inflammation and damage. Over time, this damage can lead to various symptoms and complications.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Here is a comprehensive description of celiac disease:</p>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes and Risk Factors:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Celiac disease is primarily caused by a combination of genetic and environmental factors. The presence of specific genes, particularly HLA-DQ2 and HLA-DQ8, predisposes individuals to develop celiac disease. However, not everyone with these genes develops the condition, indicating that other factors, such as environmental triggers, play a role.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The main environmental trigger for celiac disease is gluten. When individuals with the genetic predisposition consume gluten, it triggers an immune response that damages the lining of the small intestine. Other factors that may contribute to the development of celiac disease include early introduction of gluten in an infant&#39;s diet, gastrointestinal infections, and certain autoimmune disorders, such as type 1 diabetes and autoimmune thyroid disease.</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Celiac disease can cause a wide range of symptoms that vary among individuals. Some common symptoms include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Digestive issues: These may include abdominal pain, bloating, gas, diarrhea, constipation, and pale, foul-smelling stools.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Weight loss and malnutrition: Damage to the small intestine can interfere with nutrient absorption, leading to weight loss, nutrient deficiencies, and malnutrition.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue: Chronic fatigue and weakness are common symptoms of celiac disease.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Anemia: Iron deficiency anemia may occur due to malabsorption of iron.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Dermatitis herpetiformis: Some individuals with celiac disease may develop a skin rash called dermatitis herpetiformis, characterized by itchy, blistering lesions.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bone and joint pain: Celiac disease can lead to problems with calcium absorption, resulting in bone and joint pain, osteoporosis, or osteopenia.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Growth issues: In children, celiac disease can impair growth and development.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Neurological symptoms: Some individuals may experience neurological symptoms, such as headaches, peripheral neuropathy, and coordination problems.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Reproductive issues: Celiac disease can affect reproductive health, leading to delayed puberty, infertility, or recurrent miscarriages.</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It is important to note that some individuals may have &quot;silent&quot; celiac disease, meaning they experience no noticeable symptoms despite having intestinal damage. However, long-term complications can still occur in these cases.</p>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Diagnosing celiac disease involves a combination of medical history, physical examination, serological</p>', 'Celiac disease.png'),
(28, 3, 'Hepatitis', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Hepatitis:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hepatitis is a term that refers to inflammation of the liver. It can be caused by various factors, including viral infections, alcohol consumption, certain medications, autoimmune conditions, and metabolic disorders. The most common forms of hepatitis are viral hepatitis, which are caused by specific viruses. There are several types of viral hepatitis, including hepatitis A, hepatitis B, hepatitis C, hepatitis D, and hepatitis E.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Here is a comprehensive description of hepatitis:</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes and Risk Factors:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The causes of hepatitis vary depending on the type of hepatitis. The most common causes are viral infections. The different types of viral hepatitis are transmitted through different routes:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hepatitis A (HAV): This type of hepatitis is primarily transmitted through the ingestion of contaminated food or water.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hepatitis B (HBV): HBV is transmitted through contact with infected blood, unprotected sexual intercourse, sharing needles or syringes, and from an infected mother to her baby during childbirth.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hepatitis C (HCV): HCV is primarily transmitted through contact with infected blood, such as sharing needles or syringes during drug use, receiving contaminated blood transfusions or organ transplants, and less commonly, through sexual transmission.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hepatitis D (HDV): HDV only affects individuals who are already infected with HBV. It is transmitted through similar routes as HBV.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hepatitis E (HEV): HEV is primarily transmitted through the consumption of contaminated water or food, particularly in areas with poor sanitation.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Other forms of hepatitis can be caused by factors such as excessive alcohol consumption, certain medications (drug-induced hepatitis), autoimmune conditions, metabolic disorders, or exposure to toxins and chemicals.</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The symptoms of hepatitis can vary depending on the type of hepatitis and the individual&#39;s overall health. Some common symptoms include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue and weakness</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abdominal pain or discomfort</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Jaundice (yellowing of the skin and eyes)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Loss of appetite</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Nausea and vomiting</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Dark urine</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pale stools</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Joint pain</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fever</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Enlarged liver or spleen</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Itching</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">However, it is important to note that some individuals, especially in the early stages of hepatitis, may not exhibit any noticeable symptoms. This makes regular testing and screening important, especially for those at risk.</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Diagnosing hepatitis involves a combination of medical history, physical examination, and diagnostic tests. These may include:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blood tests: Blood tests are used to detect the presence of viral antigens or antibodies, measure liver enzyme levels, and assess liver function.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Imaging tests: Imaging techniques such as ultrasound, CT scan, or MRI may be used to evaluate the liver&#39;s size, structure, and any signs of liver damage.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Liver biopsy: In some cases, a small sample of liver tissue may be obtained through a biopsy procedure to assess the extent of liver damage and determine the cause of hepatitis.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The treatment for hepatitis depends on the underlying cause and type of hepatitis.</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Viral hepatitis: Hepatitis A and E typically resolve on their own with supportive care. Hepatitis B and C may require antiviral medications to suppress viral replication and reduce liver inflammation. Vaccines are available for hepatitis A and B to prevent infection.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Autoimmune hepatitis: Immunosuppressive medications are prescribed to manage autoimmune hepatitis and reduce liver inflammation.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Drug-induced hepatitis: Stopping the causative medication and supportive care are typically the main treatments.</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">For all types of hepatitis, it is important to manage symptoms, maintain proper nutrition, avoid alcohol and substances that may further damage the liver, and seek regular medical follow-ups to monitor liver function and evaluate treatment response.</p>', 'Hepatitis.png'),
(29, 3, 'Cirrhosis', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Cirrhosis:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cirrhosis is a chronic and progressive liver disease characterized by the replacement of healthy liver tissue with scar tissue. This scarring disrupts the normal structure and function of the liver, impairing its ability to perform essential functions, such as detoxification, metabolism, and synthesis of important proteins. Cirrhosis is often a result of long-term liver damage caused by various factors, including chronic viral hepatitis, excessive alcohol consumption, fatty liver disease, autoimmune liver diseases, and certain inherited disorders.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Here is a comprehensive description of cirrhosis:</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes and Risk Factors:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The most common causes of cirrhosis include:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chronic viral hepatitis: Hepatitis B, hepatitis C, and, less commonly, hepatitis D can lead to chronic liver inflammation and, over time, progress to cirrhosis.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Excessive alcohol consumption: Long-term and heavy alcohol consumption can cause alcoholic cirrhosis. The risk is higher in individuals who consume alcohol in excessive quantities or over an extended period.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD) and non-alcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH): These conditions are characterized by the accumulation of fat in the liver, which can progress to inflammation and cirrhosis in some individuals.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Autoimmune liver diseases: Conditions such as autoimmune hepatitis, primary biliary cholangitis (PBC), and primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC) can cause chronic inflammation and cirrhosis.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Genetic and metabolic disorders: Certain inherited disorders, such as Wilson&#39;s disease, hemochromatosis, alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency, and glycogen storage diseases, can lead to cirrhosis.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chronic bile duct obstruction: Prolonged blockage of the bile ducts due to conditions like primary biliary cholangitis, primary sclerosing cholangitis, or bile duct strictures can cause cirrhosis.</p> 	</li> </ol> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> In the early stages, cirrhosis may not cause noticeable symptoms. As the disease progresses, the following symptoms and complications may occur:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue and weakness</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Jaundice (yellowing of the skin and eyes)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Itching</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Loss of appetite and weight loss</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Nausea and vomiting</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abdominal pain or discomfort</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abdominal swelling (ascites)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Swelling of the legs and ankles (edema)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Easy bruising and bleeding</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Spider-like blood vessels on the skin (spider angiomas)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Mental confusion or changes in behavior (hepatic encephalopathy)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Increased sensitivity to medications and toxins</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hormonal imbalances and symptoms in men (e.g., reduced libido, breast enlargement) and women (e.g., irregular menstrual periods, infertility)</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Complications:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Cirrhosis can lead to various complications, including:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Portal hypertension: The scarring in the liver can increase pressure within the portal vein, leading to the development of enlarged veins (varices) in the esophagus and stomach. These varices are prone to bleeding, which can be life-threatening.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Ascites: Fluid accumulation in the abdomen can cause swelling and discomfort.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hepatic encephalopathy: Accumulation of toxins in the blood, such as ammonia, can affect brain function, leading to confusion, cognitive impairment, and even coma.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Liver cancer: Cirrhosis increases the risk of developing liver cancer (hepatocellular carcinoma).</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Liver failure: In advanced stages, cirrhosis can progress to liver failure, where the liver can no longer perform its vital functions.</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Diagnosing cirrhosis involves a combination of medical history, physical examination, laboratory tests, imaging studies, and sometimes a liver biopsy. These may include:</p>', 'Cirrhosis.png');
