(30, 3, 'Diverticulitis', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diverticulitis:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Diverticulitis is a condition characterized by inflammation or infection of small pouches (diverticula) that develop along the walls of the digestive tract, typically in the large intestine (colon). Diverticula form when weak spots in the intestinal wall bulge outward. When these pouches become inflamed or infected, it can lead to various symptoms and complications.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Here is a comprehensive description of diverticulitis:</p>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes and Risk Factors:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The exact cause of diverticulitis is not fully understood, but it is believed to occur when stool and bacteria become trapped in the diverticula, leading to inflammation or infection. Several factors may contribute to the development of diverticula and the risk of diverticulitis, including:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Age: The risk of diverticulitis increases with age, and it is more commonly seen in individuals over the age of 40.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Diet: A diet low in fiber and high in refined foods may increase the risk of diverticulitis. Insufficient fiber intake can lead to harder and smaller stools, which can contribute to the development of diverticula.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lack of physical activity: A sedentary lifestyle and lack of regular exercise may increase the risk of diverticulitis.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Genetics: There may be a genetic component that increases the likelihood of developing diverticula and diverticulitis.</p> 	</li> </ol> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Diverticulitis can cause a range of symptoms, which may vary in severity. Common symptoms include:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abdominal pain: The most common symptom of diverticulitis is persistent or sudden onset of abdominal pain, usually on the left side of the lower abdomen. The pain may be sharp, cramping, or constant.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Changes in bowel habits: Diverticulitis can cause changes in bowel movements, such as diarrhea or constipation.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fever and chills: In cases of infection, fever and chills may be present.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Nausea and vomiting: Some individuals with diverticulitis may experience nausea and vomiting.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abdominal tenderness: The abdomen may feel tender to the touch, particularly in the area affected by diverticulitis.</p> 	</li> </ol> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Complications:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Diverticulitis can lead to various complications, including:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abscess: An infected diverticulum can develop into an abscess, which is a localized collection of pus. This may cause persistent pain and require drainage or surgical intervention.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fistula formation: In rare cases, an abnormal connection (fistula) may develop between the colon and nearby organs, such as the bladder or the skin.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Intestinal obstruction: Inflammation and scarring can narrow the intestine, leading to partial or complete blockage of the bowel.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Peritonitis: If an infected diverticulum ruptures, it can cause an infection in the lining of the abdominal cavity (peritonitis), which is a serious and potentially life-threatening condition.</p> 	</li> </ol> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis and Treatment:</h3> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Diagnosing diverticulitis typically involves a combination of medical history, physical examination, and diagnostic tests, which may include:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blood tests: Blood tests can help determine if there is an infection and evaluate overall health.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Imaging tests: Imaging techniques such as computed tomography (CT) scan or ultrasound may be used to visualize the affected area and assess the extent of inflammation or complications.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Stool sample analysis: A stool sample may be tested to rule out other possible causes of symptoms, such as infections.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Treatment for diverticulitis depends on the severity of the condition. Mild cases may be treated with conservative measures, including:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Resting the bowel by following a clear liquid diet.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Taking oral antibiotics to treat infection.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pain management with</li> </ul>', 'Diverticulitis.png'),
(31, 4, 'Diabetes mellitus', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diabetes mellitus:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Diabetes mellitus is a chronic metabolic disorder characterized by high blood sugar levels over a prolonged period. There are several types of diabetes mellitus, each with its own underlying causes and characteristics. The main types include type 1 diabetes, type 2 diabetes, and gestational diabetes. </p>  <ol> 	<li> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Here&#39;s a description of each type:</h3>	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Type 1 Diabetes: This form of diabetes is an autoimmune disease in which the immune system mistakenly attacks and destroys the insulin-producing cells in the pancreas. As a result, the body cannot produce enough insulin, leading to high blood sugar levels. Type 1 diabetes usually develops in childhood or adolescence, but it can occur at any age. People with type 1 diabetes require lifelong insulin therapy to manage their blood sugar levels.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Type 2 Diabetes: Type 2 diabetes is the most common form of diabetes, accounting for the majority of cases. It occurs when the body becomes resistant to the effects of insulin or fails to produce enough insulin to regulate blood sugar levels effectively. Type 2 diabetes is often associated with lifestyle factors such as obesity, sedentary lifestyle, and poor dietary choices. It typically develops in adulthood, although it is increasingly diagnosed in children and adolescents due to the rise in childhood obesity. Initially, lifestyle modifications such as dietary changes, exercise, and weight loss may be sufficient to manage type 2 diabetes. However, some individuals may also require oral medications or insulin therapy.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Gestational Diabetes: Gestational diabetes occurs during pregnancy and affects some women who have not previously had diabetes. It is usually temporary and resolves after childbirth. Hormonal changes during pregnancy can lead to insulin resistance, resulting in high blood sugar levels. Gestational diabetes requires careful monitoring and management to ensure the well-being of both the mother and the baby. Women who have had gestational diabetes are at an increased risk of developing type 2 diabetes later in life.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Common symptoms of diabetes mellitus, regardless of type, include frequent urination, excessive thirst, unexplained weight loss, increased hunger, fatigue, blurred vision, slow-healing wounds, and recurrent infections. However, some individuals with type 2 diabetes may not experience noticeable symptoms in the early stages.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">If left unmanaged, diabetes mellitus can lead to various complications affecting the heart, blood vessels, kidneys, eyes, and nerves. Therefore, it is essential for individuals with diabetes to maintain regular medical check-ups, follow a healthy lifestyle, monitor blood sugar levels, and adhere to prescribed treatment plans to minimize the risk of complications and lead a fulfilling life. It is advisable to consult with a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis, personalized advice, and appropriate management strategies for diabetes mellitus.</p>', 'Diabetes mellitus.png'),
(32, 4, 'Thyroid disease', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Thyroid disease:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Thyroid disease refers to a group of disorders that affect the thyroid gland, a small butterfly-shaped gland located in the front of the neck. The thyroid gland plays a crucial role in regulating various bodily functions by producing hormones that help control metabolism. There are several types of thyroid diseases, including:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hypothyroidism: Hypothyroidism occurs when the thyroid gland does not produce enough thyroid hormones. This condition can be caused by an autoimmune disease called Hashimoto&#39;s thyroiditis, thyroid surgery, radiation therapy, certain medications, or a congenital condition. Symptoms of hypothyroidism may include fatigue, weight gain, cold intolerance, dry skin, constipation, depression, and muscle weakness. Treatment typically involves taking synthetic thyroid hormone medication to replace the deficient hormones.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hyperthyroidism: Hyperthyroidism is the opposite of hypothyroidism and occurs when the thyroid gland produces an excess of thyroid hormones. The most common cause of hyperthyroidism is an autoimmune disorder known as Graves&#39; disease. Symptoms may include weight loss, increased appetite, rapid heartbeat, anxiety, irritability, heat intolerance, trembling hands, and difficulty sleeping. Treatment options include medications to regulate thyroid hormone levels, radioactive iodine therapy to destroy part of the thyroid gland, or thyroid surgery to remove the gland.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Thyroid Nodules: Thyroid nodules are growths or lumps that form within the thyroid gland. Most nodules are benign (non-cancerous) and do not cause symptoms. However, some nodules can be cancerous or produce excess thyroid hormones, leading to hyperthyroidism. Treatment depends on the nature of the nodule, and options may include monitoring, medication, radioactive iodine therapy, or surgical removal.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Thyroid Cancer: Thyroid cancer is the malignant (cancerous) growth of cells in the thyroid gland. It is usually detected as a nodule or lump in the neck. Thyroid cancer is relatively uncommon but has a high cure rate if diagnosed and treated early. Treatment may involve surgery to remove part or all of the thyroid gland, radioactive iodine therapy, and sometimes radiation therapy or targeted drug therapy.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Thyroiditis: Thyroiditis refers to inflammation of the thyroid gland, which can cause temporary thyroid hormone imbalances. There are several types of thyroiditis, including Hashimoto&#39;s thyroiditis (an autoimmune condition), postpartum thyroiditis (occurs after childbirth), and subacute thyroiditis (viral infection). Symptoms and treatment depend on the specific type of thyroiditis.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It&#39;s important to note that the symptoms and treatment options can vary depending on the specific thyroid disease and individual circumstances. If you suspect you may have a thyroid condition, it is recommended to consult with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis, evaluation, and personalized treatment.</p>', 'Thyroid disease.png'),
(33, 4, 'Adrenal gland disorders', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Adrenal gland disorders:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Adrenal gland disorders refer to a group of medical conditions that affect the adrenal glands, which are small triangular-shaped glands located on top of the kidneys. The adrenal glands produce essential hormones that help regulate various bodily functions and respond to stress. There are several types of adrenal gland disorders, including:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Adrenal Insufficiency: Adrenal insufficiency occurs when the adrenal glands do not produce enough of the hormones cortisol and, in some cases, aldosterone. This can be caused by primary adrenal insufficiency (Addison&#39;s disease), which is usually due to autoimmune destruction of the adrenal glands, or secondary adrenal insufficiency, which is often caused by a malfunction of the pituitary gland or hypothalamus. Symptoms may include fatigue, weakness, weight loss, low blood pressure, abdominal pain, salt cravings, and darkening of the skin. Treatment involves hormone replacement therapy to restore adequate hormone levels.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cushing&#39;s Syndrome: Cushing&#39;s syndrome is a disorder characterized by an excess production of cortisol, either due to excessive cortisol production by the adrenal glands (adrenal Cushing&#39;s syndrome) or prolonged exposure to high levels of corticosteroid medications (exogenous Cushing&#39;s syndrome). Symptoms may include weight gain, particularly in the upper body and face, thinning of the skin, easy bruising, muscle weakness, high blood pressure, and emotional changes. Treatment depends on the cause and may involve surgery, medication, or reducing corticosteroid medication doses under medical supervision.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Congenital Adrenal Hyperplasia (CAH): CAH is a genetic disorder in which the adrenal glands do not produce enough cortisol and sometimes aldosterone. It is usually caused by enzyme deficiencies that lead to the overproduction of androgens (male hormones). CAH can present with different degrees of severity and may cause ambiguous genitalia in females. Treatment aims to replace deficient hormones and manage specific symptoms.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Adrenal Tumors: Adrenal tumors can be benign (adenomas) or malignant (adrenal cancer). They can originate from the adrenal glands (primary adrenal tumors) or spread to the adrenal glands from other sites (metastatic tumors). Adrenal tumors can affect hormone production, leading to conditions such as adrenal adenomas, pheochromocytomas, or adrenocortical carcinoma. Treatment options depend on the type of tumor and may involve surgery, radiation therapy, or chemotherapy.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pheochromocytoma: Pheochromocytomas are rare tumors that develop in the adrenal medulla and produce excessive amounts of adrenaline and noradrenaline hormones. Symptoms may include high blood pressure, rapid heartbeat, palpitations, sweating, anxiety, and headaches. Surgical removal of the tumor is the primary treatment.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">These are some of the common adrenal gland disorders, but there are other rarer conditions that can affect the adrenal glands as well. It&#39;s important to consult with a healthcare professional for an accurate diagnosis, proper evaluation, and appropriate management of adrenal gland disorders. Treatment options may vary depending on the specific condition and individual circumstances.</p>', 'Adrenal gland disorders.png'),
(34, 4, 'Pituitary gland disorders', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Pituitary gland disorders:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pituitary gland disorders refer to medical conditions that affect the pituitary gland, a small gland located at the base of the brain. The pituitary gland is often referred to as the &quot;master gland&quot; because it produces and regulates several hormones that control various functions in the body. Here are descriptions of some common pituitary gland disorders:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pituitary Tumors: Pituitary tumors are abnormal growths that can be benign (non-cancerous) or, in rare cases, malignant (cancerous). Most pituitary tumors are non-cancerous and are classified as adenomas. Depending on the size and type of tumor, it can affect hormone production and cause specific symptoms. The symptoms may include headaches, vision problems, hormonal imbalances, fatigue, and changes in menstrual cycles or sexual function. Treatment options include observation, medication, surgery, and radiation therapy, depending on the characteristics of the tumor and its impact on hormone production.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pituitary Hormone Deficiencies: Pituitary hormone deficiencies occur when the pituitary gland does not produce or release adequate amounts of one or more hormones. This can be caused by various factors, such as pituitary tumors, pituitary surgery, radiation therapy, or certain genetic conditions. Common hormone deficiencies include growth hormone deficiency (GHD), thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) deficiency, adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) deficiency, and gonadotropin deficiencies (luteinizing hormone and follicle-stimulating hormone). Treatment typically involves hormone replacement therapy to restore adequate hormone levels and manage symptoms.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pituitary Hypersecretion Disorders: Pituitary hypersecretion disorders refer to conditions in which the pituitary gland produces excessive amounts of one or more hormones. Examples include:</p>  	<ul> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Acromegaly: Acromegaly is caused by the overproduction of growth hormone (GH) in adulthood, usually due to a benign pituitary tumor. It leads to the enlargement of body tissues, bone overgrowth, and other physical changes. Treatment may involve surgery to remove the tumor, radiation therapy, or medications to regulate GH levels.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Prolactinoma: Prolactinomas are benign tumors that cause the overproduction of prolactin hormone, resulting in the production of breast milk (galactorrhea), irregular menstrual cycles, infertility, and decreased libido. Medications are commonly used to reduce prolactin levels and manage symptoms. In some cases, surgery or radiation therapy may be required.</p> 		</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pituitary Apoplexy: Pituitary apoplexy is a rare but serious condition that occurs when there is bleeding or impaired blood supply to the pituitary gland, often associated with a pituitary tumor. Symptoms may include severe headache, visual disturbances, hormonal deficiencies, and neurological symptoms. It is considered a medical emergency, and immediate medical attention is required.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">These are some of the common pituitary gland disorders, but there are other rare conditions that can affect the pituitary gland as well. The diagnosis and management of pituitary gland disorders require medical evaluation, hormone level testing, imaging studies, and consultation with specialists such as endocrinologists or neurosurgeons. Treatment options depend on the specific condition, its impact on hormone production, and individual factors.</p>', 'Pituitary gland disorders.png'),
(35, 4, 'Hypoglycemia', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Hypoglycemia:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hypoglycemia is a condition characterized by low blood sugar levels, typically defined as a blood glucose concentration below 70 mg/dL (3.9 mmol/L). It occurs when there is an imbalance between the amount of glucose in the bloodstream and the body&#39;s need for it. Hypoglycemia can be a primary condition or a complication of other underlying health conditions or medications. Here&#39;s a description of hypoglycemia:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Causes: Hypoglycemia can occur due to various factors, including:</p>  	<ul> 		<li> 	<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diabetes:</h3>	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> People with diabetes, especially those on insulin or certain diabetes medications, are at risk of hypoglycemia. This can happen if too much insulin is taken, meals are skipped or delayed, or if physical activity increases without adjusting medication or food intake.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Non-Diabetic Hypoglycemia: Some individuals who do not have diabetes may experience hypoglycemia due to other causes such as excessive alcohol consumption, certain medications (e.g., those used to treat certain cancers), hormonal deficiencies, liver or kidney disorders, or pancreatic tumors.</p> 		</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3>	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The symptoms of hypoglycemia can vary depending on the severity and individual response. Common signs and symptoms include:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Shakiness or tremors</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Sweating</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Palpitations or a fast heartbeat</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue or weakness</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hunger</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Irritability or mood changes</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Dizziness or lightheadedness</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Confusion or difficulty concentrating</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Headaches</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blurred vision</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Slurred speech</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Seizures (in severe cases)</li></ul> </li> <li> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Hypoglycemia is typically diagnosed through blood tests that measure blood glucose levels during episodes of symptoms. A healthcare professional may also evaluate the medical history, perform a physical examination, and order additional tests to identify the underlying cause of hypoglycemia.</p> 	</li> 	<li> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment: </h3>	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The treatment of hypoglycemia depends on the cause and severity. In cases of mild to moderate hypoglycemia, consuming a fast-acting source of carbohydrates such as fruit juice, glucose tablets, or a sugary snack can quickly raise blood sugar levels. For individuals with diabetes, regular monitoring of blood glucose levels and adjusting medications, meals, and physical activity can help prevent hypoglycemic episodes. In severe cases or if the person is unable to eat or drink, glucagon (a hormone that raises blood sugar levels) may be administered via injection.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It is important for individuals who experience recurrent or severe hypoglycemia to consult with a healthcare professional to determine the underlying cause and develop an appropriate management plan. Preventive measures, such as regular meals and snacks, balanced nutrition, appropriate medication use, and awareness of individual triggers, can help minimize the risk of hypoglycemia.</p>', 'Hypoglycemia.png'),
(36, 4, 'Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS)', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS):</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is a hormonal disorder that affects women of reproductive age. It is a common condition that can cause a range of symptoms and reproductive abnormalities. Here&#39;s a description of PCOS:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hormonal Imbalance: PCOS is characterized by hormonal imbalances, particularly an excess production of androgens (male hormones) by the ovaries. This hormonal imbalance disrupts the normal functioning of the ovaries and leads to the development of small cysts on the ovaries, hence the term &quot;polycystic.&quot;</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Symptoms: The symptoms of PCOS can vary from person to person and may include:</p>  	<ul> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Irregular or absent menstrual periods: Women with PCOS may experience irregular menstrual cycles or have long gaps between periods.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Excess hair growth (hirsutism): Due to the elevated androgen levels, some women may develop excess hair growth on the face, chest, abdomen, or other areas of the body.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Acne: Increased androgen levels can contribute to the development of acne or oily skin.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Weight gain: Many women with PCOS struggle with weight gain or have difficulty losing weight.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hair loss: Thinning of the hair or male-pattern baldness may occur in some cases.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Skin darkening: Areas of the skin, such as the neck, groin, or underarms, may appear darker than usual (acanthosis nigricans).</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fertility problems: PCOS is a leading cause of infertility in women due to irregular ovulation or failure to ovulate.</p> 		</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Health Risks: PCOS is associated with an increased risk of several health complications, including:</p>  	<ul> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Insulin resistance and type 2 diabetes: Many women with PCOS have insulin resistance, which can lead to high blood sugar levels and an increased risk of developing type 2 diabetes.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">High blood pressure and cardiovascular disease: Women with PCOS have a higher likelihood of developing high blood pressure, elevated cholesterol levels, and an increased risk of heart disease and stroke.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Sleep apnea: PCOS is linked to an increased risk of sleep apnea, a sleep disorder characterized by breathing interruptions during sleep.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Endometrial cancer: Prolonged periods of irregular or absent menstruation can lead to an overgrowth of the uterine lining (endometrium), increasing the risk of endometrial cancer.</p> 		</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Diagnosis and Treatment: PCOS is diagnosed based on a combination of symptoms, medical history, physical examination, and blood tests to evaluate hormone levels. There is no cure for PCOS, but the symptoms can be managed. Treatment options may include:</p>  	<ul> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lifestyle modifications: This includes adopting a healthy diet, regular exercise, and weight management to improve insulin sensitivity and regulate hormone levels.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Birth control pills, progestin therapy, and anti-androgen medications may be prescribed to regulate menstrual cycles, reduce androgen levels, and manage symptoms.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fertility treatments: If fertility is a concern, medications such as clomiphene citrate or assisted reproductive technologies (ART) may be used to induce ovulation and improve the chances of pregnancy.</p> 		</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Long-Term Management: Long-term management of PCOS focuses on regular health check-ups, monitoring of hormone levels, managing associated health risks, and addressing specific concerns such as acne, hirsutism, and hair loss.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It&#39;s important for women with PCOS to work closely with healthcare professionals, such as gynecologists or endocrinologists, to develop an individualized treatment plan and address any concerns or complications associated with the condition.</p>', 'Polycystic ovary syndrome.png'),
(37, 4, 'Menopause', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Menopause:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Menopause is a natural biological process that marks the end of a woman&#39;s reproductive years. It is defined as the permanent cessation of menstrual periods for at least 12 consecutive months. Menopause typically occurs in women between the ages of 45 and 55, with the average age being around 51. Here&#39;s a description of menopause:</p>  <ol> 	<li> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Perimenopause:</h3>	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The transition to menopause is known as perimenopause, which can start several years before menopause itself. During this phase, the ovaries gradually produce less estrogen and progesterone, leading to irregular menstrual cycles and various symptoms. Perimenopause can last for a few months to several years.</p> 	</li> 	<li> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3>	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Menopause is associated with a wide range of physical and emotional symptoms, which can vary among women. Common symptoms include:</p>  	<ul> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Irregular periods: Menstrual cycles may become shorter or longer, and bleeding may be heavier or lighter than usual.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hot flashes: Sudden, intense feelings of heat that can cause flushing, sweating, and a rapid heartbeat. Hot flashes can last from a few seconds to several minutes.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Night sweats: Hot flashes that occur during sleep, leading to excessive sweating and disrupted sleep patterns.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Vaginal dryness and discomfort: Decreased estrogen levels can result in thinning and drying of the vaginal tissues, leading to vaginal dryness, itching, and discomfort during sexual intercourse.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Sleep disturbances: Insomnia, sleep fragmentation, or frequent waking during the night may occur.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Mood changes: Hormonal fluctuations can cause mood swings, irritability, anxiety, and feelings of sadness or depression.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Changes in sexual function: Decreased estrogen levels may affect libido, vaginal lubrication, and sexual satisfaction.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Weight gain and changes in body composition: Many women may experience weight gain, particularly in the abdominal area, as well as changes in body fat distribution.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Other symptoms: Fatigue, difficulty concentrating, joint and muscle aches, headaches, and changes in hair and skin may also occur.</p> 		</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Health Risks:</h3>	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Menopause is associated with an increased risk of certain health conditions, including:</p>  	<ul> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Osteoporosis: The decline in estrogen levels during menopause can lead to bone loss and increase the risk of osteoporosis, a condition characterized by weakened bones and an increased risk of fractures.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cardiovascular disease: The risk of heart disease, including heart attacks and stroke, increases after menopause.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Urinary incontinence: Some women may experience an increased risk of urinary incontinence or urinary tract infections due to changes in the urinary system.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Changes in cholesterol levels: Menopause can lead to unfavorable changes in cholesterol levels, including an increase in LDL (bad) cholesterol and a decrease in HDL (good) cholesterol.</p> 		</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Management:</h3>	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> The management of menopause involves both lifestyle modifications and, in some cases, medical interventions. Treatment options may include:</p>  	<ul> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hormone therapy: Estrogen therapy or combined estrogen-progestin therapy can be used to relieve menopausal symptoms such as hot flashes, vaginal dryness, and bone loss. Hormone therapy is tailored to individual needs and medical history.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Non-hormonal medications: Certain medications such as selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) or serotonin-norepinephrine reuptake inhibitors (SNRIs) may be prescribed to help manage hot flashes and mood symptoms.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lifestyle changes: Regular exercise, a healthy diet rich in calcium and vitamin D, stress management, and adequate sleep can help alleviate symptoms and reduce the risk of associated health conditions.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Vaginal lubricants and moisturizers: Over-the-counter or prescription</p> 		</li> 	</ul> 	</li> </ol>', 'Menopause.png'),
(38, 4, 'Osteoporosis', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Osteoporosis:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Osteoporosis is a condition characterized by weakened bones that are more prone to fractures. It occurs when the body loses too much bone, makes too little bone, or both. Osteoporosis is often called a &quot;silent disease&quot; because it progresses without symptoms until a fracture occurs. Here&#39;s a description of osteoporosis:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bone Density and Structure: Bones are composed of a dense outer layer called cortical bone and a spongy inner structure known as trabecular bone. In osteoporosis, the bone density and quality are reduced, making the bones fragile and susceptible to fractures.</p> 	</li> 	<li> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Risk Factors:</h3>	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Several factors contribute to the development of osteoporosis, including:</p>  	<ul> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Age: The risk of osteoporosis increases with age as bone mass naturally declines over time.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Gender: Women are more prone to osteoporosis than men, especially after menopause, due to the decrease in estrogen levels.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hormonal changes: Low levels of sex hormones, such as estrogen in women and testosterone in men, can contribute to bone loss.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Family history: Having a family history of osteoporosis or fractures increases the risk.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lifestyle factors: Lack of physical activity, smoking, excessive alcohol consumption, and a diet low in calcium and vitamin D can increase the risk of osteoporosis.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medical conditions: Certain medical conditions, such as rheumatoid arthritis, celiac disease, and hormonal disorders, can increase the risk of osteoporosis.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Long-term use of certain medications, including glucocorticoids (steroids) and some anti-seizure medications, can weaken bones and increase the risk of fractures.</p> 		</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms:</h3>	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Osteoporosis itself does not cause symptoms until a fracture occurs. Common sites for fractures related to osteoporosis include the spine, hip, wrist, and other bones. Fractures can cause pain, limited mobility, height loss, and a hunched or stooped posture.</p> 	</li> 	<li> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3>	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Osteoporosis is diagnosed using a bone mineral density (BMD) test, typically measured by a dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry (DXA) scan. The results are compared to the average peak bone density of a young adult to determine the T-score, which indicates the degree of bone loss and the diagnosis of osteoporosis or its precursor, osteopenia.</p> 	</li> 	<li> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment and Management: </h3>	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The goals of osteoporosis treatment and management include reducing the risk of fractures, relieving symptoms, and improving overall bone health. Treatment options may include:</p>  	<ul> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lifestyle modifications: Regular weight-bearing exercise, a balanced diet rich in calcium and vitamin D, smoking cessation, limited alcohol consumption, and fall prevention strategies can help maintain bone health and reduce the risk of fractures.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Several medications are available to slow down bone loss, increase bone density, and reduce fracture risk. These may include bisphosphonates, selective estrogen receptor modulators (SERMs), hormone therapy, denosumab, and teriparatide.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fall prevention: Taking steps to prevent falls, such as removing tripping hazards, using assistive devices, improving lighting, and exercising for balance and strength, can help prevent fractures.</p> 		</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Osteoporosis Management in Men: While osteoporosis is more common in women, it can also affect men. Men with risk factors or symptoms of osteoporosis should undergo evaluation and may require similar treatment approaches.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Regular monitoring, follow-up appointments, and adherence to treatment recommendations are crucial in managing osteoporosis effectively. It is essential to consult with a healthcare professional, such as an endocrinologist or a rheumatologist, to determine the appropriate management plan based on individual circumstances.</p>', 'Osteoporosis.png'),
(39, 5, 'Migraine', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Migraine:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Migraineis a type of headache that is often accompanied by symptoms such as:</p>\n<ol> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Severe head pain, usually on one side of the head</li><li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Sensitivity to light, sound, and smells</li><li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Nausea and vomiting</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blurred vision</li><li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lightheadedness or dizziness</li> </ol>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The exact cause of migraines is not fully understood, but they are thought to be related to changes in brain activity and the blood vessels in the brain. Migraines may also be triggered by certain factors such as stress, certain foods, changes in sleep patterns, and hormonal changes.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Treatment for migraines typically includes medications to reduce the severity and frequency of migraines and to alleviate symptoms. Non-pharmacological treatments such as relaxation techniques, physical therapy, and lifestyle changes may also be helpful in managing migraines.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Migraines can last anywhere from a few hours to a few days, and they can be very debilitating. Some people experience an aura before a migraine, which can include visual disturbances such as flashing lights or blind spots.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Migraine with aura: This type of migraine is preceded by visual or other sensory disturbances known as an aura.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Migraine with brainstem aura: This type of migraine is also known as a basilar migraine, and it is characterized by aura symptoms that affect the brainstem rather than the cortex.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chronic migraine: A person is diagnosed with chronic migraine if they have 15 or more headache days per month for at least three months, and at least eight of those days meet the criteria for a migraine.</p>', 'Migraine.png'),
(40, 5, 'Epilepsy', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Epilepsy:</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Epilepsy is a neurological disorder characterized by recurrent, unprovoked seizures. Seizures are sudden, abnormal electrical disturbances in the brain that can cause a wide range of symptoms. Here&#39;s a description of epilepsy:</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Seizures:</h3>	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Seizures are the hallmark of epilepsy. They can vary in their manifestation, duration, and intensity. There are several types of seizures, including:</p> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Generalized seizures: These seizures involve both sides of the brain and can cause loss of consciousness, muscle rigidity, convulsions, and abnormal movements.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Focal seizures: Formerly known as partial seizures, these seizures originate in one specific area of the brain and can cause localized symptoms such as muscle twitching, sensory changes, and altered consciousness.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Absence seizures: These seizures are characterized by a brief loss of awareness and staring spells, typically lasting a few seconds.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Tonic-clonic seizures: Also known as grand mal seizures, these seizures involve a loss of consciousness, stiffening of the body (tonic phase), followed by jerking movements (clonic phase), and possible loss of bladder or bowel control.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Other seizure types: There are additional seizure types, such as myoclonic seizures (sudden jerking or twitching of muscles), atonic seizures (sudden loss of muscle tone and postural control), and focal aware seizures (formerly known as simple partial seizures).</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Causes:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Epilepsy can have various causes, but in many cases, the exact cause is unknown. Some common causes and risk factors include:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Genetic factors: Certain genetic mutations or family history of epilepsy can increase the risk.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Brain conditions: Brain tumors, stroke, traumatic brain injury, infections (such as meningitis or encephalitis), developmental disorders (such as cerebral palsy), and abnormal brain structures can contribute to epilepsy.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Prenatal factors: Exposure to prenatal factors like maternal drug use, infections, or inadequate oxygen supply to the baby&#39;s brain can increase the risk.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Developmental disorders: Some developmental disorders, such as autism spectrum disorder or neurofibromatosis, can be associated with epilepsy.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis:</h3>	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Diagnosing epilepsy involves a comprehensive evaluation, including a detailed medical history, physical examination, and various diagnostic tests. These tests may include:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Electroencephalogram (EEG): This test records the brain&#39;s electrical activity to detect abnormal patterns that may indicate epilepsy.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Imaging tests: Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) or computed tomography (CT) scans can help identify structural abnormalities or brain lesions.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blood tests: Blood tests may be performed to identify any underlying medical conditions or genetic factors.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\"> Epilepsy is typically managed with medications, but other treatment options may be considered depending on the individual&#39;s condition. Treatment options include:</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Antiepileptic medications: The primary treatment for epilepsy involves medications that help control seizures. The specific medication and dosage depend on the seizure type and individual response.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lifestyle modifications: Certain lifestyle changes can help manage epilepsy, such as maintaining regular sleep patterns, managing stress, avoiding triggers, and following a balanced diet.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Surgical interventions: In some cases, surgery may be considered to remove the area of the brain responsible for triggering seizures. This option is typically explored when seizures cannot be controlled with medications or when the affected brain area can be safely removed without significant functional loss.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Vagus nerve stimulation (VNS): VNS involves implanting a device that stimulates the vagus nerve to help reduce seizures.</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Ketogenic diet: This high-fat, low-carbohydrate diet may be recommended for some individuals with epilepsy, particularly children,</p>', 'Epilepsy.png');
