(41, 5, 'Parkinson disease', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Parkinson&#39;s disease (PD)</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Parkinson&#39;s disease (PD) is a chronic and progressive neurological disorder that affects movement and motor control. It is named after James Parkinson, the British physician who first described its symptoms in 1817. Parkinson&#39;s disease primarily results from the gradual degeneration of specific neurons in the brain, particularly those responsible for producing a chemical called dopamine.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The hallmark symptoms of Parkinson&#39;s disease are often referred to as &quot;motor symptoms.&quot; These include:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Tremors: Involuntary shaking or trembling, usually starting in the hands, fingers, or thumbs. Tremors are often present while the person is at rest and decrease or disappear during voluntary movement.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Rigidity: Stiffness and resistance to movement in the muscles, making it difficult to initiate or control movements. This can lead to a decreased range of motion and muscle pain.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bradykinesia: Slowness of movement, causing a delay in initiating and executing voluntary movements. It can result in difficulties with everyday activities such as walking, getting up from a chair, or even simple tasks like buttoning a shirt.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Postural instability: Impaired balance and coordination, leading to a tendency to stoop, shuffle, or experience frequent falls. Maintaining an upright posture becomes challenging, and the risk of injury increases.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">In addition to motor symptoms, Parkinson&#39;s disease can also manifest non-motor symptoms, which may appear before the onset of motor symptoms or develop later in the course of the disease. These non-motor symptoms include:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cognitive changes: Problems with memory, attention, and executive functions, such as multitasking, planning, and problem-solving. Some individuals may develop dementia in the later stages of the disease.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Mood disorders: Depression, anxiety, and apathy are common in Parkinson&#39;s patients. They may experience changes in mood, sleep disturbances, and a loss of motivation.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Autonomic dysfunction: Dysfunction of the autonomic nervous system can lead to various symptoms such as constipation, urinary problems, excessive sweating, and low blood pressure.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Sleep disturbances: Parkinson&#39;s disease can cause sleep disorders like insomnia, restless legs syndrome, and REM sleep behavior disorder, where individuals act out their dreams.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The exact cause of Parkinson&#39;s disease is not yet fully understood, but it is believed to result from a combination of genetic and environmental factors. The primary risk factor is age, with the majority of cases occurring in people over the age of 60. However, a small percentage of cases, known as early-onset Parkinson&#39;s, can occur in individuals younger than 50.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">There is currently no cure for Parkinson&#39;s disease, but several treatment options are available to manage its symptoms and improve the quality of life for affected individuals. These treatments may include medications to increase dopamine levels, physical therapy, occupational therapy, speech therapy, and in some cases, deep brain stimulation (DBS) surgery.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It&#39;s important for individuals with Parkinson&#39;s disease to work closely with healthcare professionals, including neurologists and movement disorder specialists, to develop a personalized treatment plan and receive ongoing care and support.</p>', 'Parkinson\'s disease.png'),
(42, 5, 'Multiple sclerosis', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Multiple sclerosis (MS)</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a chronic and unpredictable autoimmune disease that affects the central nervous system (CNS), which includes the brain and spinal cord. It is characterized by the immune system mistakenly attacking the protective covering of nerve fibers, called myelin, leading to inflammation, damage, and scarring (sclerosis) in multiple areas of the CNS.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The exact cause of multiple sclerosis is not fully understood, but it is believed to result from a combination of genetic and environmental factors. Some studies suggest that certain viruses or infections may trigger an abnormal immune response in individuals with a genetic predisposition to MS.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The symptoms of multiple sclerosis can vary widely among affected individuals and depend on the location and extent of the nerve damage. Common symptoms include:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue: A persistent feeling of exhaustion, often unrelated to physical exertion, and may interfere with daily activities.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Motor difficulties: Weakness, muscle stiffness, spasms, and problems with coordination and balance. These symptoms can affect walking, manual dexterity, and overall mobility.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Sensory changes: Numbness or tingling in the limbs, impaired sensation, and sensitivity to touch or temperature changes.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Visual disturbances: Blurred vision, double vision (diplopia), eye pain, and partial or complete loss of vision. Optic neuritis, inflammation of the optic nerve, is a common symptom of MS.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cognitive impairment: Problems with memory, attention, concentration, and information processing. Some individuals may experience difficulty with problem-solving, decision-making, and multitasking.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Emotional changes: Depression, anxiety, mood swings, and uncontrollable laughing or crying (known as pseudobulbar affect).</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bowel and bladder dysfunction: Constipation, diarrhea, difficulty urinating, frequent urination, or loss of bladder control.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Speech and swallowing difficulties: Slurred speech, difficulty articulating words, and problems with swallowing (dysphagia).</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">MS is typically diagnosed based on a combination of medical history, neurological examination, imaging tests (such as magnetic resonance imaging or MRI), and sometimes cerebrospinal fluid analysis.</p>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">There are different types of multiple sclerosis, including:</h3><ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Relapsing-remitting MS (RRMS): The most common form, characterized by unpredictable relapses (flare-ups) of new or worsening symptoms followed by periods of partial or complete recovery (remission).</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Secondary progressive MS (SPMS): Develops in individuals with an initial RRMS diagnosis. It involves a progressive worsening of symptoms with or without relapses, and fewer periods of remission.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Primary progressive MS (PPMS): A less common form where symptoms progressively worsen from the onset without distinct relapses or remissions.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Progressive-relapsing MS (PRMS): A rare form characterized by a steady worsening of symptoms along with occasional relapses and minor remissions.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">While there is currently no cure for multiple sclerosis, various treatment approaches aim to manage symptoms, slow disease progression, and improve quality of life. Medications, such as disease-modifying therapies (DMTs), are prescribed to reduce inflammation, modify the immune response, and prevent relapses or new lesions in the CNS. Rehabilitation strategies, including physical therapy, occupational therapy, and speech therapy, can help manage symptoms and improve function. Supportive care, such as assistive devices and emotional support, also plays a crucial role in managing the disease.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It&#39;s important for individuals with multiple sclerosis to work closely with healthcare professionals, particularly neurologists or MS specialists, to develop an individualized treatment plan, monitor disease progression, and address specific symptoms and needs.</p>', 'Multiple sclerosis.png'),
(43, 5, 'Alzheimer disease', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Alzheimer&#39;s disease</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Alzheimer&#39;s disease is a progressive and irreversible neurological disorder that primarily affects the brain, leading to a decline in memory, thinking abilities, and overall cognitive function. It is the most common cause of dementia, a term used to describe a range of symptoms associated with a decline in memory and cognitive abilities severe enough to interfere with daily life.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The exact cause of Alzheimer&#39;s disease is not fully understood, but it is believed to result from a combination of genetic, environmental, and lifestyle factors. The disease is characterized by the accumulation of abnormal protein deposits in the brain, including beta-amyloid plaques and tau tangles. These deposits disrupt the normal functioning of brain cells, leading to their degeneration and eventual death.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The symptoms of Alzheimer&#39;s disease generally develop slowly and worsen over time. They can vary from person to person but typically include:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Memory loss: Difficulty remembering recent events, names, and conversations. As the disease progresses, long-term memory may also be affected.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cognitive decline: Impairments in thinking abilities, such as difficulties with problem-solving, decision-making, judgment, concentration, and abstract thinking.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Language problems: Trouble finding the right words, difficulty following conversations, and challenges in expressing oneself clearly.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Disorientation: Confusion about time, place, and familiar surroundings. Individuals may get lost in previously familiar locations.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Impaired visual-spatial skills: Difficulty with tasks that involve visual perception and spatial relationships, such as judging distances or recognizing objects.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Poor judgment: Decreased ability to make sound decisions, leading to risky behaviors or financial mismanagement.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Personality and behavioral changes: Mood swings, irritability, apathy, withdrawal from social activities, and changes in personality and behavior.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Loss of initiative: Apathy and a reduced motivation to engage in activities or hobbies that were previously enjoyable.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">As Alzheimer&#39;s disease progresses, individuals may experience more severe symptoms, including severe memory loss, an inability to recognize family members and loved ones, significant communication difficulties, and a need for round-the-clock care.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Alzheimer&#39;s disease is typically diagnosed through a comprehensive assessment that includes medical history, cognitive tests, neurological examinations, and sometimes brain imaging. Currently, a definitive diagnosis can only be made after death through an examination of brain tissue during an autopsy.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">While there is no cure for Alzheimer&#39;s disease, treatment focuses on managing symptoms, slowing down disease progression, and improving quality of life. Medications may be prescribed to temporarily alleviate cognitive symptoms and manage behavioral and psychological symptoms. Additionally, non-drug interventions such as cognitive stimulation, physical exercise, and social engagement may provide some benefit.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Support from healthcare professionals, family members, and caregivers is crucial in managing the challenges associated with Alzheimer&#39;s disease. Caregivers play a vital role in providing physical and emotional support, ensuring safety, and helping with daily activities as the disease progresses.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Research into the causes, prevention, and treatment of Alzheimer&#39;s disease is ongoing, and various clinical trials are underway to explore potential therapies and interventions.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It&#39;s important for individuals with Alzheimer&#39;s disease and their caregivers to seek medical guidance, access support services, and join support groups to navigate the challenges of the disease and maintain the best possible quality of life.</p>', 'Alzheimer\'s disease.png'),
(44, 5, 'Depression', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Depression</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Depression, also known as major depressive disorder (MDD), is a common and serious mental health condition characterized by persistent feelings of sadness, low mood, or a loss of interest or pleasure in activities. It affects how a person thinks, feels, and behaves and can cause a variety of emotional and physical symptoms.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The symptoms of depression can vary from person to person, but typically include:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Persistent sadness or feelings of emptiness: Feeling down or hopeless most of the day, nearly every day. This may include feelings of worthlessness or guilt.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Loss of interest or pleasure: Losing interest in activities once enjoyed, including hobbies, socializing, or sex. A lack of motivation or enthusiasm for life may be present.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Changes in appetite or weight: Significant changes in appetite, leading to weight loss or weight gain. This may result in a loss of interest in food or using food as a means of comfort.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Sleep disturbances: Insomnia (difficulty falling asleep or staying asleep) or hypersomnia (excessive sleepiness or prolonged sleep). Sleep patterns may be disrupted, leading to fatigue and a lack of energy.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue or loss of energy: Feeling tired and lacking energy, even after minimal exertion. This can impact daily activities and overall functioning.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Feelings of worthlessness or excessive guilt: Negative self-perception, self-criticism, and feelings of guilt over past events or perceived failures. These thoughts may be exaggerated or irrational.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Difficulty concentrating or making decisions: Problems with concentration, memory, and decision-making. Individuals may experience mental fog or a slowed thought process.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Psychomotor agitation or retardation: Restlessness, pacing, or fidgeting, or conversely, slowed movements and speech.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Recurrent thoughts of death or suicide: Persistent thoughts about death, dying, or suicide, or making plans for suicide. It&#39;s important to take such thoughts seriously and seek immediate help.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The exact cause of depression is not fully understood, but it is believed to result from a combination of genetic, biological, environmental, and psychological factors. Certain life events, such as trauma, loss, or major transitions, can contribute to the onset of depression. Additionally, imbalances in brain chemicals (neurotransmitters) like serotonin, norepinephrine, and dopamine are thought to play a role in its development.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Depression can occur as a single episode, but it can also be recurrent, with multiple episodes throughout a person&#39;s lifetime. It can significantly impair daily functioning, relationships, and overall quality of life. It is essential to differentiate clinical depression from normal sadness or grief, as the symptoms of depression are more severe, persistent, and pervasive.</p>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment for depression typically involves a combination of therapies, including:</h3> <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Psychotherapy: Talk therapy, such as cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT) or interpersonal therapy (IPT), helps individuals identify and change negative thought patterns and develop healthy coping strategies.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Antidepressant medications, such as selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) or serotonin-norepinephrine reuptake inhibitors (SNRIs), may be prescribed to help regulate brain chemicals and alleviate symptoms.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lifestyle changes: Engaging in regular exercise, adopting a healthy diet, ensuring adequate sleep, and reducing stress levels can have a positive impact on depressive symptoms.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Support network: Building a strong support system, including friends, family, and support groups, can provide emotional support and understanding.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">In severe cases of depression or when other treatments are ineffective, electroconvulsive therapy (ECT) or transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) may be considered.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">If you or someone you know is experiencing symptoms of depression, it is crucial to seek professional help from a</p>', 'Depression.png'),
(45, 5, 'Anxiety disorders', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Anxiety disorders</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Anxiety disorders encompass a group of mental health conditions characterized by excessive and persistent feelings of anxiety, fear, and worry that significantly interfere with daily life. These disorders involve a heightened sense of apprehension and a range of emotional and physical symptoms.</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">There are several types of anxiety disorders, including:</h3> <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Generalized Anxiety Disorder (GAD): GAD is characterized by excessive and uncontrollable worry about various aspects of life, such as work, health, relationships, or everyday situations. Individuals with GAD often experience chronic anxiety, restlessness, irritability, muscle tension, and difficulties with concentration and sleep.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Panic Disorder: Panic disorder involves recurrent panic attacks, which are sudden and intense episodes of fear or discomfort that reach their peak within minutes. Symptoms of a panic attack may include a racing or pounding heart, shortness of breath, chest pain, dizziness, trembling, sweating, and a fear of losing control or dying.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Social Anxiety Disorder (Social Phobia): Social anxiety disorder is characterized by an intense fear of social situations or performance situations due to the fear of being embarrassed, judged, or humiliated. People with social anxiety disorder may avoid social interactions or endure them with significant distress. Physical symptoms may include blushing, sweating, trembling, and rapid heartbeat.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Specific Phobias: Specific phobias involve an intense and irrational fear of specific objects, situations, or activities. Common phobias include fear of heights, animals, blood, flying, or certain environments. Individuals with specific phobias may go to great lengths to avoid their feared stimuli, leading to disruptions in their daily lives.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (OCD): OCD is characterized by intrusive and persistent thoughts, images, or urges (obsessions) that create distress and anxiety. To alleviate this distress, individuals engage in repetitive behaviors or mental acts (compulsions) in an attempt to reduce anxiety or prevent a feared outcome. Common OCD themes include contamination fears, excessive checking, symmetry and orderliness, and intrusive thoughts.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD): PTSD can develop after exposure to a traumatic event such as warfare, assault, natural disaster, or a severe accident. Symptoms may include intrusive memories or flashbacks of the traumatic event, avoidance of triggers associated with the event, negative mood, hyperarousal, and heightened anxiety levels.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The specific causes of anxiety disorders are not fully understood, but a combination of genetic, environmental, and neurobiological factors is believed to play a role. Traumatic life events, chronic stress, and imbalances in brain chemistry, particularly involving neurotransmitters such as serotonin and gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA), are thought to contribute to the development of anxiety disorders.</p>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment for anxiety disorders often involves a combination of therapies, including:</h3>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Psychotherapy: Cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT) is the most commonly used psychotherapy for anxiety disorders. It helps individuals identify and challenge distorted thoughts, develop coping mechanisms, and gradually confront feared situations through exposure therapy.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Antidepressants, such as selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) or benzodiazepines, may be prescribed to manage symptoms of anxiety. These medications can help regulate brain chemistry and reduce the intensity of anxiety symptoms.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Relaxation Techniques: Learning and practicing relaxation techniques, such as deep breathing exercises, progressive muscle relaxation, and mindfulness meditation, can help reduce anxiety levels.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lifestyle Modifications: Engaging in regular physical exercise, maintaining a balanced diet, ensuring adequate sleep, and minimizing the use of substances like caffeine or alcohol can contribute to overall well-being and help manage anxiety symptoms.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Support Network: Building a strong support system, involving friends, family, and support groups, can</p> </li> </ol>', 'Anxiety disorders.png'),
(46, 5, 'Bipolar disorder', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Bipolar disorder</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bipolar disorder, formerly known as manic-depressive illness, is a chronic mental health condition characterized by extreme mood swings that alternate between periods of mania (elevated mood) and depression (low mood). These mood episodes can significantly impact a person&#39;s energy levels, thinking patterns, behavior, and overall functioning.</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">There are several types of bipolar disorder, including:</h3><ol><li> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bipolar I Disorder: This type involves manic episodes that last for at least one week or require immediate hospitalization. Depressive episodes may also occur, lasting for at least two weeks.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bipolar II Disorder: Bipolar II disorder is characterized by recurrent depressive episodes and hypomanic episodes (less severe than full manic episodes) that last for at least four days. Individuals with Bipolar II disorder do not experience full-blown manic episodes.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cyclothymic Disorder: Cyclothymic disorder involves numerous periods of hypomanic symptoms and depressive symptoms that last for at least two years (one year in children and adolescents). The symptoms, however, do not meet the criteria for full manic or depressive episodes.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">The symptoms of bipolar disorder depend on the specific mood episode experienced:</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Manic Episode Symptoms:</p>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Elevated mood or extreme irritability</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Increased energy and decreased need for sleep</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Racing thoughts and rapid speech</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Grandiose or inflated self-esteem</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Increased goal-directed activity or agitation</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Impulsive behavior, poor judgment, or risk-taking</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Decreased appetite or increased appetite</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Increased involvement in pleasurable activities with a potential for negative consequences (e.g., excessive spending, reckless sexual behavior)</li> </ul> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Depressive Episode Symptoms:</h3> <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Persistent sadness or empty mood</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Loss of interest or pleasure in activities</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue or loss of energy</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Changes in appetite or weight (significant weight loss or gain)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Sleep disturbances (insomnia or hypersomnia)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Feelings of worthlessness or excessive guilt</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Difficulty concentrating or making decisions</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Recurrent thoughts of death or suicide</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The exact cause of bipolar disorder is not known, but it is believed to involve a combination of genetic, biological, and environmental factors. Neurochemical imbalances, particularly involving neurotransmitters like serotonin, dopamine, and norepinephrine, play a role in the disorder&#39;s development.</p>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment for bipolar disorder usually involves a combination of medications, psychotherapy, and lifestyle adjustments:</h3> <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Mood Stabilizers: Medications like lithium, anticonvulsants (e.g., valproate, lamotrigine), and certain atypical antipsychotics help stabilize mood and prevent manic and depressive episodes.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Antidepressants or Antipsychotics: These medications may be prescribed cautiously during depressive or manic episodes, sometimes in combination with mood stabilizers.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Psychotherapy: Different types of therapy, such as cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT) or interpersonal and social rhythm therapy (IPSRT), can help individuals manage mood swings, improve coping skills, and establish a routine.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lifestyle Modifications: Maintaining a stable routine, getting enough sleep, managing stress, and avoiding substances like alcohol or drugs can help minimize the risk of mood episode triggers.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It&#39;s essential for individuals with bipolar disorder to work closely with healthcare professionals, including psychiatrists or psychologists, to develop an individualized treatment plan, monitor mood fluctuations, and address specific needs. Regular medication management and therapy sessions are crucial for long-term management and stability.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Support from family, friends, and support groups can also provide valuable assistance in managing the challenges of bipolar disorder and maintaining overall well-being.</p>', 'Bipolar disorder.png'),
(47, 5, 'Schizophrenia', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Schizophrenia</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Schizophrenia is a chronic and severe mental disorder that affects how a person thinks, feels, and behaves. It is characterized by a range of symptoms that can include hallucinations, delusions, disorganized thinking and speech, social withdrawal, and impaired cognitive functioning. These symptoms often significantly impact an individual&#39;s ability to function in daily life.</p>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">The symptoms of schizophrenia can be classified into three main categories:</h3><ol> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Positive Symptoms: Positive symptoms involve an excess or distortion of normal functioning and include:</li> </ol>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hallucinations: Sensory experiences that are not based in reality, most commonly auditory hallucinations (hearing voices). Visual, olfactory, tactile, and gustatory hallucinations can also occur.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Delusions: False beliefs that persist despite evidence to the contrary. Delusions may involve paranoid beliefs (e.g., feeling persecuted or spied upon) or grandiose beliefs (e.g., having special powers or a famous identity).</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Disorganized Thinking and Speech: Difficulty organizing thoughts, making logical connections, and expressing oneself coherently. Speech may be tangential, incoherent, or contain loose associations.</li> </ul>  <ol start=\"2\"> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Negative Symptoms: Negative symptoms involve a reduction or absence of normal functioning and include:</li> </ol>  <ul><li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Flat Affect: Reduced emotional expression, leading to a lack of facial expression, monotone speech, and reduced body language.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Alogia: Poverty of speech or a decrease in the amount and quality of speech.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Avolition: Lack of motivation, reduced initiative, and an inability to persist in goal-directed activities.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Anhedonia: Loss of interest or pleasure in activities that were previously enjoyable.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Social Withdrawal: Decreased desire for social interaction and reduced engagement in social relationships.</li> </ul>  <ol start=\"3\"> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cognitive Symptoms: Cognitive symptoms involve difficulties with thinking processes and include:</li> </ol>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Impaired Attention: Difficulty focusing and sustaining attention.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Impaired Memory: Problems with short-term memory and difficulties with memory recall.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Executive Dysfunction: Challenges with planning, organizing, problem-solving, and decision-making.</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The exact cause of schizophrenia is not known, but it is likely multifactorial, involving a combination of genetic, environmental, and neurobiological factors. Imbalances in neurotransmitters, particularly dopamine and glutamate, are thought to play a role in the development of the disorder.</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment for schizophrenia typically involves a combination of medications, psychosocial interventions, and support:</h3><ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Antipsychotic Medications: Antipsychotic medications are the primary treatment for schizophrenia. They help reduce the intensity of symptoms and manage psychotic episodes.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Psychosocial Interventions: Psychosocial interventions, such as cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT), family therapy, and social skills training, can help individuals manage symptoms, improve coping strategies, and enhance social functioning.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Rehabilitation and Supportive Services: Rehabilitation programs provide support in areas such as employment, education, and daily living skills to promote recovery and independent living.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Peer and Family Support: Support from family members, peers, and support groups can be invaluable in providing understanding, encouragement, and practical assistance.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Long-term management of schizophrenia requires ongoing treatment, regular monitoring, and support from mental health professionals. Early intervention and a comprehensive treatment approach can significantly improve outcomes and quality of life for individuals with schizophrenia.</p>', 'Schizophrenia.png'),
(48, 5, 'Traumatic brain injury', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Traumatic Brain Injury</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Traumatic Brain Injury (TBI) refers to damage to the brain caused by an external force. It can occur as a result of various incidents, including falls, motor vehicle accidents, sports injuries, assaults, or explosive blasts. TBI can have wide-ranging effects on a person&#39;s physical, cognitive, emotional, and behavioral functioning, depending on the severity and location of the injury.</p>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">TBI can be classified into two types:</h3><ol><li> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Closed Head Injury: This occurs when the brain is injured due to a blow or impact to the head without penetration or skull fracture. It can result in various types of brain damage, such as bruising, bleeding, or swelling.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Penetrating Head Injury: This occurs when an object penetrates the skull and damages brain tissue. It can cause focal injuries and may require surgical intervention.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The symptoms and effects of TBI can vary widely depending on the severity and location of the injury. They can be classified into three categories:</p>  <ol> 	<li>Physical Symptoms:</li> </ol>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Headaches or migraines</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Nausea or vomiting</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue or drowsiness</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Sensory disturbances (blurred vision, ringing in the ears, altered taste or smell)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Motor impairments (weakness, paralysis, loss of coordination)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Seizures or convulsions</li> </ul>  <ol start=\"2\"> 	<li>Cognitive Symptoms:</li> </ol>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Memory problems (short-term or long-term memory loss)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Difficulty concentrating or paying attention</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Slowed thinking or information processing</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Problems with problem-solving, planning, and decision-making</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Executive function deficits (organizing, initiating tasks, multitasking)</li> </ul>  <ol start=\"3\"> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Emotional and Behavioral Symptoms:</li> </ol>  <ul> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Mood swings or emotional instability</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Depression or anxiety</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Irritability or agitation</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Impulsive behavior or lack of impulse control</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Social withdrawal or isolation</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Changes in personality or behavior</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Sleep disturbances (insomnia or excessive sleep)</li> </ul>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Recovery from TBI can vary greatly depending on the severity of the injury, the individual&#39;s overall health, and the quality of medical care and rehabilitation received. Some individuals may experience a complete recovery, while others may have long-lasting or permanent impairments.</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Treatment and management of TBI typically involve a multidisciplinary approach:</h3> <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medical Care: Immediate medical attention focuses on stabilizing the individual, preventing further damage, and addressing any life-threatening injuries. Surgery may be required for severe cases.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Rehabilitation: Rehabilitation aims to maximize functional abilities and improve quality of life. It may involve physical therapy, occupational therapy, speech therapy, and cognitive rehabilitation to address physical, cognitive, and communication impairments.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Medications may be prescribed to manage symptoms such as pain, seizures, depression, or anxiety.</p> </li> <li> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Psychological Support: Emotional support and counseling can help individuals and their families cope with the emotional and psychological challenges that may arise as a result of TBI.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Assistive Devices and Supportive Services: Depending on the individual&#39;s needs, assistive devices, such as mobility aids or communication aids, may be recommended. Supportive services, including vocational training and community support programs, can aid in the transition back to daily life.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Prevention of TBI involves implementing safety measures such as wearing seatbelts, using protective headgear during sports activities, following workplace safety protocols, and taking precautions to prevent falls.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It&#39;s important to note that the information provided is a general overview of TBI, and individual cases can vary significantly. A healthcare professional should be consulted for a comprehensive evaluation and personalized treatment plan.</p>', 'Traumatic brain injury.png'),
(49, 5, 'Carpal tunnel syndrome', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Carpal tunnel syndrome</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Carpal tunnel syndrome (CTS) is a condition that affects the hand and wrist. It occurs when the median nerve, which runs from the forearm to the hand, becomes compressed or squeezed as it passes through the narrow passageway called the carpal tunnel. The carpal tunnel is a narrow tunnel formed by the bones and ligaments in the wrist.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The primary cause of carpal tunnel syndrome is the compression of the median nerve within the carpal tunnel. This compression can be caused by several factors, including:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Repetitive Hand and Wrist Movements: Performing repetitive hand and wrist motions, such as typing, using a computer mouse, or working with vibrating tools, can contribute to the development of CTS.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Wrist Position: Prolonged or repeated wrist flexion or extension, especially when combined with forceful gripping, can increase pressure on the median nerve.</p> </li> 	<li> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Anatomic Factors: Certain anatomical factors, such as having a smaller carpal tunnel or a wrist fracture, can make individuals more susceptible to developing CTS.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">The symptoms of carpal tunnel syndrome typically include:</h3><ol> <li> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Numbness and Tingling: Individuals may experience numbness, tingling, or a &quot;pins and needles&quot; sensation in the thumb, index finger, middle finger, and half of the ring finger. These sensations may extend up the arm.</p> </li> <li> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hand Weakness: Weakness and a tendency to drop objects or have a reduced grip strength can occur due to muscle weakness in the hand.</p> </li> <li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pain or Discomfort: Some individuals may experience pain or aching in the hand or wrist, which may radiate up the forearm or arm. The pain may worsen at night.</p> </li> <li> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Sensory Changes: A loss of sensation or a feeling of swelling in the fingers, even though no visible swelling is present.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">In the early stages, symptoms may come and go or be more noticeable during certain activities. However, as the condition progresses, symptoms may become more persistent and severe.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Treatment for carpal tunnel syndrome may involve a combination of conservative measures and, in some cases, surgery:</p>  <ol> <li> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Rest and Modification of Activities: Taking frequent breaks, modifying hand and wrist movements, and avoiding repetitive activities that exacerbate symptoms can help alleviate symptoms.</p> </li> <li> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Wrist Splinting: Wearing a splint or brace that immobilizes the wrist in a neutral position can help relieve pressure on the median nerve and reduce symptoms, especially at night.</p> </li> <li> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs), such as ibuprofen, may be recommended to reduce pain and inflammation.</p> </li> <li> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Physical Therapy: Stretching and strengthening exercises, as well as techniques to improve wrist posture and ergonomics, may be prescribed by a physical therapist.</p> </li> <li> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Corticosteroid Injections: In some cases, a corticosteroid injection may be administered to reduce inflammation and alleviate symptoms.</p> </li> <li> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Surgery: If conservative treatments do not provide relief, or if symptoms are severe, surgery may be recommended. The procedure, called carpal tunnel release surgery, involves releasing the ligament that forms the roof of the carpal tunnel to relieve pressure on the median nerve.</p></li></ol> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Early diagnosis and treatment can help prevent the condition from progressing and causing long-term complications. If you suspect you have carpal tunnel syndrome or are experiencing symptoms, it is important to consult a healthcare professional for an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment plan.</p>', 'Carpal tunnel syndrome.png');
