(63, 7, 'Urinary tract infection (UTI)', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Urinary tract infection (UTI)</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Urinary tract infection (UTI) is a common infection that occurs in any part of the urinary system, including the kidneys, bladder, ureters, and urethra. It is primarily caused by bacteria entering the urethra and multiplying in the urinary tract. UTIs can affect people of all ages, but they are more common in women.</p>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Common symptoms of a UTI may include:</h3>  <ol> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Frequent and intense urge to urinate</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Burning sensation or pain during urination</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Passing small amounts of urine frequently</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cloudy, dark, or strong-smelling urine</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blood in the urine (hematuria)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pelvic pain, specifically in the lower abdomen</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue or general malaise</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fever or chills (a sign of a more severe infection)</li> </ol>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">UTIs are typically categorized based on the part of the urinary tract affected:</h3><ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cystitis: An infection in the bladder, causing symptoms such as frequent urination, urgency, and pelvic discomfort.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pyelonephritis: A more severe infection that reaches the kidneys, causing symptoms like fever, back pain, and nausea. This condition may require prompt medical attention.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Treatment for UTIs usually involves a course of antibiotics to eliminate the bacteria causing the infection. The specific antibiotic and duration of treatment will depend on factors such as the type of bacteria, the severity of symptoms, and the patient&#39;s medical history.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">In addition to antibiotics, several self-care measures can help alleviate UTI symptoms and prevent further infections:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Drinking plenty of water: This helps flush out bacteria from the urinary system and promotes urine flow.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Urinating frequently: Emptying the bladder regularly helps prevent the growth of bacteria.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Avoiding irritants: Minimize or avoid substances that may irritate the urinary tract, such as caffeine, alcohol, spicy foods, and acidic drinks.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Good hygiene practices: Wiping from front to back after using the toilet, maintaining proper genital hygiene, and wearing breathable cotton underwear can help reduce the risk of bacterial contamination.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Preventing UTIs includes strategies such as:</h3><ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Drinking an adequate amount of water daily to stay hydrated.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Urinating before and after sexual intercourse to flush out bacteria.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Proper hygiene practices, including regular washing of the genital area.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Avoiding holding urine for extended periods.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">While UTIs are typically caused by bacterial infections, certain factors increase the risk of developing them, such as urinary tract abnormalities, urinary catheter use, reduced immune function, pregnancy, menopause, and certain underlying medical conditions.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It&#39;s important to seek medical attention if UTI symptoms arise, especially if accompanied by fever, severe pain, or blood in the urine. Prompt diagnosis and treatment can help alleviate symptoms, prevent complications, and reduce the risk of recurrent infections.</p>', 'Urinary tract infection.png'),
(64, 7, 'Kidney stones', ' <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Kidney stones</h3>\n    <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Kidney stones are hard, pebble-like substances that form in the kidney when certain substances in the urine become highly concentrated. They can vary in size and shape, and they may be smooth or jagged. There are several types of kidney stones, including:</p>\n  <ol> <li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Calcium stones: These are the most common type of kidney stones. They can be made of calcium oxalate or calcium phosphate.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Uric acid stones: These stones form when the urine is too acidic. They are more common in people who eat a lot of protein or who have gout.</li><li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Struvite stones: These stones form in response to an infection, such as a urinary tract infection.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cystine stones: These stones form in people with a rare genetic disorder that causes the kidneys to excrete too much of certain amino acids.</li> </ol> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms of kidney stones can include:</h3> <ul> <li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pain in the side, back, or lower abdomen</li> <li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pain or burning during urination</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blood in the urine</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Nausea and vomiting</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Frequent urges to urinate<</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Difficulty urinating or a weak urine stream</li> </ul>', 'Kidney stones.png'),
(65, 7, 'Kidney disease', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Kidney disease</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Kidney disease, also known as renal disease, refers to a condition in which the kidneys are damaged and cannot perform their normal functions effectively. The kidneys play a crucial role in filtering waste products, excess fluids, and toxins from the blood, as well as regulating electrolyte balance and producing hormones that are important for various bodily functions.</p><h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">There are several types of kidney disease, including:</h3> <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chronic kidney disease (CKD): This is a long-term condition characterized by gradual and irreversible loss of kidney function over time. CKD can be caused by various factors, such as diabetes, high blood pressure, glomerulonephritis, polycystic kidney disease, or other inherited conditions.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Acute kidney injury (AKI): AKI occurs suddenly and is often reversible with proper treatment. It can be caused by factors like severe infections, dehydration, kidney infections, urinary tract blockage, or certain medications.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Glomerular diseases: These conditions affect the glomeruli, which are the tiny filtering units in the kidneys. Examples include glomerulonephritis, nephrotic syndrome, and lupus nephritis.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Kidney stones: Kidney stones are hard deposits that form in the kidneys and can cause pain and obstruction in the urinary tract.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Polycystic kidney disease (PKD): This is an inherited disorder characterized by the growth of cysts in the kidneys, which can lead to kidney damage and decline in function over time.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Symptoms of kidney disease can vary depending on the specific condition and the stage of the disease. However, common signs and symptoms may include:</p>  <ol> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue and weakness</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Swelling in the legs, ankles, feet, or hands (edema)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Changes in urine output (decreased or increased urine production)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blood in the urine (hematuria)</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Foamy or bubbly urine</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Persistent itching</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">High blood pressure</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Loss of appetite and weight loss</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Nausea and vomiting</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Shortness of breath or difficulty breathing</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Muscle cramps</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Diagnosis of kidney disease involves a combination of medical history evaluation, physical examination, laboratory tests (such as blood tests and urine analysis), imaging studies (such as ultrasound or CT scan), and kidney biopsy in certain cases.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Treatment of kidney disease depends on the underlying cause and the stage of the disease. The primary goals of treatment are to slow down the progression of kidney damage, manage symptoms, and prevent complications. Treatment approaches may include:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Depending on the specific condition, medications may be prescribed to control blood pressure, manage symptoms, reduce inflammation, or treat underlying causes.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lifestyle changes: Adopting a healthy lifestyle, including a balanced diet low in salt and protein, regular exercise, maintaining a healthy weight, and avoiding smoking and excessive alcohol consumption, can help manage kidney disease.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Dialysis: In advanced stages of kidney disease or kidney failure, dialysis may be necessary. Dialysis involves the use of a machine to filter and purify the blood, replicating the functions of the kidneys.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Kidney transplant: In cases of end-stage kidney disease, a kidney transplant may be an option. This involves replacing the diseased kidney with a healthy kidney from a living or deceased donor.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Managing kidney disease requires regular monitoring, adherence to treatment plans, and close communication with healthcare professionals. It is essential to consult with a nephrologist or kidney specialist for proper diagnosis, treatment, and ongoing care of kidney disease.</p>', 'Kidney disease.png'),
(66, 7, 'Bladder cancer', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Bladder cancer</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bladder cancer is a type of cancer that starts in the cells of the bladder, which is a hollow organ located in the lower abdomen that stores urine. Bladder cancer is one of the most common types of cancer, typically affecting older adults, with men being more prone to develop it than women.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The most common type of bladder cancer is called transitional cell carcinoma, which begins in the cells lining the inside of the bladder. Other, less common types include squamous cell carcinoma and adenocarcinoma.</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Common signs and symptoms of bladder cancer may include:</h3> <ol><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blood in the urine (hematuria), which is often the most noticeable symptom. Blood may make the urine appear red or darker in color.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Frequent urination or a strong urge to urinate, even when the bladder is not full.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pain or burning sensation during urination.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lower back pain, usually a sign that the cancer has spread to the kidneys.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pelvic pain or discomfort.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Changes in urinary habits or patterns.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The exact cause of bladder cancer is often unclear, but certain risk factors can increase the likelihood of developing the disease. These risk factors include smoking, exposure to certain chemicals (such as those used in the dye industry or in the production of rubber, textiles, and paint), chronic bladder inflammation or infections, a family history of bladder cancer, and certain genetic conditions.</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Diagnosis of bladder cancer involves several tests and procedures, which may include:</h3> <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Urine tests: Analysis of a urine sample to check for blood or abnormal cells.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Imaging tests: Such as ultrasound, CT scan, or MRI, to visualize the bladder and surrounding structures.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cystoscopy: A procedure in which a thin tube with a camera (cystoscope) is inserted through the urethra to examine the inside of the bladder.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Biopsy: If abnormal tissue is found during cystoscopy, a small sample may be taken for laboratory analysis to determine if it is cancerous.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Treatment options for bladder cancer depend on various factors, including the stage and grade of the cancer, the location and size of tumors, and the individual&#39;s overall health. Treatment approaches may include:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Surgery: The removal of cancerous tissue is a common treatment method. It may involve transurethral resection (TURBT) for early-stage tumors, partial or radical cystectomy (removal of part or all of the bladder), or urinary diversion surgeries.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Radiation therapy: High-energy X-rays or other forms of radiation are used to target and destroy cancer cells.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Immunotherapy: Medications are used to stimulate the body&#39;s immune system to recognize and attack cancer cells.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chemotherapy: Drugs are used to kill cancer cells or prevent their growth and spread. It can be administered orally, intravenously, or directly into the bladder (intravesical chemotherapy).</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The choice of treatment depends on factors such as the stage of the cancer, whether it has spread to other parts of the body, and the overall health and preferences of the individual.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Regular follow-up care is essential for individuals with bladder cancer to monitor for recurrence and manage any potential side effects of treatment. Lifestyle changes, such as quitting smoking and maintaining a healthy lifestyle, can also contribute to overall well-being and may reduce the risk of bladder cancer.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It is crucial to consult with a healthcare professional for an accurate diagnosis, appropriate staging, and a personalized treatment plan for bladder cancer.</p>', 'Bladder cancer.png'),
(67, 7, 'Prostate cancer', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Prostate cancer</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Prostate cancer is a type of cancer that develops in the prostate gland, which is a small walnut-shaped gland located below the bladder in men. The prostate gland produces seminal fluid that nourishes and transports sperm. Prostate cancer is one of the most common types of cancer in men.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The exact cause of prostate cancer is unknown, but certain risk factors can increase the likelihood of developing the disease. These risk factors include age (the risk increases with age, particularly after the age of 50), family history of prostate cancer, certain genetic mutations, race (African-American men have a higher risk), and a diet high in red meat and low in fruits and vegetables.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">In the early stages, prostate cancer may not cause noticeable symptoms. However, as the cancer progresses, it can lead to various signs and symptoms, including:</p>  <ol> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Frequent urination, especially at night.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Difficulty starting or stopping urination.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Weak urine flow or a sense of incomplete bladder emptying.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blood in the urine or semen.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Erectile dysfunction (difficulty achieving or maintaining an erection).</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pain or discomfort in the pelvic area or lower back.</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">To diagnose prostate cancer, a healthcare professional may perform several tests and procedures, which may include:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Digital rectal examination (DRE): A physical examination in which the doctor inserts a gloved finger into the rectum to feel the prostate gland for any abnormalities or lumps.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Prostate-specific antigen (PSA) test: A blood test that measures the levels of PSA, a protein produced by the prostate gland. Elevated PSA levels may indicate the presence of prostate cancer, but further tests are needed to confirm the diagnosis.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Prostate biopsy: If the PSA levels are elevated or an abnormality is detected during the DRE, a small tissue sample (biopsy) may be taken from the prostate gland for laboratory analysis to confirm the presence of cancer.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The treatment options for prostate cancer depend on various factors, including the stage of the cancer, the aggressiveness of the tumor, the individual&#39;s overall health, and personal preferences. Treatment approaches may include:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Active surveillance: For slow-growing or early-stage cancers, the healthcare provider may recommend regular monitoring of the cancer&#39;s progression with periodic PSA tests, DREs, and imaging tests without immediate active treatment.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Surgery: Surgical removal of the prostate gland, known as a radical prostatectomy, may be performed to remove the cancerous tissue. This can be done using open surgery or minimally invasive techniques such as laparoscopic or robotic-assisted surgery.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Radiation therapy: High-energy beams, such as X-rays or protons, are used to kill cancer cells or prevent their growth. Radiation therapy can be administered externally or by placing radioactive material directly into the prostate (brachytherapy).</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hormone therapy: Medications are used to block the production or activity of male hormones (androgens) that stimulate the growth of prostate cancer cells.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Chemotherapy: Drugs are used to kill cancer cells or slow down their growth. Chemotherapy is usually reserved for advanced cases of prostate cancer.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Immunotherapy: This treatment option aims to stimulate the body&#39;s immune system to recognize and attack cancer cells.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The choice of treatment depends on various factors, and the healthcare provider will discuss the options and their potential risks and benefits with the individual.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Regular follow-up care is essential for individuals with prostate cancer to monitor for recurrence and manage any potential side effects of treatment. It is important to have open discussions with healthcare professionals and make informed decisions about treatment based on individual circumstances.</p>', 'Prostate cancer.png'),
(68, 7, 'Erectile dysfunction', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Erectile dysfunction (ED)</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Erectile dysfunction (ED), also known as impotence, refers to the inability to achieve or maintain an erection sufficient for satisfactory sexual performance. It is a common condition that can affect men of all ages but becomes more prevalent with increasing age.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">ED can have various underlying causes, including physical, psychological, or a combination of both. Physical causes may include conditions that affect blood flow to the penis, such as cardiovascular disease, diabetes, obesity, high blood pressure, hormonal imbalances, or neurological disorders. Psychological factors can contribute to ED, including stress, anxiety, depression, relationship problems, or performance anxiety.</p>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms of erectile dysfunction may include:</h3>    <ol> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Difficulty achieving an erection.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Difficulty maintaining an erection during sexual activity.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Reduced sexual desire or libido.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Premature ejaculation.</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Delayed ejaculation.</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Diagnosis of erectile dysfunction involves a thorough medical history evaluation, physical examination, and sometimes additional tests, depending on the suspected underlying causes. These tests may include blood tests to check hormone levels, lipid profile, or blood sugar levels. In some cases, specialized tests such as ultrasound or nocturnal penile tumescence (NPT) testing may be performed to assess the blood flow and function of the penis during sleep.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Treatment options for erectile dysfunction depend on the underlying cause, severity of symptoms, and individual preferences. They may include:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lifestyle changes: Making healthy lifestyle choices can have a positive impact on erectile function. This includes regular exercise, maintaining a healthy weight, managing stress, quitting smoking, reducing alcohol consumption, and improving overall cardiovascular health.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Oral medications: Medications such as sildenafil (Viagra), tadalafil (Cialis), vardenafil (Levitra), or avanafil (Stendra) are commonly prescribed to improve blood flow to the penis and facilitate erections. These medications are usually taken shortly before sexual activity.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Vacuum erection devices: These devices involve placing a cylindrical pump over the penis, which creates a vacuum and draws blood into the penile tissues, leading to an erection. A constriction band is then placed at the base of the penis to maintain the erection.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Penile injections or suppositories: Medications, such as alprostadil, can be injected into the base or side of the penis or inserted as suppositories into the urethra to promote the relaxation of blood vessels and improve blood flow for achieving an erection.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Testosterone replacement therapy: In cases where low testosterone levels contribute to erectile dysfunction, testosterone replacement therapy may be considered under the guidance of a healthcare professional.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Psychological counseling: If psychological factors are the primary cause of ED, counseling or therapy can help address underlying issues such as anxiety, stress, or relationship problems.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It is important to consult with a healthcare professional for a proper diagnosis and personalized treatment plan for erectile dysfunction. Open communication with one&#39;s partner and seeking support are also essential aspects of managing the condition.</p>', 'Erectile dysfunction.png'),
(69, 7, 'Premenstrual syndrome (PMS)', '<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Premenstrual syndrome (PMS) refers to a collection of physical, emotional, and behavioral symptoms that occur in the days or weeks leading up to menstruation. It is a common condition that affects many menstruating individuals, typically starting during their late teens or 20s.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The exact cause of PMS is not fully understood, but hormonal fluctuations during the menstrual cycle are believed to play a role. The changing levels of estrogen and progesterone can affect neurotransmitters in the brain, leading to the onset of symptoms. Additionally, factors such as stress, lifestyle, and individual sensitivity can influence the severity of PMS symptoms.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Common symptoms of PMS can vary among individuals and may include:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p>Physical symptoms:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Breast tenderness or swelling</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bloating and fluid retention</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fatigue or low energy levels</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Headaches or migraines</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Muscle aches and joint pain</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Abdominal cramps or discomfort</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p>Emotional and psychological symptoms:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Mood swings and irritability</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Anxiety or feelings of tension</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Depression or sadness</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Increased sensitivity or crying spells</li> <li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Changes in appetite or food cravings</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Difficulty concentrating or remembering</li> 	</ul> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The symptoms of PMS typically occur in a predictable pattern, starting a week or two before menstruation and improving or disappearing shortly after the start of menstruation. The severity and duration of symptoms can vary from person to person, ranging from mild to more severe and interfering with daily activities and quality of life.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">There is no specific diagnostic test for PMS, and the diagnosis is usually made based on the pattern of symptoms experienced over several menstrual cycles. Keeping a symptom diary can help track the symptoms and their timing, aiding in the diagnosis process.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Treatment options for PMS aim to alleviate the symptoms and improve overall well-being. They may include:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p>Lifestyle modifications:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Regular exercise, which can help reduce symptoms.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">A balanced diet with reduced salt, sugar, and caffeine intake.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Stress management techniques, such as relaxation exercises or meditation.</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p>Medications:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) for pain relief.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hormonal contraceptives, such as birth control pills, to regulate hormone levels and reduce symptoms.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Antidepressant medications, specifically selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs), which can help alleviate emotional symptoms.</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p>Psychological support:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Counseling or therapy, such as cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT), can assist in managing emotional symptoms and developing coping strategies.</li> 	</ul> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It is important for individuals experiencing significant disruption or distress due to PMS to consult with a healthcare professional for proper evaluation, diagnosis, and treatment options. Tracking and monitoring symptoms can assist in identifying patterns and tailoring treatment approaches for better symptom management.</p>', 'Premenstrual syndrome.png'),
(70, 7, 'Endometriosis', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Endometriosis</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Endometriosis is a chronic and often painful disorder in which tissue similar to the lining of the uterus (endometrium) grows outside the uterus, commonly affecting the pelvic area. This misplaced tissue, called endometrial implants, can develop on the ovaries, fallopian tubes, outer surface of the uterus, and other pelvic organs.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The exact cause of endometriosis is not fully understood, but several theories exist, including retrograde menstruation (when menstrual blood flows backward into the pelvic cavity), genetic factors, hormonal imbalances, and immune system dysfunction. Endometriosis can cause various symptoms and complications, including:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pelvic pain: Chronic or intermittent pelvic pain, often worsening during menstruation, can range from mild to severe.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Painful periods: Dysmenorrhea, or severe menstrual cramps, can be accompanied by lower back and abdominal pain.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pain during intercourse: Discomfort or pain during sexual intercourse (dyspareunia) is a common symptom of endometriosis.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Infertility: Endometriosis can contribute to difficulties in conceiving due to the obstruction or distortion of the reproductive organs.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Heavy or irregular periods: Endometriosis can lead to heavy or prolonged menstrual bleeding or irregular menstrual cycles.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Gastrointestinal symptoms: Some individuals may experience digestive issues such as bloating, constipation, diarrhea, or nausea, especially during menstruation.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Diagnosis of endometriosis typically involves a combination of medical history evaluation, pelvic examination, imaging tests (such as ultrasound or MRI), and sometimes a surgical procedure called laparoscopy to directly visualize and biopsy the endometrial implants.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Treatment options for endometriosis focus on relieving symptoms, managing pain, and improving fertility if desired. They may include:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pain medication: Over-the-counter pain relievers (e.g., nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs) can help alleviate mild to moderate pain. Stronger prescription medications may be necessary for severe pain.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hormonal therapy: Birth control pills, progestin-only contraceptives, or other hormonal treatments can help regulate hormone levels, suppress the growth of endometrial tissue, and reduce pain.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Surgery: Laparoscopic surgery is often performed to remove or destroy endometrial implants and scar tissue. In severe cases, a hysterectomy (removal of the uterus) may be recommended.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fertility treatments: Assisted reproductive technologies (such as in vitro fertilization) can help individuals with endometriosis conceive.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Lifestyle modifications, such as exercise, stress management, and dietary changes, may also be beneficial in managing symptoms.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Endometriosis is a chronic condition that requires long-term management. It is important for individuals experiencing symptoms suggestive of endometriosis to consult with a healthcare professional, preferably a gynecologist or specialist in reproductive health, for an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment plan tailored to their specific needs.</p>', 'Endometriosis.png'),
(71, 7, 'Fibroids', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Fibroids</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fibroids, also known as uterine fibroids or leiomyomas, are noncancerous growths that develop in the uterus. They are made up of smooth muscle cells and fibrous connective tissue. Fibroids can vary in size, ranging from small, undetectable growths to large masses that can distort the shape and size of the uterus.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The exact cause of fibroids is unknown, but hormonal factors, particularly estrogen and progesterone, are believed to play a role in their development and growth. Other factors that may contribute to the formation of fibroids include genetics, family history, and certain risk factors such as obesity and early onset of menstruation.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Many women with fibroids may not experience any symptoms, but when symptoms do occur, they can vary in severity and depend on the size, number, and location of the fibroids. Common signs and symptoms of fibroids include:</p>  <ol> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Heavy or prolonged menstrual periods</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pelvic pain or pressure</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Frequent urination or difficulty emptying the bladder</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Constipation or bloating</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Back or leg pain</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Enlarged abdomen or visible abdominal mass</li> 	<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pain during sexual intercourse</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The diagnosis of fibroids is typically made through a combination of medical history evaluation, pelvic examination, and imaging tests such as ultrasound, magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), or hysteroscopy (a procedure that allows the visualization of the uterus).</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Treatment options for fibroids depend on various factors, including the severity of symptoms, the size and location of the fibroids, desire for future fertility, and overall health. Treatment approaches may include:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Watchful waiting: If fibroids are small, not causing symptoms, and not affecting fertility, regular monitoring without active treatment may be recommended.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Hormonal medications such as birth control pills, gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) agonists, or progestin-releasing intrauterine devices (IUDs) can help regulate menstrual bleeding, reduce pain, or shrink fibroids.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Noninvasive procedures: Procedures like uterine artery embolization (UAE) and magnetic resonance-guided focused ultrasound surgery (MRgFUS) use targeted energy to destroy or shrink fibroids without surgery.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Surgical options: If symptoms are severe or other treatments are ineffective, surgical interventions may be considered. These include myomectomy (removal of fibroids while preserving the uterus), hysterectomy (removal of the uterus), or endometrial ablation (destruction of the uterine lining).</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">The choice of treatment depends on individual circumstances, and healthcare providers will discuss the available options, risks, benefits, and potential impact on future fertility with each person.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It&#39;s important for individuals experiencing symptoms of fibroids to seek medical evaluation and consult with a healthcare professional, preferably a gynecologist or specialist in reproductive health, to determine the most appropriate management plan for their specific situation.</p>', 'Fibroids.png'),
(73, 8, 'Allergies', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Allergies</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Allergies refer to an overreactive response of the immune system to substances that are normally harmless to most people. These substances, known as allergens, can trigger an allergic reaction when they come into contact with individuals who are sensitized or allergic to them. Allergies can manifest in various ways and affect different parts of the body, including the respiratory system, skin, gastrointestinal tract, and eyes.</p> <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Common types of allergies include: </h3> <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Allergic rhinitis (hay fever): This allergy is triggered by airborne allergens such as pollen, dust mites, or pet dander. Symptoms may include sneezing, itching or watery eyes, nasal congestion, and a runny or itchy nose.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Asthma: Allergic asthma is a condition where exposure to certain allergens causes inflammation and narrowing of the airways, leading to breathing difficulties, wheezing, coughing, and chest tightness.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Food allergies: These occur when the immune system reacts to certain proteins in food, such as peanuts, tree nuts, eggs, milk, wheat, soy, fish, or shellfish. Symptoms can range from mild to severe and may include hives, itching, swelling, digestive problems, and in severe cases, anaphylaxis.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Skin allergies: Allergic reactions on the skin can result from contact with substances like certain metals (e.g., nickel), latex, medications, or certain chemicals. Symptoms may include redness, itching, rashes (such as eczema or hives), or swelling at the site of contact.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Drug allergies: Some individuals may develop allergic reactions to certain medications, such as antibiotics (e.g., penicillin), nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs), or chemotherapy drugs. Symptoms can range from mild skin rashes to severe reactions like anaphylaxis.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Diagnosis of allergies typically involves a combination of medical history evaluation, physical examination, and allergy testing methods. These tests may include skin prick tests, blood tests (such as IgE antibody tests), or oral food challenges, depending on the suspected allergen.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Management of allergies involves allergen avoidance, medication, and in some cases, immunotherapy. Treatment options may include:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Allergen avoidance: Identifying and avoiding the allergen or taking measures to minimize exposure can help reduce symptoms.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Medications: Over-the-counter or prescription medications, such as antihistamines, nasal sprays, corticosteroids, or bronchodilators, can help alleviate symptoms and manage allergic reactions.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Immunotherapy: For individuals with severe allergies or insufficient response to medications, allergen immunotherapy (allergy shots or sublingual tablets) may be recommended. This treatment gradually exposes the person to increasing doses of the allergen to build tolerance and reduce allergic reactions.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Allergies can vary in severity, ranging from mild discomfort to life-threatening reactions. It is important for individuals with known allergies to be prepared, carry necessary medications (such as epinephrine auto-injectors for severe allergies), and seek immediate medical attention in case of severe allergic reactions or anaphylaxis.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Consulting with a healthcare professional, such as an allergist or immunologist, can provide a comprehensive evaluation, accurate diagnosis, and personalized management plan for allergies.</p>', 'Allergies.png'),
(74, 8, 'Anaphylaxis', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Anaphylaxis</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Anaphylaxis is a severe and potentially life-threatening allergic reaction that occurs rapidly after exposure to an allergen. It is a medical emergency that requires immediate attention. Anaphylaxis can be triggered by various substances, including certain foods, medications, insect stings, latex, or even physical factors like exercise.</p>  <h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Symptoms of anaphylaxis can affect multiple systems in the body and may include:</h3><ol> <li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Skin reactions: Itching, hives, redness, or swelling at the site of exposure.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Respiratory symptoms: Difficulty breathing, wheezing, shortness of breath, coughing, or chest tightness.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cardiovascular symptoms: Rapid or weak pulse, low blood pressure, lightheadedness, dizziness, or fainting.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Gastrointestinal symptoms: Nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, or diarrhea.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Swelling: Swelling of the lips, tongue, throat, or face, which can lead to difficulty swallowing or speaking.</p> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Anxiety or a sense of impending doom.</p> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Anaphylaxis is a severe systemic allergic reaction that can progress rapidly and can be life-threatening. If left untreated, it can lead to a sudden drop in blood pressure (shock), loss of consciousness, and even death.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Immediate treatment for anaphylaxis involves the administration of epinephrine (adrenaline) through an auto-injector device, which helps counteract the allergic reaction and opens up the airways. Emergency medical assistance should be sought immediately after administering epinephrine.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">After the administration of epinephrine, additional treatments may be provided to manage and stabilize the person&#39;s condition, including antihistamines and corticosteroids. In severe cases, intravenous fluids, oxygen, and other supportive measures may be necessary.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Following an episode of anaphylaxis, individuals should be monitored closely, and they may require follow-up care with an allergist or immunologist for further evaluation, identification of triggers, and development of an anaphylaxis action plan. This plan typically includes education on allergen avoidance, carrying emergency medications (such as epinephrine auto-injectors), and recognizing the signs and symptoms of anaphylaxis.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Prevention plays a crucial role in managing anaphylaxis. This involves identifying and avoiding known allergens, reading food and medication labels carefully, wearing medical alert identification, and undergoing appropriate testing and evaluation to identify triggers.</p>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Educating oneself and others about anaphylaxis, recognizing the symptoms, and seeking immediate medical attention in case of a suspected anaphylactic reaction are essential steps to ensure prompt and effective management of this potentially life-threatening condition.</p>', 'Anaphylaxis.png');
