(95, 9, 'Testicular cancer', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Testicular cancer</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Testicular cancer is a relatively rare form of cancer that develops in the testicles, which are the male reproductive organs responsible for producing sperm and testosterone. It typically affects younger men between the ages of 15 and 35, but it can occur at any age. Here is a comprehensive description of testicular cancer:</p>  <ol> 	<li> 	<p>Types of Testicular Cancer:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Germ Cell Tumors: Germ cell tumors account for the majority of testicular cancer cases. They originate from the cells that produce sperm and can be further classified into two subtypes: 		<ul> 			<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Seminomas: These tumors tend to grow more slowly and are more sensitive to radiation therapy.</li> 			<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Nonseminomas: These tumors are more aggressive and consist of several subtypes, including embryonal carcinoma, yolk sac tumor, choriocarcinoma, and teratoma.</li> 		</ul> 		</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Stromal Cell Tumors: Stromal cell tumors are rare and develop in the supportive tissue of the testicles. The most common type is Leydig cell tumors and Sertoli cell tumors.</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p>Risk Factors:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Undescended Testicle (Cryptorchidism): Men with a history of undescended testicles have an increased risk of testicular cancer.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Family History: Having a close relative with testicular cancer increases the risk.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Age: Testicular cancer is more common in younger men.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Race and Ethnicity: White men have a higher risk compared to men of other racial or ethnic backgrounds.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Congenital Abnormalities: Certain genetic conditions, such as Klinefelter syndrome, may increase the risk.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Personal History: Men who have had testicular cancer in one testicle are at higher risk of developing it in the other testicle.</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p>Symptoms:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Painless Lump or Swelling: The most common symptom is a painless lump or swelling in one of the testicles. It may be small or large and can be detected through self-examination.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Testicular Pain or Discomfort: Some men may experience testicular pain or discomfort, swelling, or a heavy sensation in the scrotum.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Changes in Size or Consistency: Other changes may include a noticeable increase in size of one testicle, changes in shape or texture, or the development of a hard mass within the testicle.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fluid Accumulation: In some cases, there may be a buildup of fluid in the scrotum, causing swelling or enlargement.</li> 	</ul> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It&#39;s important to note that these symptoms are not specific to testicular cancer and can be caused by other conditions. However, if any of these symptoms are present, it is recommended to consult a healthcare professional for further evaluation.</p>  <ol start=\"4\"> 	<li> 	<p>Diagnosis:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Physical Examination: A healthcare professional examines the testicles, scrotum, and groin area for any abnormalities.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Ultrasound: An ultrasound scan is performed to visualize the testicles and assess the presence of any masses or tumors.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Blood Tests: Blood tests may be conducted to measure tumor markers, such as alpha-fetoprotein (AFP), human chorionic gonadotropin (HCG), and lactate dehydrogenase (LDH).</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Biopsy: If an abnormality is found, a biopsy may be performed to remove a sample of testicular tissue for laboratory analysis. This helps confirm the presence of cancer cells and determines the specific type and characteristics of the cancer.</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p>Treatment:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Surgery: Surgery is the primary treatment for testicular cancer and typically involves the removal of the affected testicle (radical inguinal orchiectomy). In some cases, a nerve-sparing technique can be used to preserve ejaculation and fertility.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Radiation Therapy: High-energy X-rays or other forms</li> 	</ul> 	</li> </ol>', 'Testicular cancer.png'),
(96, 10, 'Acne', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Acne</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Acne is a common skin condition that occurs when hair follicles become clogged with oil and dead skin cells. It most commonly affects teenagers but can occur at any age. Acne typically appears on the face, forehead, chest, back, and shoulders. Here is a comprehensive description of acne:</p>  <ol class=\"pl-3\"> <li> <p>Causes:</p> <ul> <li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Excess Oil Production: Increased oil (sebum) production by the sebaceous glands can contribute to the development of acne.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Clogged Hair Follicles: The excess oil combines with dead skin cells, clogging the hair follicles and forming comedones (whiteheads and blackheads).</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Bacteria: The Propionibacterium acnes (P. acnes) bacteria that naturally reside on the skin can multiply in clogged follicles, leading to inflammation.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Hormonal Changes: Hormonal fluctuations during puberty, menstrual cycles, pregnancy, or hormonal disorders can trigger acne.</li> <li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Certain Medications: Some medications, such as corticosteroids, androgenic steroids, and lithium, may contribute to acne development.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Diet: Although not fully understood, certain dietary factors, such as high glycemic index foods and dairy products, may exacerbate acne in some individuals.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Family History: A family history of acne can increase the likelihood of developing acne.</li> </ul> </li> 	<li> <p>Types of Acne Lesions:</p> <ul> <li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Comedones: Non-inflammatory lesions that can be open (blackheads) or closed (whiteheads).</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Papules: Small, red, raised bumps.</li> <li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pustules: Inflamed lesions filled with pus.</li> <li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Nodules: Large, painful, solid lesions beneath the skin.</li><li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Cysts: Painful, pus-filled, deep-seated lesions that can lead to scarring.</li> 	</ul> </li> <li> <p>Symptoms:</p> <ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Presence of different types of acne lesions, including comedones, papules, pustules, nodules, and cysts.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Redness and inflammation around the affected area.</li><li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Pain or tenderness in severe cases.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Scarring or pigmentation changes can occur if acne lesions are not properly treated.</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p>Treatment:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Over-the-Counter (OTC) Products: Topical creams, gels, or lotions containing ingredients like benzoyl peroxide, salicylic acid, or sulfur can help reduce mild acne.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Prescription Medications: Topical or oral medications, such as retinoids, antibiotics, or hormonal therapies, may be prescribed for moderate to severe acne.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Isotretinoin: This oral medication is used for severe, cystic acne that has not responded to other treatments. It requires close medical monitoring due to potential side effects.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Procedures: Dermatological procedures like chemical peels, microdermabrasion, laser therapy, or extraction of comedones may be recommended to treat acne and minimize scarring.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Skincare Practices: Gentle cleansing of the affected area, avoiding harsh scrubbing, and using non-comedogenic (non-pore-clogging) products can help manage acne.</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p>Self-Care Tips:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Keep the affected area clean by washing twice daily with a gentle cleanser.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Avoid squeezing or picking at acne lesions, as it can worsen inflammation and increase the risk of scarring.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Use oil-free, non-comedogenic cosmetics and skincare products.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Protect the skin from excessive sun exposure and use non-comedogenic sunscreen.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Maintain a healthy diet and lifestyle, including a balanced diet, regular exercise, and stress management.</li> 	</ul> 	</li> </ol>  <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">It&#39;s important to note that the severity of acne can vary from person to person, and treatment approaches may differ accordingly. If acne significantly affects self-esteem or does not respond to self</p>', 'Acne.png'),
(97, 10, 'Eczema', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Eczema</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Eczema, also known as atopic dermatitis, is a chronic skin condition characterized by inflammation, dryness, itching, and rashes. It is a common condition that affects people of all ages, but it often begins in early childhood and may persist into adulthood. Here is a comprehensive description of eczema:</p>  <ol class=\"pl-3\"> 	<li> 	<p>Causes and Triggers:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Genetic Factors: Eczema tends to run in families, suggesting a genetic predisposition to the condition.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Immune System Dysfunction: People with eczema have an overactive immune system that responds excessively to irritants and allergens.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Skin Barrier Dysfunction: Eczema is associated with defects in the skin&#39;s protective barrier, allowing moisture to escape and irritants to penetrate.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Environmental Triggers: Various environmental factors can exacerbate eczema symptoms, including dry air, hot or cold weather, exposure to irritants (such as chemicals or harsh soaps), allergens (such as pollen, pet dander, or dust mites), and certain fabrics or clothing materials.</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p>Symptoms:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Dry, sensitive skin: Eczema often causes dryness, roughness, and flakiness of the skin.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Itching: Intense itching is a hallmark symptom of eczema, leading to scratching that can further irritate the skin.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Redness and Inflammation: Affected skin areas may appear red, swollen, and inflamed.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Rashes and Lesions: Eczema rashes are typically patchy, may be raised or have a rough texture, and can develop blisters that may ooze or crust over.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Thickened, Leathery Skin: Over time, constant scratching and inflammation can lead to thickening and hardening of the skin in affected areas (known as lichenification).</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p>Types of Eczema:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Atopic Dermatitis: The most common form of eczema, often associated with a family history of allergies or asthma.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Contact Dermatitis: Caused by direct contact with irritants or allergens, such as certain soaps, detergents, metals, or plants.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Nummular Dermatitis: Characterized by circular or coin-shaped patches of irritated skin.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Seborrheic Dermatitis: Affects areas rich in oil glands, such as the scalp (dandruff) or face (cradle cap in infants).</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Dyshidrotic Eczema: Manifests as small, itchy blisters on the palms, fingers, and soles of the feet.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Stasis Dermatitis: Occurs in the lower legs due to poor circulation and fluid buildup.</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p>Treatment:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Moisturizers: Regular and adequate use of moisturizers helps hydrate the skin, restore its barrier function, and reduce dryness and itching.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Topical Corticosteroids: These anti-inflammatory creams or ointments are commonly prescribed to reduce inflammation and relieve symptoms during flare-ups.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Topical Calcineurin Inhibitors: Non-steroidal creams or ointments that help modulate the immune response and reduce inflammation.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Antihistamines: Oral antihistamines may be recommended to relieve itching and improve sleep.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Wet Wrap Therapy: In severe cases, wet wraps can be used to enhance the absorption of moisturizers and medications while providing a cooling effect.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Avoiding Triggers: Identifying and avoiding triggers that worsen eczema symptoms, such as certain foods, fabrics, or environmental factors.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Phototherapy: Controlled exposure to ultraviolet light, under medical supervision, can help reduce inflammation and improve symptoms.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Systemic Medications: In severe or refr</li> 	</ul> 	</li> </ol>', 'Eczema.png'),
(99, 10, 'Skin cancer', '<h3 style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight:600;\">Skin cancer</h3><p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Skin cancer refers to the abnormal growth of skin cells, typically caused by the uncontrolled development of damaged skin cells. It is the most common type of cancer globally, and it primarily affects areas of the skin exposed to sunlight. There are several types of skin cancer, including basal cell carcinoma, squamous cell carcinoma, and melanoma. Here is a comprehensive description of skin cancer:</p>  <ol class=\"pl-3\"> 	<li> 	<p>Types of Skin Cancer:</p>  	<ul> 		<li> <p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Basal Cell Carcinoma (BCC): BCC is the most common form of skin cancer. It usually develops in areas exposed to the sun, such as the face, neck, scalp, and shoulders. BCC often appears as a raised, pearly bump or a pinkish patch of skin that may bleed or develop a crust. It grows slowly and rarely spreads to other parts of the body.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Squamous Cell Carcinoma (SCC): SCC is the second most common type of skin cancer. It typically occurs on sun-exposed areas but can also develop on scars, sores, or chronic skin ulcers. SCC often appears as a firm, red nodule, a scaly patch, or a sore that fails to heal. It may grow and spread more aggressively than BCC, potentially reaching nearby lymph nodes.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Melanoma: Melanoma is a less common but more aggressive type of skin cancer. It can develop from existing moles or appear as a new, unusual growth. Melanoma typically presents as an asymmetrical mole or lesion with irregular borders, varied coloration, and a larger diameter (greater than 6mm). Melanoma can spread to other parts of the body if not detected and treated early, making it potentially life-threatening.</p> 		</li> 		<li> 		<p style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Other Types: Other less common types of skin cancer include Merkel cell carcinoma, dermatofibrosarcoma protuberans, and various rare skin lymphomas.</p> 		</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p>Risk Factors:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Ultraviolet (UV) Radiation Exposure: Excessive exposure to UV radiation from the sun or tanning beds is the primary risk factor for skin cancer.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Fair Skin: People with lighter skin tones are more susceptible to skin damage from UV radiation.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Family History: Having a family history of skin cancer increases the risk.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Personal History: Previous skin cancer or precancerous skin lesions raise the likelihood of developing new skin cancers.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Immunosuppression: Weakened immune systems, such as those in organ transplant recipients or individuals with certain diseases, increase the risk.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Certain Moles or Skin Conditions: Having many moles or atypical moles, as well as certain inherited conditions like xeroderma pigmentosum or basal cell nevus syndrome, can increase the risk of developing skin cancer.</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p>Symptoms:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Changes in the Skin: Any changes in the appearance of the skin, such as the development of new moles or growths, changes in existing moles, or non-healing sores, should be evaluated by a healthcare professional.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Asymmetry: Irregular or asymmetric shape of moles or lesions.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Border Irregularity: Jagged or blurred edges of moles or lesions.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Color Variation: Moles or lesions with uneven coloration, such as different shades of brown, black, red, white, or blue.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Diameter: Moles or lesions larger than 6mm in diameter.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Evolution: Moles or lesions that change in size, shape, color, or texture over time.</li> 	</ul> 	</li> 	<li> 	<p>Diagnosis:</p>  	<ul> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Visual Examination: A healthcare professional examines the skin, noting any suspicious areas.</li> 		<li style=\"text-align:justify;font-weight: normal;\">Skin Biopsy: If a suspicious lesion is found, a small sample of skin is removed for examination under a microscope to determine if cancer cells are present.</li> 	</ul> 	</li> </ol>', 'Skin cancer.png');
