(30, '1', 'Ankit Verma', '2024', 'male', '\n\nThe most likely diagnosis of a 7-day shoulder pain is musculoskeletal shoulder pain. To confirm this diagnosis, physical examination and imaging tests may be needed. Imaging tests such as an X-ray or MRI can help rule out any underlying medical conditions and provide a better understanding of the cause of the pain. Other tests, such as an electromyography (EMG) may also be helpful in assessing the shoulder muscles and nerves. Depending on the diagnosis, treatment options may include medications, physical therapy, or even surgery.'),
(31, '1', 'Ankit Verma', '2024', 'male', '\n\nThe first step in diagnosing the cause of shoulder pain following exercise would be a physical exam performed by a doctor or health care professional. During the exam, they may palpate (feel) around the shoulder to determine the location and type of pain. They may also check for signs of inflammation and range of motion. Depending on the findings, the doctor may suggest one or more of the following tests:\n\n1. Imaging tests such as x-ray, MRI, or ultrasound; \n2. Arthrography;\n3. Arthroscopy;\n4. Blood tests;\n5. Electromyography (EMG);\n6. Nerve testing. \n\nThe exact diagnosis and any recommended tests depend on the results of the physical exam and any other symptoms the patient is experiencing. Therefore, it\'s important to see a doctor for an evaluation and diagnosis.'),
(32, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nMouth sores can be a symptom of a variety of conditions, including viral infections, fungal infections, allergies, chemotherapy, and radiation. It is important to have a doctorevaluate the cause of your mouth sores in order to determine the best course of treatment. Your doctor may recommend clinical testing such as blood tests, X-Rays, or a biopsy.'),
(33, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nThe most likely diagnosis would be an infection which would probably require a diagnostic test such as a complete blood count, urinalysis, chest X-ray, and/or a throat culture. It is important to consult with a doctor to determine the best course of action and to rule out any underlying health issues.'),
(34, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nThe best way to diagnose a Fever is to get tested for any underlying infection or illness. Tests that may be recommended include a complete blood count (CBC), chest X-ray, urine culture, blood cultures, a throat culture, and a sputum culture. Your doctor can also order tests to determine if you have any underlying conditions, such a viral infections, bacterial infections, fungal infections, or even autoimmune disorders. Depending on the results from the tests and examinations your doctor can suggest a treatment plan designed to reduce your fever and help you feel better.'),
(35, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nChest pain can have a variety of causes, including musculoskeletal pain, heart-related pain, or even gastroenterological issues. It is important that you see a doctor as soon as possible so they can assess your symptoms and diagnose the cause of your chest pain. Depending on the root cause of your symptoms, some of the tests they may order include an electrocardiogram (ECG or EKG) to assess the electrical activity in your heart, imaging studies like a chest X-ray, MRI, or CT scan to check for any physical abnormalities, blood tests to check levels of enzymes or hormones, a stress test to check your heart\'s function while exercising, or an echocardiogram to assess your heart\'s size and shape.'),
(36, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nDiagnosis: \nPossible causes of weight loss include: malnutrition, malabsorption, endocrine disorders, metabolic disorders, gastrointestinal conditions, malignancy, medications, and chronic illnesses such as heart disease and cancer. \n\nTests:\nTo diagnose the cause of weight loss, your doctor may suggest certain tests, including: \n• Blood tests: including full blood count, electrolyte levels, liver function tests, kidney function tests and thyroid function tests \n• Imaging tests: including X-ray, CT scan or MRI\n• Gastroscopy: visual examination of the digestive tract with an endoscope\n• Colonoscopy: visual examination of the colon and rectum with an endoscope \n• Gastric emptying studies: to measure how quickly food leaves the stomach\n• Celiac disease antibody testing: to screen for celiac disease\n• Endoscopy: visual examination of the esophagus, stomach, and small intestine with an endoscope. \n• Stool tests: to screen for parasites, to look for gastrointestinal bleeding, or to measure malabsorption \n• Breath tests: to detect Helicobacter pylori infection or carbohydrate intolerance\n'),
(37, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nIt is possible that you have a gastrointestinal disorder. You should schedule a consultation with your doctor as soon as possible. They will be able to properly diagnose and treat your condition. Tests that may be ordered to help determine a diagnosis include a complete blood test, a stool sample analysis, a urine analysis, and imaging tests such as an ultrasound.'),
(38, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nThe first step in diagnosis is to have diagnostic tests done in order to better understand the underlying cause of your symptoms. These tests can include a complete blood count (CBC), urinalysis, stool tests for Blood and occult Blood, Ultrasound (or CT/MRI) of the Kidneys and urinary tract, and a kidney function tests. Based on the results of those tests, your doctor may order other tests such as a cystoscopy, IVP, or kidney biopsy. In addition, your doctor may ask questions about your medical history, diet, medications, family history, and symptoms in order to make a more accurate diagnosis.'),
(39, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nDiagnosing a fever can involve several steps. \n\nFirst, it is important to determine the cause of the fever. Depending on the accompanying symptoms, it may be something as simple as a viral illness, or something more serious such as an infection. In addition, age and medical history may play a role in identifying the underlying cause.\n\nSecond, your doctor will likely order several tests to make a definitive diagnosis. This could include a blood test to look for signs of infection, a urine test to look for bacteria in the urine, a chest X-ray to assess for pneumonia, or a sputum test to identify what type of bacteria is present in the lungs. Other tests may be ordered depending on the diagnosis the doctor is considering.\n\nFinally, if symptoms are severe enough, your doctor may recommend a course of antibiotics or other medications.'),
(40, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nIt is difficult to diagnose a medical condition simply based on a description of symptoms. A physical examination and lab tests may be needed. Generally, fever lasting more than 7 days warrants further investigation, especially if the fever is above 101°F and is accompanied by other symptoms such as chills, fatigue, headache, or loss of appetite. Some of the common tests to help diagnose the cause of the fever are blood tests, urine tests, chest X-ray, CT scans, and MRI. Depending on the symptoms, a doctor may recommend other tests specific to the suspected cause. Treatment and management of fever depends on the underlying diagnosis and the severity of presenting symptoms.'),
(41, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nSince you have been having fever for such a long period of time, it is recommended that you see a doctor to get a proper diagnosis. There is a variety of tests that your doctor may want to perform to determine the cause of your fever. These tests may include a complete blood count, urinalysis, chest X-ray, culture of blood or other body fluids, and more specialized tests such as MRI or CT scan. Along with these tests, your doctor may also want to perform a physical examination and ask about your medical history. Based on the results of these tests, your doctor will suggest the needed diagnosis and treatment.'),
(42, '19', 'Anshuman', '34', 'male', '\n\nFatigue can be a symptom of many conditions, including anemia, depression, diabetes, hypothyroidism, and chronic fatigue syndrome. In order to make a diagnosis, your doctor will need to evaluate your symptoms and conduct a physical exam. Additional testing may include blood tests, urine tests, imaging tests, and other specialized tests. The specific tests your doctor will order depend on your age, medical history, and the results of the physical exam.'),
(43, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nBased on your symptoms, it appears that you may be suffering from a viral or bacterial infection of the upper respiratory tract or lungs such as bronchitis, sinusitis, or pneumonia. To confirm the diagnosis and rule out other possible conditions, your doctor or healthcare provider will likely recommend a physical exam, chest X-ray, lab tests, sputum culture, or other tests as needed.'),
(44, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nA diagnosis cannot be determined without performing testing. Some tests that may be helpful in determining a diagnosis include a blood test for inflammatory markers, chest X-ray, urine analysis, and abdominal ultrasound. Depending upon the results of these tests, further testing or more specific testing may be suggested. In addition to testing, a physical exam and detailed history may provide additional information helpful in determining a diagnosis.'),
(45, '10', 'gufran', '25', 'male', '\n\nBased on your symptoms, some possible conditions you could be dealing with include the flu, pneumonia, bronchitis, or a urinary tract infection. To determine which condition you may have, your doctor may recommend certain blood tests, such as a full blood count, liver enzyme tests, a urine test, and a chest X-ray. Your doctor may also suggest other tests or scans depending on their findings.'),
(46, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nBased on the symptoms you listed before, the possible healthcare conditions that you may be dealing with include: digestive disorders (such as irritable bowel syndrome, diverticulitis, inflammatory bowel disease), abdominal infections (such as food poisoning or a UTI), gallbladder disorders (such as gallstones or cholecystitis), appendicitis, kidney stones, pancreatitis, or gastrointestinal tumors.\n\nIn order to diagnose your condition, your doctor may order blood tests, imaging tests (such as an ultrasound), a urine test, or other diagnostic tests. Blood tests that you doctor may order in order to help diagnose the cause of your abdominal pain include a complete blood count (CBC), blood chemistry tests (such as a liver function test or pancreatic function test), a C-reactive protein test (to check for inflammation in the body), and a urinalysis.'),
(47, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', ' \n\nBased on your symptoms, you could be dealing with a variety of health conditions, including infection, inflammatory bowel disease, gastroesophageal reflux disease, irritable bowel syndrome, gallbladder disease, appendicitis, and even cancer. It is important to see your doctor for a diagnosis since many of these conditions come with similar symptoms and may require different types of testing. \n\nYour doctor may recommend a physical exam, blood tests, urinalysis, abdominal imaging (such as an abdominal ultrasound or CT scan), or sigmoidoscopy to further investigate your condition. Blood tests may include a complete blood cell count, C-reactive protein (CRP), erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR), electrolyte panel, and liver function tests.'),
(48, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nBased on the symptoms that you have listed, it is difficult to accurately diagnose your condition without conducting a physical examination or performing tests. A few conditions that could be causing your fever include infection (viral, bacterial, or fungal), inflammatory conditions (such as lupus or reactive arthritis), and malignancies (such as lymphoma or leukemia).\n\nYour doctor may request blood tests to look for an underlying cause of your fever, such as a complete blood count (CBC), blood culture, C-reactive protein (CRP), erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR), and tests to screen for infections such as HIV, Lyme disease, hepatitis, and syphilis. Depending on your symptoms and medical history, your doctor may also order additional tests to help diagnose the cause of your fever.'),
(49, '16', 'Neeraj Rai', '25', 'male', '\n\nThe possible healthcare conditions you could be dealing with include upper respiratory infections, sinus infections, strep throat, bronchitis, pneumonia, or asthma. For blood tests, your doctor will likely suggest having a complete blood count (CBC) and/or a rapid strep test. These tests can help diagnose infection as well as rule out other illnesses. Your doctor may order other tests depending on the results of these tests.'),
(50, '16', 'Neeraj Rai', '25', 'male', '\n\nThe possible healthcare conditions you could be dealing with include upper respiratory tract infection, bronchitis, sinusitis, and allergies. The blood tests your doctor should consider for you include a complete blood count, an analysis of your white blood cells, electrolyte levels, and tests for fever and infection.'),
(51, '10', 'gufran', '25', 'male', '\n\nBased on the symptoms listed, the possible healthcare conditions you could be dealing with include a common cold, flu, bronchitis, pneumonia, and sinus infection. Your doctor may recommend a complete blood count (CBC) test to check for signs of infection, as well as a chest x-ray and throat culture to check for any other underlying causes. Depending on your symptoms, they may also recommend an influenza or rapid antigen test as well. It is important to get a proper diagnosis and treatment from a medical professional if you are experiencing any of these symptoms.'),
(52, '10', 'gufran', '25', 'male', '\n\nPossible healthcare conditions: \n1. Influenza viral infection \n2. Bronchitis \n3. Respiratory syncytial virus \n4. Pneumonia \n\nBlood Test: \n1. Complete Blood Count (CBC) \n2. Urea and electrolytes \n3. Liver Function Test \n4. Coagulation Profile \n5. Chest X-ray \n6. Sputum culture and sensetivity test.'),
