(159, '16', 'Neeraj Rai', '25', 'male', '\n\nPossible healthcare conditions:\n\n1. Influenza\n2. Common cold \n3. Bronchitis\n4. Pneumonia\n5. Sinus infection \n6. Urinary tract infection\n\nBlood tests:\n\n1. Complete Blood Count (CBC) \n2. C-Reactive Protein\n3. Blood cultures\n4. Urinalysis \n5. Electrolyte tests\n6. Chest X-ray'),
(160, '16', 'Neeraj Rai', '25', 'male', '\n\nPossible Healthcare Conditions: \n1. Viral fever \n2. Flu \n3. Bacterial infection \n4. Upper respiratory infection\n\nBlood Tests: \n1. Complete Blood Count \n2. ESR \n3. Influenza test \n4. Strep test \n5. Culture and sensitivity testing'),
(161, '10', 'gufran', '25', 'male', '\n\nPossible Healthcare Conditions: \n1. Influenza \n2. Common Cold \n3. Viral Pneumonia \n4. Systemic Infect including Septicemia\n\nBlood Tests: \n1. Complete Blood Count (CBC) \n2. C-Reactive Protein (CRP) \n3. Blood Cultures \n4. Cardiac Enzymes (CK and Troponin I and T) \n5. Blood Urea Nitrogen (BUN) and Creatinine Levels.'),
(162, '10', 'gufran', '25', 'male', '\n\nPossible healthcare conditions: \n1. Viral Infection \n2. Flu \n3. Bronchitis \n4. Pneumonia \n\nBlood tests: \n1. Complete Blood Count Test \n2. Blood Culture \n3. Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate \n4. C-Reactive Protein Test \n5. Chest X-Ray'),
(163, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nPossible Healthcare Conditions:\n1. Influenza \n2. Respiratory Infection \n3. Viral Infection\n4. Fever of Unknown Origin \n\nBlood Tests:\n1. Complete Blood Count \n2. Blood Culture \n3. Urine Dipstick \n4. Stool Examination \n5. Liver Function Test \n6. Chest X-Ray \n7. Thyroid Function Test \n8. Swab Test (Nasopharyngeal)'),
(164, '20', 'Surag K R', '34', 'male', '\n\nPossible healthcare conditions:\n\n1. Viral or bacterial throat infection\n2. Bronchitis \n3. Asthma \n4. Pneumonia \n\nBlood Tests:\n\n1. Complete Blood Count (CBC) Test\n2. C-Reactive Protein (CRP) Test\n3. Interleukin 6 (IL-6) Test\n4. Fecal Occult Blood Test (FOBT) \n5. Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate (ESR) Test\n6. Antibody Titre Test'),
(165, '20', 'Surag K R', '34', 'male', '\n\nPossible healthcare conditions: \n1. Influenza \n2. Common cold \n3. Acute bronchitis \n4. Mononucleosis \n5. Strep throat\n\nTests:\n1. CBC (Complete Blood Count)\n2. Throat Swab Culture  \n3. Urine Culture\n4. Rapid Strep Test\n5. Blood culture for Bacterial identification \n6. Serology Test for Viral identification.'),
(166, '10', 'gufran', '25', 'male', '\n\nPossible Healthcare Conditions: \n\n-Viral Infection \n-Bacterial Infection \n-Influenza \n-Mononucleosis \n\nBlood Test: \n\n-Complete Blood Count (CBC) \n-Reverse Transcription Polymerase Chain Reaction (RT-PCR) \n-Blood Culture for Bacteria \n-Urine Culture \n-Throat Swab \n-ESR or erythrocyte sedimentation rate'),
(167, '10', 'gufran', '25', 'male', '\n\nPossible healthcare conditions:\n\n1. Influenza \n2. Viral Infection \n3. Upper Respiratory Infection \n4. Pneumonia \n5. Bacterial Infection \n\nSuggested Tests:\n\n1. Complete Blood Count (CBC) \n2. Blood Culture \n3. Urinalysis and Urinary Culture \n4. Throat Swab Culture \n5. X-ray \n6. Stool Test'),
(168, '10', 'gufran', '25', 'male', '\n\nPossible healthcare conditions: \n1. Influenza \n2. Common cold \n3. Lyme disease \n4. Viral gastroenteritis \n\nBlood tests: \n1. Complete blood count (CBC) \n2. C-reactive protein (CRP) test \n3. Erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) test \n4. Urine culture test \n5. Antibody test \n6. Antiviral Screening test \n7. Chest X-ray \n8. Electrolyte Blood test'),
(169, '16', 'Neeraj Rai', '25', 'male', '\n\nPossible Healthcare Conditions:\n1. Viral Infection\n2. Influenza\n3. Pneumonia\n\nBlood Tests:\n1. Full Blood Count Test\n2. C-Reactive Protein Test \n3. Urine Test\n4. Chest X-Ray'),
(170, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nGiven the duration and the collection of symptoms, it is sensible to see a physician, to make sure there is a proper diagnosis. It is especially important to seek medical care if the fever persists for more than four days, or rises above 102-degrees Fahrenheit. Possible medical conditions could include:\n\n- Influenza \n- COVID-19\n- Mono\n- Lyme Disease \n- Meningitis\n\nIt would be wise to discuss the following blood tests with your doctor:\n\n- Complete Blood Count (CBC) Test \n- C-Reactive Protein (CRP) Test\n- Antibody testing to measure immunity to certain viruses, i.e. HIV \n- Monospot Test to detect the Epstein-Barr virus which is associated with Mononucleosis \n- Urine Culture to detect any infections in the urinary tract\n- Thyroid Stimulating Hormone (TSH) testing to detect any thyroid issues \n- Rheumatoid Factor (RF) Test to detect any issues with joints.'),
(171, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nHaving a sore throat for 5 days could be caused by a number of different underlying conditions, including viral, bacterial, and allergic causes. It is essential to identify the underlying cause of your sore throat in order to ensure a proper treatment plan. It is recommended to discuss your symptoms with your doctor to rule out any serious illnesses. There are two common types of blood tests recommended for a sore throat: a Monospot test and a Complete Blood Count (CBC). \n\nPossible healthcare conditions: \n1. Viral Pharyngitis\n2. Bacterial Pharyngitis \n3. Allergic Rhinitis\n4. Tonsillitis\n5. Acute laryngitis\n6. Epstein-Barr virus (EBV)\n7. Mononucleosis\n\nTests: \n1. Monospot test: This test is used to look for antibodies that indicate infectious mononucleosis, which is one possible cause of sore throat. \n2. Complete Blood Count (CBC): The CBC gives health professionals important information about the number and types of cells in the blood, and can help to diagnose numerous conditions and illnesses.'),
(172, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nIt is important to pay attention to any weight loss symptoms that occur over a sustained period of time because it can result in serious underlying health conditions. When losing weight over a period of 30 days, it is highly recommended to speak with a doctor to discuss potential medical causes and preventive measures to take. Common healthcare conditions with weight loss symptoms that occur over 30 days include:\n\n1. Diabetes: Blood tests such as fasting blood glucose, glycated hemoglobin (A1C), and oral glucose tolerance tests can be used to diagnose or monitor the condition.\n\n2. Celiac disease: Blood tests like tissue transglutaminase antibody (tTG-IgA), endomysial antibody (EMA-IgA), deamidated gliadin peptide (DGP-IgA), gliadin/disease-related IgA/IgG antibodies can all be used to diagnose or monitor celiac disease.\n\n3. Hyperthyroidism: Tests such as Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH), free thyroxine (free T4), or triiodothyronine (free T3) are generally ordered to look for possible cases of an overactive thyroid.\n\n4. Cancer: Blood tests such as complete blood count (CBC), liver function tests, and tumor markers are often suggested to detect any abnormal growth in the body.\n\n5. Gastrointestinal issues: Blood tests such as C-reactive protein (CRP) and fecal occult blood tests can be used to detect inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) and other digestive issues.\n\n6. HIV/AIDS: HIV antibody tests or even a polymerase chain reaction (PCR) test are used to detect any abnormalities. \n\n7. Anemia: Tests such as complete blood count (CBC), iron, total iron-binding capacity (TIBC), and ferritin tests are used to detect anemia.\n\nThese are only a few examples of possible healthcare conditions that may cause weight loss symptoms over a period of 30 days. Your doctor may suggest other tests and healthcare conditions during your visit.'),
(173, '1', 'Ankit Verma', '2024', 'male', '\n\nIt is important to take note of any abnormal symptoms such as sore throat and weight loss, as these can be indicative of underlying health issues. Sore throat and weight loss together can indicate a variety of health conditions, including viral infections, bacterial infections, autoimmune diseases, digestive tract issues, and even certain cancerous conditions. To determine the underlying cause, a doctor should be consulted and lab tests conducted.\n\nThe following tests should be recommended by a doctor for investigating the cause of age throat and weight loss over two days: \n\n1. Complete blood count with differential (CBC)\n2. Liver enzyme test (LFT)\n3. Kidney function tests (urine and blood)\n4. Thyroid test\n5. Ferritin levels \n6. Tests for common viruses like Epstein-Barr virus, hepatitis virus, and human immunodeficiency virus (HIV)\n\nSome of the possible medical conditions that could cause both sore throat and weight loss, include: \n\n1. Viral infections, such as the common cold, influenza, and mononucleosis\n2. Bacterial infections, such as strep throat or tonsillitis\n3. Lung bacterial infections, such as pneumonia\n4. Autoimmune diseases, such as lupus and rheumatoid arthritis\n5. Digestive tract issues, such as acid reflux, celiac disease, or irritable bowel syndrome (IBS)\n6. Hypothyroidism\n7. Cancer, including lymphomas and other malignancies\n8. Chronic stress or depression\n9. Anorexia nervosa or bulimia nervosa'),
(174, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nGiven the symptoms of Fever, Sore throat, Fatigue, Bruising and bleeding, it is important to discuss these with a healthcare professional to identify any possible underlying health conditions. Such symptoms may indicate a wide array of health conditions and can be treated effectively with the right diagnosis; therefore, seeking professional help is essential. Tests you could discuss with your doctor may include a complete blood count (CBC), a comprehensive metabolic panel (CMP), viral culture for throat swab, human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) tests, drug screening, among many other tests depending on the diagnosis.\n\nPossible Healthcare Conditions: \n1. Acute Viral Syndrome\n2. Mono/Infectious Mononucleosis \n3. Sepsis\n4. Diabetes\n5. Blood Clotting Disorder\n6. Anemia\n7. Leukemia\n8. Blood Infection/Septicemia\n9. Pneumonia\n10. Lyme Disease\n\nTests:\n1. Complete Blood Count (CBC)\n2. Comprehensive Metabolic Panel (CMP)\n3. Viral Culture for Throat Swab\n4. Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) Tests\n5. Drug Screening\n6. X-Ray\n7. Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI)\n8. Urinalysis\n9. Arterial Blood Gas\n10. Thromboplastin Time Test'),
(175, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', ' \n\nGiven the fact that you have been suffering from enlarged liver and spleen for 30 days, it is important that you seek professional medical assistance as soon as possible. There are various possible health conditions that could be associated with these symptons which are as follows:\n\nHealth Conditions:\n\n1. Viral hepatitis: This is an infection of the liver caused by one of the hepatitis viruses, like hepatitis B or C. \n\n2. Gallbladder disease: This is when your gallbladder becomes inflamed from infection or gallstones.\n\n3. Mononucleosis: Mono is an infection caused by a virus that can lead to an enlarged spleen.\n\n4. Liver cancer: An enlarged liver can be a sign of liver cancer. \n\n5. Cirrhosis: This is a condition where the liver tissue becomes scarred and less able to function. It is often caused by long-term alcohol or drug abuse.\n\n6. Pancreatitis: Inflammation of the pancreas can cause enlargement of the organs nearby, including the liver and spleen.\n\nBlood Tests: \n\n1. Complete blood count (CBC): This will help detect anemia or infection, which can be associated with an enlarged liver or spleen.\n\n2. Liver function tests: These tests help determine how well the liver is functioning.\n\n3. Amylase and lipase tests: These tests are used to diagnose inflamed or infected pancreas. \n\n4. Antibodies tests: This will detect whether a person has had certain viruses, such as mononucleosis. \n\n5. Imaging tests: These tests are used to detect the size and shape of the liver and spleen, and can also be used to diagnose liver cancer. \n\nIt is highly recommended for you to discuss with your doctor about these health conditions and blood tests to determine the cause of your symptoms.'),
(176, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '34', 'male', '\n\nChest pain is a common symptom that can be caused by several potential health conditions. It is important to discuss any chest pain that lasts more than one day with a doctor as it may be a sign of something more severe. Common health conditions that could cause chest pain include cardiac problems, musculoskeletal conditions, inflammation of the rib muscles or tendons, or gastrointestinal disturbances such as acid reflux.\n\nTo diagnose the source of chest pain, it is vital to discuss the symptoms with a doctor and ask for the appropriate blood tests. Some tests that may be relevant include: \n\n1. Blood tests to evaluate cardiac enzymes, such as creatine phosphokinase, troponin I, and myoglobin \n2. Blood tests to evaluate possible issues with inflammation, including erythrocyte sedimentation rate and C-reactive protein \n3. Full blood count, which assesses red and white blood cell counts\n4. Plasma glucose, to assess blood sugar levels\n5. Tests to assess the possible presence of infection, such as Urea and Electrolytes, Liver Function Tests and test for viruses such as HIV \n6. Tests to assess potential risk factors for cardiac conditions, including cholesterol and lipids, electrolyte levels, and thyroid function tests'),
(177, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nIntroducing the combination of Fever and Coughing as symptoms, it is important to take such symptoms seriously to avoid any serious turmoil. Therefore, it is essential to determine the possible health condition faced and to proceed with the essential blood tests to arrive at an accurate diagnosis. \n\nFollowing are some of the possible health conditions that can be associated with such symptoms: \n\n1. Influenza: It is a virus, commonly known as the ‘flu’, which can cause fever, fatigue, aching muscles, headaches, sore throats, coughing, and block the nose. \n\n2. Common Cold: It is a viral infection that affects the upper respiratory system and can cause symptoms such as sore throat, fever, runny nose, coughing, headaches, fatigue, and more.\n\n3. Respiratory Tract Infection: This infection can happen in the sinuses, throat, voice boxes, lungs, or windpipes also called bronchitis. Common symptoms include sore throat, coughing, fever, wheezing, chest pain, and fatigue.\n\n4. Bronchitis: It is an inflammation of the bronchial tubes in the lungs and can cause a severe chest cold with coughing, slowed breathing, and problem in breathing.  \n\nBlood tests that should be considered to accurately diagnose the health condition include: \n\n1. Complete Blood Count (CBC) - a CBC measures the levels of red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets in the body. These cells give information related to the infection and anemia.\n\n2. Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate (ESR) - It measures the level of inflammation and gives an indication of any infection.\n\n3. Chest X-Ray - It helps to get images of the lungs to detect any occurrence of a viral or bacterial infection.\n\n4. Blood Culture Tests - It looks for any bacteria in the blood and gives information about the type of the infection and the causative agent. \n\nIt is of utmost importance to consult a doctor for prescription of medicine and further treatment to cure the health conditions discussed.'),
(178, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nIt is important to pay attention to your body and be aware of the early sign of serious health conditions like fever or sore throat. In this case, based on your symptoms of fever for 3 days and sore throat for 2 days, there are a few healthcare conditions that could be causing these; these include Flu, Common cold, Strep throat, Mononucleosis and Bronchitis. Other serious health issues that could also be causing this could be Tonsillitis, Influenza, Meningitis and Pneumonia. \n\nBlood Tests that should be discussed regarding these symptoms are Complete Blood Count (CBC), Throat cultures, Monospot test, Antibody tests and Antigen test. These are some tests that can help diagnose any underlying medical conditions.'),
(179, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nIt is important to pay attention to changes in our physical and mental state. Fever and cough are two common symptoms of a variety of health conditions. Possible healthcare conditions that could be related to your 2 days of fever and cough include a common cold, bronchitis, pneumonia, sinusitis, influenza, and COVID-19.\n\nIt is recommended to speak to your doctor and/or healthcare provider to receive a thorough diagnosis of your condition. It is also recommended to have tests done to rule out other possible diagnoses. Tests that should be discussed with a doctor include a physical examination, complete blood count, chest X-ray, and sputum culture. Additionally, depending on the diagnosis, tests like blood culture, throat swab of nasopharyngeal swab, urine test, and a hepatitis test should be discussed with your doctor.'),
(180, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nAs cough and runny or stuffy nose are two of the most common respiratory illnesses, it is important to recognize and treat any potential underlying cause. Possible health care conditions that could be caused by these symptoms include:\n\n1. Common cold: This acute viral infection is caused by the rhinovirus and is characterized by runny nose, cough, sore throat, and fatigue.\n\n2. Allergy: Prolonged exposure to certain allergens can lead to chronic sinus infection, which can cause prolonged coughing and runny nose.\n\n3. Bronchitis: This form of respiratory infection causes inflammation of the bronchial tubes and can lead to coughing and runny nose.\n\n4. Asthma: This chronic pulmonary disorder may cause coughing and wheezing.\n\n5. Pneumonia: This bacterial or viral infection affects the lungs and can lead to symptoms such as cough and shortness of breath.\n\nTo further investigate these causes, it is recommended that you undergo blood tests. These tests may include complete blood count, chest X-ray, comprehensive metabolic panel, and sputum culture. Some additional tests may include culture tests for bacteria and viruses, pulmonary function test, and allergy tests. It is important to consult your doctor for the appropriate blood tests for your symptoms.'),
(181, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nThe runny nose is a common symptom for an array of illnesses and should not be taken for granted. It is essential to identify the right condition in order to choose the appropriate treatment. Here are the potential conditions and blood tests that might be discussed with a doctor : \n\n1. Allergic Rhinitis: skin prick test, total IgE (Immunoglobulin E) levels, and allergy panel. \n\n2. Viral Infection: Complete Blood Count (CBC) and Blood Culture test.\n\n3. Bacterial Infection: Widal Test and Complete Blood Count (CBC).\n\n4. Sinusitis: sinus CT scan, nasal smear test, and X-ray. \n\n5. Autoimmune Disorders: ANA (Antinuclear Antibody Test), Anti-dsDNA (Double Stranded DNA) Antibodies, and RF/ASO (Rheumatoid Factor/ Anti-streptolysin O) Test. \n\n6. Nonallergic Rhinitis: Immunoglobulin E levels, nasal smear test, and Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI). \n\nIn order to identify the underlying cause and facilitate an effective treatment for the runny nose, the aforementioned tests should be discussed with a doctor. '),
(182, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nIt is important to understand the severity and cause of any ongoing symptoms, particularly when a fever has persisted for several days. Continuous Fever is a symptom which can be indicative of multiple underlying health conditions, ranging from mild to severe diseases like Influenza, Diabetes, Blood Clotting Disorders, Tuberculosis, Typhoid and other viral infections, among others. It is also important to consider underlying factors such as lifestyle habits, existing environmental conditions, contact with other people, etc. The following blood tests should be discussed with your doctor to evaluate the possible causes of your Fever:\n\n-White Blood Cell Count \n-Complete Blood Count \n-Antinuclear Antibody Test \n-Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate \n-Blood cultures \n-Glucose tests \n-Blood clotting tests \n-Kidney Function tests\n-Liver Function Tests \n-Thyroid Function Tests. \n\nHealth Conditions associated with continuous Fever:\n-Influenza \n-Chikungunya\n-Cytomegalovirus Infection \n-Toxoplasmosis \n-Typhoid \n-Malaria\n-Dengue \n-Upper Respiratory Tract Infection \n-Hepatitis \n-Tuberculosis \n-HIV/AIDS \n-Mononucleosis \n-Meningitis \n-Lyme Disease.'),
(183, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nTaking note of your Fever and Rhinorrhea (i.e. Runny or Stuffy Nose) of 5 days is extremely important when it comes to pinpointing the root cause of your symptoms. It is important to consult a proficient medical professional for obtaining accurate diagnosis and further investigations. \n\nGiven below are list of probable medical conditions and recommended blood tests that doctor will discuss with you:\n\n• Common Cold: To rule out this condition, a doctor may recommend a blood test to rule out viruses which can cause common cold.\n\n• Flu (Influenza): Blood Test to detect influenza and other respiratory viruses.\n\n• Allergies: Allergy testing including skin prick testing, RAST (Radioallergo sorbent test) or patch testing can be conducted to identify the nature of the allergen causing your symptoms. \n\n• Sinusitis: CT Scan of the sinuses and a sputum test can be conducted to diagnose sinusitis. \n\n• Bronchitis: X-ray and sputum analysis can be done to diagnose bronchitis.\n\n• Pneumonia: Chest X-Ray combined with a blood test known as Complete Blood Count (CBC) can confirm the presence of pneumonia.\n\n• Tuberculosis: Blood Test known as Mycobacterium Tuberculosis Complex PCR Test is used to detect and diagnose Tuberculosis. \n\nGiven above are list of potential medical conditions and related investigations that can be discussed with doctor. It is imperative to consult your doctor for further medical advice.'),
(184, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nWith a fever lasting 5 days, it is important to obtain medical advice. Without accurate diagnosis, it is impossible to determine the underlying cause of the fever. Potential health conditions that may warrant diagnostic tests include bacterial or viral infection, influenza, upper respiratory tract infection, pneumonia, malaria, dengue fever, heart disease, certain autoimmune diseases, thyroid disease, and liver disease.\n\nA series of laboratory tests—such as a complete blood count (CBC), erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR), C-reactive protein (CRP), electrolytes panel, prothrombin time (PT) and partial thromboplastin time (PTT)—should be carried out in order to identify any underlying health condition related to the fever. Additionally, blood cultures can help identify bacterial infections while testing for antibodies specific to the virus can help confirm the diagnosis of viral illnesses. '),
(185, '10', 'gufran', '25', 'male', '\n\nPain and swelling in the abdomen are often a sign of a medical condition, and it is important to address these symptoms as soon as possible. Possible healthcare conditions related to abdominal pain and swelling include appendicitis, gallbladder inflammation, irritable bowel syndrome, diverticulitis, urinary tract infection, Crohn’s Disease, and an abdominal hernia. Additionally, blood tests that could be discussed with a doctor include testing for a complete blood count, electrolyte panel to evaluate for dehydration, kidney function tests, abdominal ultrasound, and stool tests.'),
(186, '10', 'gufran', '25', 'male', '\n\nIt is essential to identify and follow up on the symptoms listed in order to ensure the best possible health outcome. The sensations of numbness or tingling and persistent cough that have been present for 1 day and 5 days respectively could potentially indicate the presence of one of several health conditions. It is essential to discuss the following with your doctor for proper diagnosis along with the recommended accompanying blood tests. \n\nPotential Health Conditions: \n1. Asthma: Asthma is an inflammatory disorder of the airways, which causes recurrent episodes of breathing difficulties. Blood tests to detect the presence of asthma include a complete blood count (CBC) and eosinophil count.\n2. Dermatitis: Dermatitis is the presence of a red, itchy, and sometimes swollen rash on the skin. Blood tests to determine if the patient has an allergic reaction due to the dermatitis include a complete blood count (CBC) to detect an increase in white blood cells and an IgE test to measure allergic antibodies.\n3. Stroke: Stroke is the second leading cause of death globally and is caused by disruption in blood supply to the brain. Blood tests to help diagnose stroke include a complete blood count (CBC) to detect signs of inflammation in the body, as well as tests to measure blood sugar levels, electrolyte levels, and cholesterol levels.\n\nIt is also essential to identify and rule out other illnesses, such as Lyme disease, Multiple Sclerosis, and Pulmonary Embolism, which may have similar symptoms as the aforementioned conditions. Accordingly, the following blood tests should also be discussed with the doctor in order to rule out other potential illnesses: \n1. Lyme disease Panel: A Lyme disease panel is a group of tests that are used to identify the presence of antibodies to bacteria that causes Lyme disease. \n2. Multiple Sclerosis Panel: A Multiple Sclerosis panel is a group of tests that are used to diagnose the presence of autoantibodies that are linked to the autoimmune disorder. \n3. Pulmonary Embolism Screening: A pulmonary embolism screening is a group of tests that are used to identify the presence of a clot in the lungs. \n\nThe aforementioned test results should be taken into consideration in order to aid in the diagnosis and treatment of the patient’s symptoms and condition.'),
(187, '10', 'gufran', '25', 'male', '\n\nIt is important to take into consideration any physical symptoms you may be experiencing as they can be a sign of underlying medical condition. If you are having khujli for 10 days, there are several possible health conditions that could be to blame, including fungal infection, eczema, atopic dermatitis, and contact dermatitis. To best determine what is causing your symptoms, you should speak with your doctor and discuss the following tests: \n\n• Allergy testing \n• Skin culture \n• Complete blood count \n• Thyroid tests \n• Iron levels \n• Specifically, serology tests for HIV and other infections that may cause skin disorder \n• Liver function tests \n• Urinalysis.'),
(188, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nGiven the symptoms of mouth sores and a sore throat, it is important to determine the underlying cause. It is possible that the symptoms are indicative of a number of oral and throat conditions, ranging from infections to immune disorders. Possible healthcare conditions associated with these symptoms include:\n\n1. Oral infections such as cold sores (herpes simplex virus) and canker sores (aphthous stomatitis/ulcers).\n\n2. Throat infections such as strep throat (streptococcal pharyngitis) or an infection of the tonsils (tonsillitis).\n\n3. Allergic reactions or irritation from certain foods or substances.\n\n4. Immune-related conditions such as lupus, Behçet’s syndrome, or lichen planus.\n\nIt is recommended to speak with a doctor to determine which healthcare condition is causing the symptoms. They may decide to order any of the following blood tests to help with the diagnosis: \n\n1. Complete Blood Count (CBC) - evaluates the number of red and white blood cells in the blood.\n\n2. C-reactive protein (CRP) test - measures the amount of inflammation in the body.\n\n3. Erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) - measures the rate of red blood cells in the blood.\n\n4. Antinuclear antibody (ANA) test - checks for conditions that affect the immune system.\n\n5. Mononucleosis test - detects Mono (Infectious Mononucleosis).\n\n6. Rheumatoid factor test - helps diagnose various forms of arthritis. \n\n7. HIV and Syphilis tests - detect the presence of viruses and bacteria that can cause mouth sores and sore throats.\n\nIt is important to speak with a doctor to determine the underlying cause of the symptoms and appropriate treatment options.'),
(189, '18', 'Kasi', '29', 'male', '\n\nGiven the information provided it is essential to understand that symptoms can vary from person to person and it is highly recommended to make an appointment to consult with medical professional to gain a better insight of the underlying root causes and for testing. Symptoms such as swollen lymph nodes, blood clots and eye inflammation can potentially point to a wide range of conditions that should be thoroughly investigated. \n\nBelow is a list of some of the possible healthcare conditions that you may be dealing with based on the mentioned symptoms: \n\n• Mononucleosis: A viral infection that can cause swollen lymph nodes, fever, sore throat, headache, and fatigue. \n\n• Blood Clotting Disorders: Disorders that are caused by abnormal clotting and are accompanied by swelling of the extremities, fatigue, shortness of breath and chest pain. \n\n• Lyme Disease: An infection caused by bacteria that can cause swollen lymph nodes, fever, skin rashes, fatigue, headaches and joint pain. \n\n• Shingles: A viral infection that can cause swollen lymph nodes, eye inflammation, headache, fever, and rash.\n\n• Rheumatoid Arthritis: An inflammatory condition that can cause swollen lymph nodes, joint pain, eye inflammation, and fatigue.\n\nIn terms of the blood tests that you should discuss with your doctor, these may include: \n• Complete Blood Count (CBC): This test looks for signs of infection and can help determine the nature of the problem.\n\n• C-Reactive Protein Test: This test helps detect inflammation in the body. \n\n• Antinuclear Antibody Test: This test is used to detect autoimmune diseases.\n\n• Blood Coagulation Tests: These tests are used to measure the levels of various clotting factors in the blood. \n\n• Lyme Disease Test: This test is used to detect the presence of Borrelia bacteria in the body.\n\nBased on the information provided, it is important to consult with a medical professional to explore further and to receive a diagnosis and treatment plan. The above listed tests are suggestions that should be discussed with your doctor in order to determine the best course of action for your healthcare needs.'),
(190, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nFeeling embarrassed is a common emotional symptom that may be associated with a range of physical and mental health problems. It is important to recognize such symptoms early and discuss them with a doctor to help diagnose and manage associated health problems. \n\nPossible healthcare conditions that may be related to feeling embarrassed include:\n\n1. Anxiety disorder: Anxiety disorder is a mental health condition characterized by feelings of fear, worry and nervousness. Common symptoms are difficulty concentrating, racing thoughts, and an inability to control worries.\n\n2. Depression: Depression is a mood disorder characterized by persistent feelings of sadness, lack of energy, and difficulty concentrating. Other common symptoms include changes in appetite or sleep patterns, feelings of guilt or worthlessness, and thoughts of death and suicide.\n\n3.Gastrointestinal problems: Feeling embarrassed may be a symptom of diverticulitis, irritable bowel syndrome, stomach ulcers, or other gastrointestinal problems.\n\n4. Crowding Effects: The feeling of embarrassment can be a reaction to feeling crowded or in crowded spaces.\n\nBlood tests to discuss with a doctor include:\n\n1. Complete Blood Count (CBC): This test can measure the number of red and white cells in the bloodstream, which can help determine if a person has an underlying infection or immune disorder.\n\n2. Complete Metabolic Panel (CMP): This test measures various electrolytes, enzymes, and metabolites in the blood. It can help to identify potential metabolic disorders, such as kidney problems or thyroid issues.\n\n3. Liver Function Test (LFT): This test measures levels of certain enzymes and other proteins in the blood to determine if there are any problems with the liver.\n\n4. Thyroid Stimulating Hormone (TSH): This test is used to measure hormone levels of the thyroid gland. Abnormal levels can point to an underactive or overactive thyroid.'),
(191, '10', 'gufran', '25', 'male', '\n\nSymptoms of fever can range from mild to severe, and it is important to seek medical advice if you experience any changes in your health. Possible healthcare conditions you may be dealing with include:\n\n- Viral Infection: Common viruses, such as influenza, parvovirus B19, and mononucleosis, can cause fever.\n\n- Bacterial Infection: Bacterial infections, such as strep throat and urinary tract infections, can lead to fever.\n\n- Autoimmune Conditions: Autoimmune conditions, such as rheumatoid arthritis and lupus, can cause low-grade fevers.\n\n- Medication Side Effects: Some medications, such as antibiotics and nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs, can lead to fever.\n\nIn order to diagnose the cause of your fever, your doctor may recommend the following blood tests: \n\n- Full blood count: A full blood count can help to identify if the fever is caused by a bacterial or viral infection.\n\n- C-reactive protein (CRP): To detect inflammation, the CRP blood test can be used.\n\n- Erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR): The ESR can measure the speed at which red blood cells settle at the bottom of a test tube and can be done to detect inflammation in the body.\n\n- Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH): A sample of your blood can be taken to determine if your fever is caused by thyroid disorder.\n\n- Blood cultures: Blood cultures can be taken to check for the presence of bacteria in the bloodstream.'),
(192, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nVomiting and fever can be concerning symptoms associated with a variety of healthcare conditions. It is important to discuss these symptoms with your doctor to investigate further and rule out any serious underlying health problems. Given below is a list of possible health conditions and the associated blood tests. \n\nPossible Healthcare Conditions:\n1. Infectious Diseases: \n• Influenza\n• Chickenpox\n• Meningitis\n• Hepatitis\n• Lyme disease\n• Strep throat\n• Tuberculosis\n• HIV\n• Malaria\n\nBlood Tests:\n• Complete Blood Count (CBC)\n• Electrolyte Panel\n• Liver Function Tests\n• Kidney Function Tests\n• C-Reactive Protein Test\n• Rheumatoid Factor Test\n• Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate (ESR)\n• Antinuclear Antibody Test (ANA)\n• Urine Culture and Sensitivity\n• Chest X-Ray\n• Blood cultures \n• C-reactive protein test.'),
(193, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nSeeing consistent symptoms like headache or vomiting for multiple days is always a reason to seek medical advice. Headache and vomiting could be indicative of various health issues, including but not limited to meningitis, brain aneurysm, bleeding within the skull, dehydration, dehydration, viral meningitis, sinusitis, diabetic ketoacidosis, appendicitis, kidney infection, concussion, gastroenteritis etc. To properly diagnose and treat the underlying cause, one should have their blood work and CT/MRI scans done. For the purpose of diagnosing, a doctor might suggest the following blood tests:\n\n1. Complete blood count (CBC): This test evaluates the number of red and white blood cells being produced by a person’s body.\n\n2. Kidney function test: It checks the functioning of kidney, which can be affected by certain infections.\n\n3. Liver function test: This test evaluates how well the liver is able to remove toxins and clean the blood.\n\n4. Electrolyte test: It helps to detect the levels of electrolytes such as potassium, calcium, magnesium, sodium, and chloride.\n\n5. Comprehensive metabolic panel (CMP): This test checks for substances like glucose, proteins, and electrolytes.\n\n6. Urinalysis: Targeting to identify infection, this test analyses urine composition.\n\nIt is advisable for one to consult their doctor and have their symptoms and tests discussed in order to get an accurate diagnosis.'),
(194, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nTaking into account the mentioned symptoms, it is important to seek medical advice in order to determine the health condition in question. Possible healthcare conditions that could be the cause of the itching include skin conditions such as eczema, psoriasis and ringworm; as well as an allergic reaction to a new product or food item. Additionally, the itching could be an indication of an infectious disease such as scabies, Lyme disease or chicken pox. \n\nIn order to determine the exact cause, it is important to discuss a full range of blood tests and examinations with the doctor, which could include: \n\n• Complete Blood Count test (CBC)\n• Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate (ESR or \"Sed rate\")\n• Liver enzyme tests\n• Thyroid function tests \n• Allergy testing (skin prick or RAST test)\n• Urine analysis \n• Stool analysis\n• Antinuclear antibody (ANA) test\n• ID Panel test (Infectious Disease)  \n• Urine Culture.'),
(195, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nSore throat is a common symptom of many different conditions, ranging from benign, such as a common cold or viral infection, to more serious, including bacterial and viral infections, allergies, and immune system illnesses. It is important to have any new or persistent sore throat evaluated by a health care professional to ensure an accurate diagnosis and appropriate course of treatment. Based on these symptoms, the following conditions and tests may be necessary to diagnose the underlying cause:\n \nHealth Conditions:\n1. Common Cold or Viral Infection: symptoms include congestion, sore throat, runny nose, sneezing, headache, and/or fever\n2. Bacterial Infections: bacterial infections of the throat can be caused by a virus, strep or other type of bacteria, and often involve fever, swollen lymph nodes, and/or white patches on the throat\n3. Allergies: an allergy to a food or airborne substance can cause sore throat, itchy throat, chest tightness, or difficulty breathing\n4. Immune System Illness: autoimmune or immune system illnesses, such as lupus or rheumatoid arthritis, can cause sore throat, fever, fatigue and other symptoms\n\nTests: \n1. Throat Culture: a sample will be taken from the throat and assessed to determine the presence of bacteria or viruses\n2. Blood Tests: to check for signs of inflammation, infection or allergies \n3. Allergy Test: skin tests or blood tests to identify an allergy trigger \n4. Imaging Tests: X-rays/CT scans to rule out structural or anatomical causes of throat pain.'),
(196, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', ' \n\nNausea is a common symptom of many health problems, ranging from minor digestive issues to serious illnesses. To accurately determine the cause of your nausea, it is important to discuss your symptoms with a health care professional. Additionally, specific blood tests may be recommended to diagnose underlying medical conditions. \n\nPossible healthcare conditions that could be causing your nausea include: \n\n1. Gastroenteritis: An infection that affects the digestive tract and can cause diarrhea and vomiting, as well as abdominal pain and nausea. \n\n2. Food poisoning: Contamination of food with bacteria or other toxins, which can lead to nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, and abdominal pain.\n\n3. Ulcers: Open sores in the lining of the stomach or intestines, which can lead to heartburn and nausea. \n\n4. Motion sickness: Nausea caused by movement and changes in the balance of the body.\n\n5. Pregnancy: Nausea is a common symptom experienced during the first trimester of pregnancy, otherwise known as morning sickness.\n\n6. Gallstones: Stones or deposits in the gallbladder, which can cause abdominal pain and nausea.\n\n7. Gastroparesis: A disorder that can slow down the stomach’s ability to empty, which can result in nausea and vomiting.\n\n8. Liver disease: Damage to the liver, which can cause abdominal pain and nausea.\n\n9. Drug or alcohol use: Intoxication from certain substances can lead to nausea.\n\n10. Infections, such as the flu: Viral respiratory tract infections can cause nausea, along with other symptoms.\n\nBlood tests that may be recommended to diagnose underlying conditions include: \n\n1. Complete blood count (CBC): Used to measure the levels of white blood cells, red blood cells, and platelets. \n\n2. Liver function tests: Used to measure the levels of albumin, bilirubin, and liver enzymes, which can indicate the presence of liver disease. \n\n3. H. pylori test: Used to detect the presence of bacteria that cause ulcers.\n\n4. Comprehensive metabolic panel (CMP): Used to measure organ function, as well as electrolyte and glucose levels.\n\n5. Thyroid test: Used to measure thyroid hormone levels.\n\nIt is important to discuss your symptoms with a healthcare professional to determine the underlying cause of your nausea. Depending on your symptoms and medical history, your doctor may recommend certain blood tests to diagnose the cause of your nausea.'),
(197, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'male', '\n\nVomiting is one of the main indications of a variety of health conditions and illnesses. It is important to discuss vomiting symptoms with a doctor as soon as they arise in order to properly assess the underlying condition and recommend appropriate treatment. The following are some of the potential illnesses associated with vomiting as well as the associated blood tests that should be discussed with a doctor:\n\nHealth Conditions:\nGastroenteritis\nGastroesophageal Reflux Disease \nPeptic Ulcer Disease\nAppendicitis\nGallbladder Disease\nHepatitis\nFood Poisoning\n\nBlood Tests:\nComplete Blood Count \nLiver Function Tests \nRenal/Kidney Function Tests \nElectrolyte Panel \nHepatic Panel \nGastrin and Secretin Test \nFecal Occult Blood Test \nBilirubin Tests'),
(198, '10', 'gufran', '25', 'Male', '\n\nGiven the information that you have provided, it is likely that you are experiencing a virus or infection, such as the flu, a cold, pneumonia, or a gastrointestinal virus. In order to determine the underlying cause of your fever, it is important to speak with a healthcare professional and discuss the possibility of running blood tests. Below are recommended tests which could help evaluate for a potential diagnosis:\n\n• Complete Blood Count (CBC): for an evaluation of red and white blood cells \n• Thyroid-Stimulating Hormone (TSH): to rule out issues with the thyroid \n• Blood Culture: to evalaute for bacteria in the blood \n• Liver Tests: to assess your liver\'s health \n• Electrolytes Test: to evaluate levels of calcium, sodium, potassium, and other minerals in your blood \n• Comprehensive Metabolic Panel (CMP): to measure the levels of various chemicals in the blood \n• Urine Test: for collecting samples of your urinary tract and testing for bacteria or other foreign objects.\n\nBy consulting with a healthcare professional and undergoing these blood tests, you can discover the source of the fever and receive the necessary treatment plan to help you recover.'),
(199, '10', 'gufran', '25', 'Male', '\n\nThe presence of fever for over a day is an indicator of an underlying condition that needs to be addressed. While self-diagnoses and home remedies may help to some extent, it is recommended to consult a medical professional for an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment. Possible health conditions that could be causing the fever include influenza, a viral or bacterial infection, pneumonia, Lyme disease, or a kidney infection. Additionally, some specific tests that should be discussed with a doctor include a complete blood count (CBC) and a blood culture. A CBC will measure the red and white blood cell levels and can indicate an infection. A blood culture is a laboratory test that helps to diagnose bacterial infections. Other tests that should be discussed with a doctor to determine the cause of the fever include a urine culture, a chest X-ray, and a throat swab.'),
(200, '10', 'gufran', '25', 'Male', ' \n\nWith these symptoms on-going for several days, it is critical to receive medical help as soon as possible to accurately diagnose and treat underlying issues. Headache and fever are two of the most common and broadest symptoms and range from a wide array of health conditions such as influenza, meningoencephalitis, stroke, sinus infections, or even something as severe as a brain tumor.  Accordingly, blood tests should be done to pinpoint the exact health concern. \n\nPossible Healthcare Conditions: \n1. Influenza \n2. Meningoencephalitis \n3. Stroke \n4. Sinus Infection \n5. Brain Tumor \n\nBlood Tests:\n1. Complete Blood Count \n2. C-Reactive Protein (CRP): to measure systemic inflammation  \n3. Rheumatoid Factor (RF): to detect autoimmune disorders\n4. Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate (ESR): Helpful in detecting infections or autoimmune-related illnesses\n5. Lactic Dehydrogenase (LDH): Used as a marker of muscle and liver damage\n6. Electrolyte panel: To evaluate body fluids and detect electrolyte imbalances  \n7. Liver Function Panel (LFT): To measure the levels of liver enzymes\n8. Kidney Function Test (KFT): To detect any abnormalities in kidney function \n9. Glucose test: To detect diabetes, insulin resistance or hypoglycemia\n10. Thyroid Function Tests (TFT): To look for any thyroid disorders, such as hypothyroidism \n11. Brain-Specific Enzymes: To detect any inflammation or signs of stroke');
