(201, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nHaving persistent headaches and fever for extended period of time is an indicator of serious health concern and such symptoms should not be ignored. Possible health conditions one could be dealing with, considering the symptoms mentioned, are: \n1. Migraine headaches \n2. Viral infections \n3. Tension headaches\n4. Bacterial sinus infection \n5. Lyme disease \n\nThe blood tests recommended in this case are: \n1. Complete Blood Count (CBC) – to check for infection, low red blood cell count or other disease\n2. Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate (ESR) – to measure how fast red blood cells settle in a test tube; high levels indicate inflammation\n3. C-reactive Protein (CRP) – to measure levels of inflammation in the body\n4. Antinuclear Antibody (ANA) – to detect autoimmune disorders such as lupus or rheumatoid arthritis \n5. Rheumatoid Factor (RF) – to detect and help diagnose rheumatoid arthritis \n6. Lyme Disease Test – to test for antibodies to the bacteria which causes Lyme disease.'),
(202, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nAs the symptoms of fever and vomiting suggested, it is important to be properly diagnosed to identify a possible healthcare condition. There could be several health conditions that may support the fever and vomiting, and it is necessary to make sure the diagnosis is correct. Some of the healthcare conditions that could explain the symptoms are:\n\n1. Influenza: Fever and vomiting could be indicative of the flu. A blood test is important to confirm the diagnosis.\n\n2. Infections: Infections such as urinary tract infection (UTI), gastroenteritis, and pelvic inflammatory diseases can present with fever and vomiting. To diagnose this, a blood test is necessary.\n\n3. Viral infection: Viral infections such as the norovirus and rotavirus can be associated with fever and vomiting. Blood tests such as a complete blood count, urine analysis, and stool cultures are recommended.\n\n4. Pregnancy: If the patient is a female and has have recently had unprotected sex, fever and vomiting could be indicative of an early pregnancy. A pregnancy test is important to confirm this.\n\n5. Kidney or Liver Disease: Fever and vomiting can also present in severe kidney or liver diseases. In both these cases, a biochemical profile of the patient\'s blood is necessary.\n\n6. Side effects of some drugs: Certain medications such as antibiotics can also cause fever and vomiting. Depending on the patient\'s medications, a blood test may be necessary to check for potential drug interactions.\n\nIn conclusion, a range of healthcare conditions can present with fever and vomiting, and the diagnosis is reliant on the patient\'s medical history, medication, and the results of some blood tests. Therefore, it is important to consult a doctor to identify the cause of the symptoms and investigate further if needed.'),
(203, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nWith the above stated symptoms (diarrhea and vomiting) that you are currently experiencing for the last 5 and 3 days respectively, it is important to understand that such conditions could be indicative of certain health issues that must not be ignored. Thus, it is suggested to see a doctor and carry out the tests as required in order to rule out any major illnesses that may be causing the symptoms. Here are a list of diseases and blood tests that may need to be discussed with your physician: \n\n1. Gastroenteritis: It is a common cause of diarrhea and vomiting and can be identified through Infectious Disease Antibody Detection tests.\n\n2. Cholera: It is an infection caused by bacteria and can be diagnosed using microscopic investigations and cultures, as well as a test called the latex agglutination test. \n\n3.Rotavirus Infection: It is a virus associated with diarrhea and vomiting and can be identified through a stool test. \n\n4.Foodborne Illness: It is an infection caused by consuming contaminated food and water and can be diagnosed through PCR (Polymerase Chain Reaction) or Enterotoxigenic E.Coli (ETEC) Tests.\n\n5. Kidney Disease: It is a condition associated with abnormal functioning of the kidneys and can be identified through Urinalysis, Blood Urea Nitrogen (BUN) or Serum Creatinine Tests. \n\n6. Ulcerative Colitis: It is an inflammatory bowel disease that may cause diarrhea and other symptoms. It can be identified through a blood test called a Complete Blood Count (CBC). \n\n7. Celiac Disease: It is a gluten intolerance associated with digestive problems and it can be diagnosed through Serology Tests. \n\nIt is highly recommended to see a physician and undergo proper diagnostic measures to seek medical advice and treatment for the symptoms.'),
(204, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nIt is important to be aware of our body\'s symptoms and to take action as soon as possible, as they may be indicative of serious underlying health issues. Fever and cough are two of the most common and frequent symptoms of many illnesses and conditions. Having these two symptoms for 5 days and 3 days respectively could be indicative of a range of possibilities, and it is important to get checked out by a healthcare professional. Below are a few potential health conditions and accompanying tests that could be discussed with a doctor:\n\n- Upper respiratory tract infection (URTI): A swab and/or viral PCR test, chest X-ray\n- Bronchitis: CXR (Chest X-ray)\n- Influenza: CXR, nasal swab, throat swab\n- Pneumonia: CXR (Chest X-ray)\n- Tuberculosis: Sputum Tests, Chemotherapy (DOTs), CXR\n- Asthma: Lung Function Tests, Allergy Tests \n- Lung cancer: CXR (Chest X-ray), Bronchoscopy, CT Scan, Biopsy'),
(205, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nIt is important to keep track of your symptoms as they can give helpful insight into potential health problems. In this case, the symptoms of fever and abdominal pain could be caused by a variety of health conditions. \n\nThe following list contains potential health conditions associated with fever and abdominal pain, along with the associated blood tests that should be discussed with a doctor:\n\n1. Infectious illness: Tests such as a complete blood count (CBC) and other serum tests, such as liver function tests or a chemistry panel.\n\n2. Gastrointestinal illness: Tests such as a fecal occult blood test and a stool sample.\n\n3. Kidney infection: Tests such as a urinalysis, serum creatinine, and Urine Culture.\n\n4. Meningitis: Tests such as a spinal tap and a blood culture.\n\n5. Urinary tract infection (UTI): Tests such as a urinalysis and urine culture.\n\n6. Appendicitis: Tests such as an abdominal ultrasound and a blood count.'),
(206, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nIt is important to recognize the mentioned symptoms of headaches and hypertension as they may indicate underlying medical issues. Some of the potential health conditions associated with these symptoms are Hypertension, Tension Headache, Stress and Anxiety, Diabetes, Stroke and Migraine.\n\nIt is recommended to speak with your doctor about the following tests:\n\n1. Comprehensive Metabolic Panel: to examine electrolytes, glucose levels, kidney and liver function.\n\n2. C-Reactive Protein: to evaluate inflammation in your body.\n\n3. Full Blood Count: to assess the status of your red and white blood cells.\n\n4. Lipid Panel: to assess cholesterol and triglyceride levels.\n\n5. Blood Pressure: to track blood pressure level.\n\n6. Electrocardiogram (ECG): to check heart rhythm.\n\n7. Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI): to look for any possible brain damage.\n\nBy undergoing all these tests, one can get a better understanding of their condition and proceed with appropriate treatment recommendations.'),
(207, '16', 'Neeraj Rai', '25', 'Male', '\n\nIt is important to identify the symptoms of diseases and health conditions, so that timely remedies can be sought to ensure a speedy recovery. Fever is an important indicator of underlying medical conditions and if it lasts for 5 days, diagnosing the health condition and seeking medical intervention is highly recommended. Here are some possible health care conditions along with the associated tests that might be required for diagnosis:\n\n1. Respiratory Problems: Chest X-Ray, Sputum Culture, Chest CT Scan, Pulmonary Function Test\n\n2. Infectious Disease: Blood Culture, Antibody Test, Antigen Test, Complete Blood Count\n\n3. Autoimmune Disease: Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate, C-Reactive Protein Test\n\n4. Thrombotic Disorders: Prothrombin Time Test, Partial Thromboplastin Time Test\n\n5. Kidney Disease: Blood Urea Nitrogen Test, Uric Acid Test, Creatinine Test, Urinalysis\n\n6. Liver Disease: Albumin Test, Bilirubin Test, Alanine Transaminase Test, Prothrombin Time Test\n\n7. Diabetes: Fasting Blood Sugar Test, Oral Glucose Tolerance Test, Hemoglobin A1C Test\n\nThese are some of the possible healthcare conditions and tests that might be discussed with the doctor to properly diagnose and treat the fever that has been persisting for 5 days.'),
(208, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nGiven the symptoms you described, it is important to consult a doctor to identify the possible healthcare conditions you may be dealing with. For a comprehensive assessment, the doctor may advise ordering certain blood tests.\n\nThe possible healthcare conditions you could be dealing with include:\n\n1. Viral infections such as influenza, common cold, COVID-19, etc.\n\n2. Pneumonia\n\n3. Bronchitis\n\n4. Tuberculosis\n\n5. Asthma\n\n6. Heart-related illnesses\n\n7. Kidney-related illnesses\n\nThe blood tests that you may need to discuss with your doctor are:\n\n1. Complete Blood Count (CBC) \n\n2. C-reactive protein (CRP) \n\n3. Erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) \n\n4. Electrolyte tests such as sodium, potassium, and chloride\n\n5. Creatinine \n\n6. Liver function tests\n\n7. Blood culture \n\n8. Arterial blood gas (ABG) \n\n9. Serology tests such as IgM and IgG antibody tests for the detection of certain infections.'),
(209, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nGiven the prolonged Fever symptom of 7 days, it is important to consult a doctor to accurately diagnose the potential medical condition(s) that may be underlying. As Fever is a common symptom, there may be a variety of conditions that could explain the symptomatology. Moreover, blood tests is frequently recommended by the doctors to ascertain the precise diagnosis. Based on these symptoms, some of the possible healthcare conditions that could be present are as follows: \n\n1. Flu infection: This is one of the most prevalent conditions that leads to Fever lasting for a week or so. A throat and nasal swab may be recommended by the doctor for confirming the diagnosis. \n\n2. Sinus Infection: This condition is caused by a bacterial or fungal infection of the sinuses. A CT scan of the sinuses is usually recommended for diagnosis.\n\n3. Kidney Infection: This is another common cause for Fever lasting for more than 3 days. In such a case, a doctor may advise for a urine analysis, complete blood count (CBC) and blood culture for diagnosis.\n\n4. Typhoid: Typhoid is a bacterial infection caused by Salmonella typhi bacteria. It is characterised by high graded Fever that is persistent for more than a week. A blood test will be required to detect the presence of this bacteria.\n\n5. Malaria: Malaria is another often encountered medical condition in Fever lasting for more than a week. This is generally diagnosed with malaria antigen tests.\n\nTherefore, some of the important investigations to be done in the present case in order to make an accurate diagnosis are: throat and nasal swab to confirm Flu infection, CT scan of sinuses, urine analysis, CBC, blood culture and malaria antigen test. Hence, it is highly advisable to consult a doctor and undertake the relevant tests as soon as possible.'),
(210, '16', 'Neeraj Rai', '25', 'Male', '\n\nHaving Fever and Cough for two days is an alarming sign and one should be aware of the possible health conditions and should seek medical help. Based on these two symptoms, the possible health conditions are: \n\n1. Common cold, \n2. Pneumonia, \n3. Tuberculosis, \n4. Bronchitis,\n5. Asthma,\n6. Influenza.\n\nTo identify the health condition, the suggested blood tests are: \n\n1. Complete Blood Count (CBC) \n2. C-Reactive Protein (CRP)\n3. White Blood Cells count (WBC)\n4. Chest X-ray \n5. Sputum Smear \n6. Lung Function Tests.'),
(211, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\n\nIt is important to recognize the significance of Fever and Vomiting symptoms and take medical help before they turn into a serious health concern. Herein are some of the possible Health conditions one could deal with or the possible blood tests to identify it. \n\n1. Viral Fever: Viral Fever could be the root cause of these high temperature and vomiting symptoms. It is suggestible to get a Blood test done to diagnose it as it detects the agents causing infection.\n\n2. Gastrointestinal Infections:It is possible that one might be suffering from Gastrointestinal Infection, leading to Nausea, Vomiting, Diarrhea and Fever. Endoscopy and Liver Function Test can be done to identify it. \n\n3. Malaria: Malaria being one of the most common mosquito-borne diseases is characterized by Fever, chills, headache and fatigue. A Malaria test can be done to confirm if one is infected. \n\n4. Typhoid: Typhoid is caused by the bacterium Salmonella typhi or Salmonella paratyphi and manifests as high fever, fatigue and abdominal pain. Blood Culture and Widal Test can be suggested to diagnose Typhoid. \n\n5. Dengue Fever: Dengue Fever caused by virus can lead to high Fever, severe headaches, joint pain, rashes and vomiting. Blood Test can be done to diagnose and identify Dengue.\n\n6. Pneumonia: Pneumonia symptoms include high fever, cough with phlegm and shortness of breath. Chest X-Ray can be done to diagnose it. \n\n7. Liver Diseases or HIV/AIDS: These diseases can lead to high fever and vomiting. ELISA Test or Liver Function should be done to diagnose it. \n\nThus, it is important to discuss with a doctor and get the required blood tests to rule out the health condition.'),
(212, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', ' \n\nIt is important to take note of all your symptoms when considering any health conditions. Fever lasting five days is certainly a cause for concern, as it could be indicative of an underlying chronic health condition. Possible conditions to consider include bacterial or viral infections, allergies, or another autoimmune disorder. Similarly, blood tests can help to determine what is causing the fever, and should be discussed with your doctor. Here are some potential conditions along with corresponding blood tests you may want to consider: \n\n1. Bacterial infection: CBC (Complete Blood Count) and C-reactive protein (CRP) are typically used to test for bacterial infection.\n\n2. Viral infection: Antibody testing to survey for infections caused by specific viruses.\n\n3. Environmental allergies: Immunoglobulin E (IgE) testing to detect environmental allergies, such as dust mites and pollen.\n\n4. Autoimmune disorder: Anti-nuclear antibody (ANA) testing to screen for autoimmune disorders, such as lupus, rheumatoid arthritis and multiple sclerosis.'),
(213, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nGiven the duration of your headache, it is important to talk with your doctor about your symptoms to determine the root cause and develop a treatment plan. Some possible health conditions that could explain your symptoms include tension headaches, migraine, cluster headaches, sinus infection, dehydration, meningitis, allergic reaction, and brain tumor. Additionally, some relevant blood tests that your doctor should consider include complete blood count (CBC), erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR), thyroid function tests (TFT), glucose tests, and brain imaging.'),
(214, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nUnderstanding symptoms is important to find the underlying health condition, although it may be difficult to diagnose without a checkup. With your given symptoms, Fever for 3 days and Joint stiffness for 10 days, it is possible that you may have an infection or inflammatory condition from a virus or bacteria. The following illnesses and tests should be discussed with your doctor: \n\n1. Blood Tests – A full blood count, liver and kidney function tests may be required to identify any potential infections. \n\n2. Rheumatoid Arthritis – This is an autoimmune disorder that affects the joints, and can cause fever as well as joint stiffness and pain. \n\n3. Infectious Diseases – Viral illnesses such as the flu, as well as bacterial infections, can cause fever and joint pain. \n\n4. Lupus - A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause inflammation of the joints as well as joint pain and stiffness. \n\n5. Lyme Disease – This is an infection caused by a bacteria carried by ticks, and can cause joint pain and stiffness. \n\nIt is important that you seek medical advice to identify the underlying cause for your symptoms and for proper treatment.'),
(215, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nGiven the information provided, it is essential to get a full diagnostic evaluation from a healthcare professional to accurately identify the underlying cause of the fever. Possible diagnoses that should be explored include infective conditions such as viral or bacterial infections, as well as a number of autoimmune and other medical conditions. \n\nFollowing are the list of health conditions and tests that should be discussed with one’s doctor:\n\n1. Infectious conditions: \n    a. Blood cultures or blood antigen tests to detect specific bacteria, fungi, or viral agents \n    b. Pharyngeal swabs to detect for streptococcus\n    c. Urine tests to detect urinary tract infections \n\n2. Autoimmune diseases:\n    a. C-Reactive Protein Test to measure a protein produced in response to inflammation\n    b. Antinuclear antibody test to detect the presence of autoantibodies \n    c. Complement levels to detect levels of immune system proteins\n\n3. Other conditions: \n    a. Complete Blood Count (CBC) to provide a detailed analysis of red and white blood cells \n    b. Creatinine and Blood Urea Nitrogen (BUN) tests to measure kidney function \n    c. Liver Enzyme Test (ALT) to measure the levels of enzymes produced in the liver \n\nIn conclusion, an accurate diagnosis of an underlying condition, whether infectious, autoimmune, or another condition, is often best determined with a full diagnostic evaluation from a healthcare professional.'),
(216, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nWith the indications provided, it is important to consider a few potential healthcare conditions and the need for further tests to evaluate and understand them. Below are some possible healthcare conditions, along with the corresponding blood tests your doctor may recommend for further evaluation:\n\n1. Anemia: A complete blood count (CBC) may be helpful in evaluating for anemia -- a condition where there is a decrease in red blood cells, leading to fatigue, pale skin, weakness, light-headedness, irregular heart beat, chest pain, shortness of breath, and coldness in hands and feet.\n\n2. Diabetes Mellitus: A fasting plasma glucose test may be helpful in evaluating for diabetes mellitus -- a chronic condition in which there is an increase in blood sugar levels and other associated symptoms, such as frequent urination, increased thirst and hunger, weight loss, and blurry vision.\n\n3. Thyroid Dysfunction: A thyroid function test may be helpful in evaluating for thyroid dysfunction -- a condition in which the thyroxine hormone in not produced in adequate amounts in the body. This can lead to various symptoms like fatigue, dry skin, irregular menstrual periods, increased sensitivity to cold, constipation, and more.\n\n4. Vitamin Deficiencies: A blood test measuring levels of vitamins such as Vitamin A, B6, B12, D, and E may help to evaluate for deficiencies which might be leading to certain symptoms. Deficiencies in vitamins can lead to various effects, such as fatigue, weakness, irritability, and mental confusion. \n\n5. Liver Dysfunction: A liver function test may be helpful in assessing for liver damage or dysfunction, which is caused by various factors like excessive alcohol consumption, obesity, hepatitis, and more. It is important to diagnose early, as it can lead to jaundice, fatigue, dark-colored urine, and more. \n\nIt is also important to discuss with your doctor about other factors which may be contributing to the symptoms -- such as lifestyle, diet, and other environmental factors.'),
(217, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nIt is important to take any kind of health-related symptom seriously and discuss it with your doctor for diagnosis of underlying health condition. The two symptoms - headache and irritability, you are reporting may indicate a wide variety of possible health conditions. Some of the health conditions that cause headache and irritability may be:\n\n- Migraine \n- Anxiety \n- Sinusitis \n- Insomnia \n- Depression \n\nYou should discuss with your doctor to look at the possibility of the above-mentioned health conditions, and ask for the following tests: \n\n- Blood tests such as complete blood count (CBC),  lipid profile, and blood glucose levels \n- Lumbar puncture or spinal tap \n- Neurological tests like EEG and EMG \n- X-ray, CT scan, or MRI of the head \n- Thyroid tests like T3, free T4, and TSH \n- Drug screen \n- Depression or anxiety test \n\nThese tests will help to determine the underlying cause of the symptoms you are having, and the required treatment can be indicated after its diagnosis.'),
(218, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nIt is important to pay close attention to your body and its symptoms, as they can provide insight into any underlying health conditions. With fever being one of the primary symptoms of numerous medical conditions, it is essential to consult with your doctor to determine the cause. Depending on the severity and duration of your fever, the following healthcare conditions could be a possibility: \n\n-Infectious diseases including colds, flu, bacterial or viral pneumonia, meningitis, encephalitis, and urinary tract infections \n-Autoimmune conditions including rheumatoid arthritis, systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), and sarcoidosis \n-Cancer\n-Thyroid issues such as Graves\' disease or Hashimoto\'s thyroiditis\n-Metabolic disorders including diabetes and disorders of lipid metabolism\n\nBased on your symptoms, your doctor may recommend further tests to understand the cause of your fever. Blood tests that can be considered are: \n-Complete Blood Count (CBC)\n-C-Reactive Protein Test \n-Thyroid Stimulating Hormone Test\n-Thyroid Peroxidase Antibodies Test\n-Viral Panel\n-Autoimmune Panel\n-Urinalysis\n-Liver Function Test\n-Kidney Function Test\n-Glucose Test\n-Vitamin D Test \n-Folate Test\n-Ferritin Test \n-Protein Test'),
(219, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nHaving fever and abdominal pain is not an ideal situation and if these symptoms have been persisting for more than a few days, it’s important to contact a healthcare professional to seek medical advice and get tested. While it is difficult to accurately pinpoint a health condition based on the described symptoms without a proper diagnosis, some possible healthcare conditions that could be the root cause of these signs include influenza, urinary tract infection, gastroenteritis, liver or gallbladder problem.\n\nA complete blood count (CBC) test and C-Reactive Protein (CRP) test are both important tests that should be considered in order to detect if the body is in a state of infection or inflammation. CBC test indicates the presence of an infection and CRP helps detect the intensity of inflammation caused in the body due to the existing condition. A renal and liver function tests are other tests required to detect kidney or liver disease or infection. Urine culture test is also recommended to identify any bacteria causing the infection in the urinary tract. Moreover, a chest x-ray might be helpful to detect pneumonia or any other conditions in the chest cavity. Lastly, an ultrasound of the abdominal region may be helpful to detect any infection or inflammation in the abdominal cavity.'),
(220, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nIt is important to pay attention to the symptoms you are having as they can be an indication of underlying health issues. By discussing these symptoms with your doctor, you can ensure your health and well-being. Here are some possible healthcare conditions associated with your symptoms, along with the corresponding blood tests you should discuss with your doctor:\n\n1. Anemia: A complete blood count test is used to diagnose anemia.\n\n2. Diabetes: A fasting blood glucose test is used to diagnose diabetes.\n\n3. Thyroid disorders: A thyroid stimulating hormone test is used to diagnose thyroid disorders.\n\n4. Vitamin deficiency: Vitamin D, B12, and iron levels should be tested to diagnose vitamin deficiencies.\n\n5. Liver disease: A liver function test is used to diagnose liver disease.\n\n6. Vitamin toxicity: A vitamin panel is used to detect any signs of vitamin toxicity.'),
(221, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nIt is important to take any chest pain and shortness of breath seriously, as they can be signs of health problems ranging from mild to serious. Based on the two symptoms that you have reported experiencing, it is important for you to discuss with your doctor possible healthcare conditions which could be causing them. The list of possible healthcare conditions and tests which should be discussed with your medical team may include: \n\n1. Asthma: This is a chronic lung condition which causes shortness of breath and chest tightness. Possible tests include spirometry and x-rays. \n2. Pulmonary embolism: This is a blockage of the pulmonary arteries caused by a blood clot. Possible tests include CT scans and lung scans.\n3. Pneumonia: This is an infection of the lungs which causes inflammation and difficulty with breathing. Possible tests include blood cultures and chest X-rays. \n4. Bronchitis: This is an infection of the airways which can cause chest pain and a cough. Possible tests include blood tests and a sputum sample. \n5. Pleurisy: This is an inflammation of the lining around the lungs which causes pain with breathing. Possible tests include chest X-rays and laboratory tests. \n\nIt is important that you discuss with your doctor any possible healthcare conditions and tests that may be necessary to rule them in or out. Your doctor will be able to determine the best course of action for your symptomatic relief.'),
(222, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nChest pain is a common symptom that can be caused by a variety of health conditions, so it is important to consult with your doctor as soon as possible to determine the underlying cause. Depending on the severity and duration of the pain, it can be indicative of anything from a muscle strain or angina to a heart attack. Your doctor may recommend diagnostic and laboratory tests, such as a physical exam, imagery studies, and blood tests to determine the cause. Here are some possible healthcare conditions and blood tests you should discuss with your doctor:\n\nHealth Conditions: \n1. Angina – a chest pain or discomfort caused when your heart muscle doesn’t get enough oxygen \n2. Pulmonary Embolism – a sudden blockage in one of the pulmonary arteries in your lungs \n3. Pericarditis – inflammation of the thin membrane that surrounds your heart \n4. Aortic Dissection – a tear in the inner layer of the aorta \n5. Myocardial Infarction (Heart Attack) – a life-threatening condition caused by a loss of blood supply to the heart muscle\n\nBlood Tests: \n1. Blood tests to measure levels of fats and proteins or enzymes released into your blood when your heart is damaged \n2. Troponin test – to measure troponin levels in the bloodstream \n3. Electrocardiogram (ECG) – to measure the electrical activity of the heart \n4. Chest X-ray – to look at the structures and organs inside the chest \n5. Stress test – to look for signs of heart damage caused by decreased blood flow to the heart muscle.'),
(223, '17', 'ANSHUMAN SINGH', '35', 'Male', '\n\nIt is important to take any symptoms, particularly when they persist for multiple days, seriously and discuss them with a medical professional. Headache is a common symptom of various healthcare conditions and can indicate the presence of underlying issues. In order to understand what\'s going on and provide appropriate treatment, it is important to take a thorough look at medical history, personal habits, and lifestyle factors prior to undergoing recommended tests. \n\nAlong with a full medical evaluation, the following tests should be considered for those experiencing recurrent headaches:\n\n1. Blood Test: A blood test can help identify anemia, diabetes, infections, and other medical issues.\n\n2. Brain Scan: A CT scan or MRI can be used to detect brain lesions, stroke, tumors, or other abnormalities that could be causing headaches.\n\n3. Spinal Tap: If a spinal tap is necessary, it can help detect signs of infection or inflammatory disorders.\n\n4. Electroencephalogram (EEG): This test helps detect seizures, the presence of tumor, or other abnormalities in the brain’s electrical functions. \n\nPossible healthcare conditions associated with recurrent headaches include: \n\n1. Tension headaches \n2. Cluster headaches \n3. Migraine headaches \n4. Sinus headaches\n5. Brain aneurysm \n6. Brain tumor \n7. Meningitis\n8. Lyme disease \n9. Rebound headaches \n10. Eye Problems \n11. High Blood Pressure \n12. Sleep Disorders \n13. Brain abscess \n14. Anxiety disorders \n15. Depression');
